{"title_page": "Kharagpur\u2013Puri line", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n | box_width   = 28em\n | name        = [[File:Indian_Railways_Suburban_Railway_Logo.svg|50px]] Kharagpur\u2013Puri line<br/>including Cuttack-Paradip line\n | color       = 800000\n | logo        =\n | logo_width  =\n | image       = Train passing through a bridge in cuttack.JPG\n | image_width = 230px\n | caption     = A train passing over a bridge on the Mahanadi at Cuttack\n | type        = \n | system      = \n | status      = Operational\n | locale      = [[Odisha]], [[West Bengal]]\n | start       = [[Kharagpur railway station|Kharagpur]]\n | end         = [[Puri railway station|Puri]]\n | stations    = \n | routes      =\n | daily_ridership   =\n | open        = 1901\n | close       =\n | owner       = [[Indian Railway]]\n | operator    = [[East Coast Railway zone|East Coast Railway]], [[South Eastern Railway zone|South Eastern Railway]]\n | character   =\n | depot       =\n | stock       = \n | linelength  = \n | tracklength = {{convert|407|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n | tracks     = 2\n | gauge       = {{RailGauge|1676mm}} [[Indian gauge|Broad gauge]]\n | old_gauge      =\n | minradius   =\n | racksystem  =\n | electrification          =\n | speed       =  up to {{convert|130|km/h|abbr=on}}\n | elevation   =\n | website     =\n | map         = \n | map_state   = \n}}\n{{ Kharagpur\u2013Puri line|collapse=y}}\nThe '''Kharagpur\u2013Puri line''' is a railway line connecting [[Kharagpur railway station]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[West Bengal]] and [[Puri railway station|Puri]] in [[Odisha]]. The Kharagpur-Khurda Road portion of this line is part of the [[Howrah-Chennai main line]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe Kharagpur\u2013Puri line traverses  the northern part of the [[Eastern Coastal Plains]] crossing such rivers as  [[Subarnarekha River|Subarnarekha]], [[Baitarani River|Baitarani]], [[Brahmani River|Brahmani]] and [[Mahanadi River|Mahanadi]]. The coastal plains lying between the [[Eastern Ghats]] and the [[Bay of Bengal]] are fertile agricultural lands with high density of population. The line enters the large delta of the {{convert|900|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} long  [[Mahanadi River|Mahanadi]],  with a series of channels, near Cuttack.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.kwintessential.co.uk/articles/india/Coastal-Plains-of-India/3029|title = Coastal Plains of India|publisher= Country facts \u2013 the world at your finger tips| accessdate = 2013-01-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.zahie.com/categories/details/social-studies/the-coastal-plains-of-india.html|title = The Coastal Plains of India|publisher= Zahie.com| accessdate = 2013-01-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.geol.lsu.edu/WDD/ASIAN/Mahanadi/mahanadi.htm |title = Mahanadi River Delta, India, Asia|publisher= The World Delta Database| accessdate = 2013-01-17 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Howrah-Chennai main line===\nDuring the period 1893 to 1896, {{convert|1287|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}  of [[East Coast State Railway]] was built and opened to traffic. It necessitated construction of some of the largest bridges across rivers like [[Brahmani River|Brahmani]], [[Kathajodi River|Kathajodi]], Kuakhai and Birupa.  [[Bengal Nagpur Railway]]\u2019s line to Cuttack was fully opened after completion of the bridge over the [[Mahanadi]] in 1901.<ref name=ser>{{cite web  | url = http://www.ser.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1  | title = Major Events in the Formation of S.E. Railway  | publisher = South Eastern Railway  | accessdate = 2013-01-02  | url-status = dead  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130401151628/http://www.ser.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0%2C1  | archive-date = 1 April 2013  | df = dmy-all  }}</ref>\n\nThe {{convert|514|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}  long northern section of the East Coast State Railway was merged with BNR in 1902.<ref>{{cite web | url =  http://www.eastcoastrail.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,261 | title =  History | publisher =  East Coast Railway | accessdate =  2013-01-02 | url-status =  dead | archive-url =  https://web.archive.org/web/20110131114416/http://www.eastcoastrail.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0%2C1%2C261 | archive-date =  31 January 2011 | df =  dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Khurda Road-Puri===\nThe Khurda Road-Puri section was opened to traffic on 1 February 1897.<ref name=ser/>\n\nThe Khurda Road-Puri section  have double lines operation finished in July 2015.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/bhubaneswar/94803-ecors-rs279-cr-plan-for-bhubaneswar-puri.html|title = ECoR\u2019s Rs. 279-cr plan for Bhubaneswar, Puri| publisher=The Pioneer, 16 September 2012| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref>\n\n===Mayurbhanj links===\n\"Work has been begun by the Bengal-Nagpur Railway on the construction of a line from Kalimati to Gurumaishini hill, from which the iron ore is to be obtained.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P10_5B-S9D0C&pg=PA217&lpg=PA217&dq=Mayurbhanj+gazetteer+railway+kalimati&source=bl&ots=0F_PQtrFb6&sig=LKFiR5KwlpqKHIyTglda35CrRpQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZJnmUM-JFYTyrQePgYG4Cg&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Mayurbhanj%20gazetteer%20railway%20kalimati&f=false|title=Bengal District Gazetteers \u2013 Singhbhum, Saraikela and Kharsawan (first published 1910)|last=O\u2019Malley|first=L.S.S.|date=|publisher=Logos Press, Building No. 4788-90, Street No. 23, Ansari Road, Daryaganj, New Delhi-110002|work=page 217|accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref>(Kalimati later became Jamshedpur/Tatanagar). That was the railway's early foray into Mayurbhanj State. (Details of the Tatanagar-Gourmahisani line are available in [[Asansol-Tatanagar-Kharagpur line]].)\n\nHowever, even before that [[Mayurbhanj State Railway]] linked [[Rupsa, India|Rupsa]] on the [[Howrah-Chennai main line]] with [[Baripada railway station|Baripada]] through a narrow gauge line in 1905 and then extended it further.<ref name=Mayurbhanj>{{cite web| url = http://www.indianexpress.com/news/mayurbhanj-state-railway/474611 |title = Mayurbhanj State Railway | last= Singh|first= Vikas|publisher= Express News Service, 11 June 2009| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref> In his \"The East Coast\", Ian Manning has jotted down the experience of his travel in the narrow gauge train.[http://www.irfca.org/articles/manning/rupsa.html ]  The Rupsa-Baripada-Bangriposi line was converted to broad gauge between 1996 and 2006.<ref name=Mayurbhanj/>\n\n===Paradip and other port links===\nThe foundation stone of the Cuttack-Paradip line was laid by Prime Minister [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] on 31 January 1962. It was opened to traffic in 1973.<ref name=ser/>\n\nOpened in 1966, [[Paradip Port]] has laid out plans to expand its cargo handling capacity from 76 million tonnes annually to 237 million tonnes by 2020. The entrance and approach channels are being deepened to handle vessels up to 1,25,000 DWT (slightly smaller than [[capesize]] vessels).<ref>{{cite web| url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/keyword/paradip-port|title = Paradip port in expansion mode|publisher= The Times of India, 4 April 2011 | accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.paradipport.gov.in/| title = Paradip Port Trust| publisher = | accessdate = 2013-01-02| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180224035244/http://paradipport.gov.in/| archive-date = 24 February 2018| url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Dhamra Port]], opened in 2011, has the capacity to handle [[capesize]] vessels up to 1,80,000 DWT. It is linked to Bhadrak with a 62&nbsp;km long railway line. It is a joint venture of [[Larsen & Toubro]] and [[Tata Steel]].<ref>{{cite news| url = http://m.indianexpress.com/story_mobile.php?storyid=889344|title = Finally, Dhamra port commissioned|newspaper= The Indian Express| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://article.wn.com/view/2011/12/18/Dhamra_port_dedicated_to_nation/ |title = Dhamra port dedicated to nation|publisher= Deccan Chronicle, 18 December 2011| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.business-standard.com/india/storypage.php?autono=19348 |title = Singapore Co Gets Odisha Nod for Dhamra Port|publisher= Business Standard, 3 April 1998| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref>\n\nApart from Dhamra, new ports are coming up at [[Kirtania port|Kirtania]] at the mouth of the [[Subarnarekha River|Subarnarekha]], [[Astaranga]] in [[Puri district]] and Chudamani in [[Bhadrak district]]<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2009/12/14/stories/2009121451090500.htm |title = Odisha to become a State of ports |work= | publisher = The Hindu Business Line, 14 December 2009 | accessdate = 2010-04-27 }}</ref> The 41&nbsp;km long newly sanctioned line connecting [[Digha railway station|Digha]] in West Bengal with Jaleswar on the Kharagpur\u2013Puri line is expected to serve the new port at Kirtania.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.ser.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,2,412,753,764| title = Upcoming projects in South Eastern Railway| publisher = South Eastern Railway| accessdate = 2013-01-02| url-status = dead| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130401094258/http://www.ser.indianrailways.gov.in//view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0%2C2%2C412%2C753%2C764| archive-date = 1 April 2013| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Astaranga port will be connected to  Bhubaneswar New Station on the Khurda Road-Puri line.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.odishatoday.com/Business/MoU_signed_for_Greenfield_port_at_Astaranga_231208-45187541797.html|title = MoU signed for Greenfield port at Astaranga|publisher=OdishaToay.com| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref>\n\n===Coalfield and iron ore mines links===\n[[Talcher Coalfield]] with reserves of 38.65 billion tonnes, the highest in India,<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.portal.gsi.gov.in/gsiDoc/pub/IndiaCoalResources2004.pdf | title =Coal Resources of India (As on 1.1.2004) | publisher =Coal Wing, Geological Survey of India, Kolkata | accessdate =2012-11-30 | url-status =dead | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120327022156/http://www.portal.gsi.gov.in/gsiDoc/pub/IndiaCoalResources2004.pdf | archive-date =27 March 2012 | df =dmy-all }}</ref> is located on the [[Cuttack-Sambalpur line]].\n\nThe Barbil-Joda region is the highest iron ore-producing region in the country, with an annual output of around 40 million tonnes of lump and fines.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://business-standard.com/india/news/poor-demand-higher-scrap-import-hit-iron-ore-lump-rates/479428/ |title =Poor demand, higher scrap import hit iron ore lump prices|last= Mohapatra |first= Sadananda| publisher= Business Standard, 5 July 2012| accessdate = 2012-12-10 }}</ref> This region, as well as the Daitari-Kalinganagar mining-industrial region is linked through the Padapahar-Jakhapura and Rajkharsawan-Barbil lines. (See [[Tatanagar-Bilaspur section]] for more information.)\n\n==Electrification==\n[[Chennai Mail|Howrah-Chennai Mail]] was the first train in South Eastern Railway to be hauled by a diesel engine ([[Indian locomotive class WDM-2|WDM-1]]) in 1965.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history4.html |title = IR History: Part - IV (1947 - 1970)| publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref>\n\nThe Howrah-Chennai route was completely electrified by 2005.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history7.html |title = IR History Part VII  (2000-present) | publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref> Electrification was in stages. Hijli-Bakhrabad was electrified in 1998\u201399, Bakhrabad-Jaleswar in 2000\u201301, Jaleswar-Amarda Road in 2001\u201302, Amarda Road-Balasore in 2002\u201303, Balasore-Ranital in 2003\u201304, Bhadrak-Kenduapara in 1998\u201399, Kapilas Road-Rajatgarh in 2003\u201304, Rajatgarh-Barang in 2002\u201303, Barang-Bhubaneswar in 2002\u201303, and Bhubaneswar-Khurda Road in 2001\u201302.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://irfca.org/docs/electrification-history.html|title = History of Electrification| publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref>\n\n==Speed limits==\nThe entire Kharagpur-Visakhapatnam-Vijayawada main line is classified as a \"Group B\" line which can take speeds up to 130&nbsp;km/h. Some of the branch lines such as Talcher-Rajatgarh-Salegaon-Nergundi, Cuttack-Paradeep, Radhakishorepur-Rajathgarh-Barang, Kapilas Road-Salegaon and Radhakishorepur-Machapur are classified as Group 'D Spl' lines. These sections already carry high traffic density or are likely to grow substantially in future. The sanctioned speed limit for such lines is 100&nbsp;km/h.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/codesmanual/IRPWM/PermanentWayManualCh2_data.htm |title = Chapter II \u2013 The Maintenance of Permanent Way|work= |last= |first= | publisher= | accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref>\n\n==Railway reorganization==\nThe [[Bengal Nagpur Railway]] was nationalized in 1944.<ref name=ser/>[[Eastern Railway zone|Eastern Railway]] was formed on 14 April 1952 with the portion of [[East Indian Railway Company]] east of [[Mughalsarai]] and the Bengal Nagpur Railway.<ref name=zones>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-geog.html#newzone |title = Geography \u2013 Railway Zones| publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 2012-11-21 }}</ref> In 1955, [[South Eastern Railway zone|South Eastern Railway]] was carved out of Eastern Railway. It comprised lines mostly operated by BNR earlier.<ref name=zones/><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history4.html |title = IR History: Part - IV (1947 - 1970)| publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 2012-11-21 }}</ref> Amongst the new zones started in April 2003 were [[East Coast Railway Zone|East Coast Railway]]  and [[South East Central Railway Zone|South East Central Railway]]. Both these railways were carved out of South Eastern Railway.<ref name=zones/>\n\n==Passenger movement==\n[[Kharagpur railway station|Kharagpur]], [[Bhubaneswar railway station|Bhubaneswar]], [[Cuttack Railway Station|Cuttack]] and [[Puri railway station|Puri]], on this line, are amongst the top hundred booking stations of Indian Railway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrail.gov.in/7days_Avl.html |title=Indian Railways Passenger Reservation Enquiry |work=Availability in trains for Top 100 Booking Stations of Indian Railways |last= |first= |publisher=IRFCA |accessdate=2012-12-30 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140510115649/http://www.indianrail.gov.in/7days_Avl.html |archive-date=10 May 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{external media\n| align=right\n| video1= [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lvXclgA__sU  Faluknama Express passing over Mahanadi bridge]\n}}\n\n{{Railway lines in Eastern India}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kharagpur - Puri line}}\n[[Category:5 ft 6 in gauge railways in India]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Odisha]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Khurda Road railway division|*]]\n[[Category:Kharagpur railway division|*]]\n[[Category:Transport in Kharagpur]]\n[[Category:Transport in Puri]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n | box_width   = 28em\n | name        = [[File:Indian_Railways_Suburban_Railway_Logo.svg|50px]] Kharagpur\u2013Puri line<br/>including Cuttack-Paradip line\n | color       = 800000\n | logo        =\n | logo_width  =\n | image       = Train passing through a bridge in cuttack.JPG\n | image_width = 230px\n | caption     = A train passing over a bridge on the Mahanadi at Cuttack\n | type        = \n | system      = \n | status      = Operational\n | locale      = [[Odisha]], [[West Bengal]]\n | start       = [[Kharagpur railway station|Kharagpur]]\n | end         = [[Puri railway station|Puri]]\n | stations    = \n | routes      =\n | daily_ridership   =\n | open        = 1901\n | close       =\n | owner       = [[Indian Railway]]\n | operator    = [[East Coast Railway zone|East Coast Railway]], [[South Eastern Railway zone|South Eastern Railway]]\n | character   =\n | depot       =\n | stock       = \n | linelength  = \n | tracklength = {{convert|407|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n | tracks     = 2\n | gauge       = {{RailGauge|1676mm}} [[Indian gauge|Broad gauge]]\n | old_gauge      =\n | minradius   =\n | racksystem  =\n | electrification          =\n | speed       =  up to {{convert|130|km/h|abbr=on}}\n | elevation   =\n | website     =\n | map         = \n | map_state   = \n}}\n{{ Kharagpur\u2013Puri line|collapse=y}}\nThe '''Kharagpur\u2013Puri line''' is a railway line connecting [[Kharagpur railway station]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[West Bengal]] and [[Puri railway station|Puri]] in [[Odisha]]. The Kharagpur-Khurda Road portion of this line is part of the [[Howrah-Chennai main line]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe Kharagpur\u2013Puri line traverses  the northern part of the [[Eastern Coastal Plains]] crossing such rivers as  [[Subarnarekha River|Subarnarekha]], [[Baitarani River|Baitarani]], [[Brahmani River|Brahmani]] and [[Mahanadi River|Mahanadi]]. The coastal plains lying between the [[Eastern Ghats]] and the [[Bay of Bengal]] are fertile agricultural lands with high density of population. The line enters the large delta of the {{convert|900|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} long  [[Mahanadi River|Mahanadi]],  with a series of channels, near Cuttack.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.kwintessential.co.uk/articles/india/Coastal-Plains-of-India/3029|title = Coastal Plains of India|publisher= Country facts \u2013 the world at your finger tips| accessdate = 2013-01-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.zahie.com/categories/details/social-studies/the-coastal-plains-of-india.html|title = The Coastal Plains of India|publisher= Zahie.com| accessdate = 2013-01-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.geol.lsu.edu/WDD/ASIAN/Mahanadi/mahanadi.htm |title = Mahanadi River Delta, India, Asia|publisher= The World Delta Database| accessdate = 2013-01-17 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Howrah-Chennai main line===\nDuring the period 1893 to 1896, {{convert|1287|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}  of [[East Coast State Railway]] was built and opened to traffic. It necessitated construction of some of the largest bridges across rivers like [[Brahmani River|Brahmani]], [[Kathajodi River|Kathajodi]], Kuakhai and Birupa.  [[Bengal Nagpur Railway]]\u2019s line to Cuttack was fully opened after completion of the bridge over the [[Mahanadi]] in 1901.<ref name=ser>{{cite web  | url = http://www.ser.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1  | title = Major Events in the Formation of S.E. Railway  | publisher = South Eastern Railway  | accessdate = 2013-01-02  | url-status = dead  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130401151628/http://www.ser.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0%2C1  | archive-date = 1 April 2013  | df = dmy-all  }}</ref>\n\nThe {{convert|514|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}  long northern section of the East Coast State Railway was merged with BNR in 1902.<ref>{{cite web | url =  http://www.eastcoastrail.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,261 | title =  History | publisher =  East Coast Railway | accessdate =  2013-01-02 | url-status =  dead | archive-url =  https://web.archive.org/web/20110131114416/http://www.eastcoastrail.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0%2C1%2C261 | archive-date =  31 January 2011 | df =  dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Khurda Road-Puri===\nThe Khurda Road-Puri section was opened to traffic on 1 February 1897.<ref name=ser/>\n\nThe Khurda Road-Puri section  have double lines operation finished in July 2015.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/bhubaneswar/94803-ecors-rs279-cr-plan-for-bhubaneswar-puri.html|title = ECoR\u2019s Rs. 279-cr plan for Bhubaneswar, Puri| publisher=The Pioneer, 16 September 2012| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref>\n\n===Mayurbhanj links===\n\"Work has been begun by the Bengal-Nagpur Railway on the construction of a line from Kalimati to Gurumaishini hill, from which the iron ore is to be obtained.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P10_5B-S9D0C&pg=PA217&lpg=PA217&dq=Mayurbhanj+gazetteer+railway+kalimati&source=bl&ots=0F_PQtrFb6&sig=LKFiR5KwlpqKHIyTglda35CrRpQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZJnmUM-JFYTyrQePgYG4Cg&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Mayurbhanj%20gazetteer%20railway%20kalimati&f=false|title=Bengal District Gazetteers \u2013 Singhbhum, Saraikela and Kharsawan (first published 1910)|last=O\u2019Malley|first=L.S.S.|date=|publisher=Logos Press, Building No. 4788-90, Street No. 23, Ansari Road, Daryaganj, New Delhi-110002|work=page 217|accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref>(Kalimati later became Jamshedpur/Tatanagar). That was the railway's early foray into Mayurbhanj State. (Details of the Tatanagar-Gourmahisani line are available in [[Asansol-Tatanagar-Kharagpur line]].)\n\nHowever, even before that [[Mayurbhanj State Railway]] linked [[Rupsa, India|Rupsa]] on the [[Howrah-Chennai main line]] with [[Baripada railway station|Baripada]] through a narrow gauge line in 1905 and then extended it further.<ref name=Mayurbhanj>{{cite web| url = http://www.indianexpress.com/news/mayurbhanj-state-railway/474611 |title = Mayurbhanj State Railway | last= Singh|first= Vikas|publisher= Express News Service, 11 June 2009| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref> In his \"The East Coast\", Ian Manning has jotted down the experience of his travel in the narrow gauge train.[http://www.irfca.org/articles/manning/rupsa.html ]  The Rupsa-Baripada-Bangriposi line was converted to broad gauge between 1996 and 2006.<ref name=Mayurbhanj/>\n\n===Paradip and other port links===\nThe foundation stone of the Cuttack-Paradip line was laid by Prime Minister [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] on 31 January 1962. It was opened to traffic in 1973.<ref name=ser/>\n\nOpened in 1966, [[Paradip Port]] has laid out plans to expand its cargo handling capacity from 76 million tonnes annually to 237 million tonnes by 2020. The entrance and approach channels are being deepened to handle vessels up to 1,25,000 DWT (slightly smaller than [[capesize]] vessels).<ref>{{cite web| url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/keyword/paradip-port|title = Paradip port in expansion mode|publisher= The Times of India, 4 April 2011 | accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.paradipport.gov.in/| title = Paradip Port Trust| publisher = | accessdate = 2013-01-02| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180224035244/http://paradipport.gov.in/| archive-date = 24 February 2018| url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Dhamra Port]], opened in 2011, has the capacity to handle [[capesize]] vessels up to 1,80,000 DWT. It is linked to Bhadrak with a 62&nbsp;km long railway line. It is a joint venture of [[Larsen & Toubro]] and [[Tata Steel]].<ref>{{cite news| url = http://m.indianexpress.com/story_mobile.php?storyid=889344|title = Finally, Dhamra port commissioned|newspaper= The Indian Express| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://article.wn.com/view/2011/12/18/Dhamra_port_dedicated_to_nation/ |title = Dhamra port dedicated to nation|publisher= Deccan Chronicle, 18 December 2011| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.business-standard.com/india/storypage.php?autono=19348 |title = Singapore Co Gets Odisha Nod for Dhamra Port|publisher= Business Standard, 3 April 1998| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref>\n\nApart from Dhamra, new ports are coming up at [[Kirtania port|Kirtania]] at the mouth of the [[Subarnarekha River|Subarnarekha]], [[Astaranga]] in [[Puri district]] and Chudamani in [[Bhadrak district]]<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2009/12/14/stories/2009121451090500.htm |title = Odisha to become a State of ports |work= | publisher = The Hindu Business Line, 14 December 2009 | accessdate = 2010-04-27 }}</ref> The 41&nbsp;km long newly sanctioned line connecting [[Digha railway station|Digha]] in West Bengal with Jaleswar on the Kharagpur\u2013Puri line is expected to serve the new port at Kirtania.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.ser.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,2,412,753,764| title = Upcoming projects in South Eastern Railway| publisher = South Eastern Railway| accessdate = 2013-01-02| url-status = dead| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130401094258/http://www.ser.indianrailways.gov.in//view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0%2C2%2C412%2C753%2C764| archive-date = 1 April 2013| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Astaranga port will be connected to  Bhubaneswar New Station on the Khurda Road-Puri line.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.odishatoday.com/Business/MoU_signed_for_Greenfield_port_at_Astaranga_231208-45187541797.html|title = MoU signed for Greenfield port at Astaranga|publisher=OdishaToay.com| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref>\n\n===Coalfield and iron ore mines links===\n[[Talcher Coalfield]] with reserves of 38.65 billion tonnes, the highest in India,<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.portal.gsi.gov.in/gsiDoc/pub/IndiaCoalResources2004.pdf | title =Coal Resources of India (As on 1.1.2004) | publisher =Coal Wing, Geological Survey of India, Kolkata | accessdate =2012-11-30 | url-status =dead | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120327022156/http://www.portal.gsi.gov.in/gsiDoc/pub/IndiaCoalResources2004.pdf | archive-date =27 March 2012 | df =dmy-all }}</ref> is located on the [[Cuttack-Sambalpur line]].\n\nThe Barbil-Joda region is the highest iron ore-producing region in the country, with an annual output of around 40 million tonnes of lump and fines.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://business-standard.com/india/news/poor-demand-higher-scrap-import-hit-iron-ore-lump-rates/479428/ |title =Poor demand, higher scrap import hit iron ore lump prices|last= Mohapatra |first= Sadananda| publisher= Business Standard, 5 July 2012| accessdate = 2012-12-10 }}</ref> This region, as well as the Daitari-Kalinganagar mining-industrial region is linked through the Padapahar-Jakhapura and Rajkharsawan-Barbil lines. (See [[Tatanagar-Bilaspur section]] for more information.)\n\n==Electrification==\n[[Chennai Mail|Howrah-Chennai Mail]] was the first train in South Eastern Railway to be hauled by a diesel engine ([[Indian locomotive class WDM-2|WDM-1]]) in 1965.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history4.html |title = IR History: Part - IV (1947 - 1970)| publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref>\n\nThe Howrah-Chennai route was completely electrified by 2005.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history7.html |title = IR History Part VII  (2000-present) | publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref> Electrification was in stages. Hijli-Bakhrabad was electrified in 1998-99, Bakhrabad-Jaleswar in 2000-01, Jaleswar-Amarda Road in 2001-02, Amarda Road-Balasore in 2002-03, Balasore-Ranital in 2003-04, Bhadrak-Kenduapara in 1998-99, Kapilas Road-Rajatgarh in 2003-04, Rajatgarh-Barang in 2002-03, Barang-Bhubaneswar in 2002-03, and Bhubaneswar-Khurda Road in 2001-02.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://irfca.org/docs/electrification-history.html|title = History of Electrification| publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref>\n\n==Speed limits==\nThe entire Kharagpur-Visakhapatnam-Vijayawada main line is classified as a \"Group B\" line which can take speeds up to 130&nbsp;km/h. Some of the branch lines such as Talcher-Rajatgarh-Salegaon-Nergundi, Cuttack-Paradeep, Radhakishorepur-Rajathgarh-Barang, Kapilas Road-Salegaon and Radhakishorepur-Machapur are classified as Group 'D Spl' lines. These sections already carry high traffic density or are likely to grow substantially in future. The sanctioned speed limit for such lines is 100&nbsp;km/h.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/uploads/codesmanual/IRPWM/PermanentWayManualCh2_data.htm |title = Chapter II \u2013 The Maintenance of Permanent Way|work= |last= |first= | publisher= | accessdate = 2013-01-02 }}</ref>\n\n==Railway reorganization==\nThe [[Bengal Nagpur Railway]] was nationalized in 1944.<ref name=ser/>[[Eastern Railway zone|Eastern Railway]] was formed on 14 April 1952 with the portion of [[East Indian Railway Company]] east of [[Mughalsarai]] and the Bengal Nagpur Railway.<ref name=zones>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-geog.html#newzone |title = Geography \u2013 Railway Zones| publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 2012-11-21 }}</ref> In 1955, [[South Eastern Railway zone|South Eastern Railway]] was carved out of Eastern Railway. It comprised lines mostly operated by BNR earlier.<ref name=zones/><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history4.html |title = IR History: Part - IV (1947 - 1970)| publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 2012-11-21 }}</ref> Amongst the new zones started in April 2003 were [[East Coast Railway Zone|East Coast Railway]]  and [[South East Central Railway Zone|South East Central Railway]]. Both these railways were carved out of South Eastern Railway.<ref name=zones/>\n\n==Passenger movement==\n[[Kharagpur railway station|Kharagpur]], [[Bhubaneswar railway station|Bhubaneswar]], [[Cuttack Railway Station|Cuttack]] and [[Puri railway station|Puri]], on this line, are amongst the top hundred booking stations of Indian Railway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrail.gov.in/7days_Avl.html |title=Indian Railways Passenger Reservation Enquiry |work=Availability in trains for Top 100 Booking Stations of Indian Railways |last= |first= |publisher=IRFCA |accessdate=2012-12-30 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140510115649/http://www.indianrail.gov.in/7days_Avl.html |archive-date=10 May 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{external media\n| align=right\n| video1= [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lvXclgA__sU  Faluknama Express passing over Mahanadi bridge]\n}}\n\n{{Railway lines in Eastern India}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kharagpur - Puri line}}\n[[Category:5 ft 6 in gauge railways in India]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Odisha]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Khurda Road railway division|*]]\n[[Category:Kharagpur railway division|*]]\n[[Category:Transport in Kharagpur]]\n[[Category:Transport in Puri]]\n", "name_user": "Lakun.patra", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eElectrification:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1998-99 \u2192 1998\u201399 (10)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kharagpur%E2%80%93Puri_line"}
{"title_page": "Kempegowda International Airport", "text_new": "{{short description|International airport in Bangalore, India}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Kempegowda International Airport\n| image = kempegowda-international-airport - logo.png\n| image-width = 150\n| image2 =Kempegowda-International-Airport-BLR.jpg\n| image2-width = 250\n| caption = \n| IATA = BLR\n| ICAO = VOBL\n| coordinates = {{coord|13|12|25|N|077|42|15|E|region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = India Karnataka#India#South Asia#Middle East#Asia\n| pushpin_label = '''BLR'''/VOBL\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location In [[Devanahalli]] , [[Karnataka]] , [[India]]\n| type = Public\n| owner = {{ubl|[[Fairfax Financial|Fairfax India Holdings\nCorp]] <small>(54%)</small>|[[Siemens Financial Services|Siemens Project Ventures GmbH]] <small>(20%)</small>|[[Airports Authority of India]] <small>(13%)</small>|Karnataka State Industrial and Infrastructure Development Corporation <small>(13%)</small><ref>{{cite web |title=Prem Watsa's Fairfax now owns Bengaluru Airport \u2013 Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/prem-watsas-fairfax-now-owns-bengaluru-airport/articleshow/63547437.cms |website=The Times of India |accessdate=20 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508231430/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/prem-watsas-fairfax-now-owns-bengaluru-airport/articleshow/63547437.cms |archive-date=8 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n| operator = Bengaluru International Airport Limited (BIAL)\n| city-served = [[Bangalore]]\n| location = [[Devanahalli]], [[Karnataka]], India\n| opened = 24 May 2008\n| hub = <div>\n* [[AirAsia India]]\n* [[Alliance Air (India)|Alliance Air]]\n* [[IndiGo]]\n* [[Go Air]]\n* [[Ghodawat Aviation|Star Air]]\n</div>\n| focus_city = <div>\n* [[Air India]]\n* [[SpiceJet]]\n</div>\n| elevation-f = 3,002\n| elevation-m = 915\n<!--|coordinates = {{Coord|13|11|56|N|077|42|20|E|type:airport_region:IN-KA|display=inline,title|name=Kempegowda International Airport}}-->| website = {{URL|http://www.bengaluruairport.com/}}\n| metric-elev = Y\n| metric-rwy = Y\n| r1-number = 09L/27R\n| r1-length-f = 13,123\n| r1-length-m = 4,000\n| r1-surface = [[Asphalt]]\n| r2-number = 09R/27L\n| r2-length-f = 13123\n| r2-length-m = 4,000\n| r2-surface = [[Asphalt]]\n| stat-year = April 2018 \u2013 March 2019\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 33,300,702 ({{increase}}23.8%)\n| stat2-header = Aircraft movements\n| stat2-data = 2,39,395 ({{increase}}23.8%)\n| stat3-header = Cargo tonnage\n| stat3-data = 3,86,849 ({{increase}}11%)\n| footnotes = Source [[Airport Authority of India|AAI]]<ref name=\"traffic_stats1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aai.aero/sites/default/files/traffic-news/Mar2K19Annex3.pdf|title=Traffic News for the month of March 2019: Annexure-III|work=[[Airports Authority of India]]|date=1 May 2019|accessdate=1 May 2019|page=3}}</ref><ref name=\"traffic_stats2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aai.aero/sites/default/files/traffic-news/Mar2K19Annex2.pdf|title=Traffic News for the month of March 2019: Annexure-II|work=[[Airports Authority of India]]|date=1 May 2019|accessdate=1 May 2019|page=3|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501224637/https://www.aai.aero/sites/default/files/traffic-news/Mar2k18annex2.pdf|archive-date=1 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"traffic_stats3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aai.aero/sites/default/files/traffic-news/Mar2k18annex4.pdf|title=Traffic News for the month of March 2018: Annexure-IV|work=[[Airports Authority of India]]|date=1 May 2018|accessdate=1 May 2018|page=3|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501224509/https://www.aai.aero/sites/default/files/traffic-news/Mar2k18annex4.pdf|archive-date=1 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Kempegowda International Airport''' {{airport codes|BLR|VOBL}} is an [[international airport]] serving [[Bangalore]], the capital of the Indian state of [[Karnataka]]. Spread over {{convert|4000|acre}}, it is located about {{convert|40|km}} north of the city near the village of [[Devanahalli]]. It is owned and operated by Bengaluru International Airport Limited (BIAL), a [[public\u2013private partnership|public\u2013private consortium]]. The airport opened in May 2008 as an alternative to increased congestion at [[HAL Airport]], the original primary commercial airport serving the city. It is named after [[Kempe Gowda I]], the founder of Bangalore. Kempegowda International Airport became Karnataka's first fully [[solar power]]ed airport developed by CleanMax Solar.<ref>{{cite news|title=CleanMax Solar to power Chennai Metro \u2013 Times of India|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/cleanmax-solar-to-power-chennai-metro/articleshow/59285311.cms|work=The Times of India|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927041952/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/cleanmax-solar-to-power-chennai-metro/articleshow/59285311.cms|archivedate=27 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kempegowda International Airport|url=https://cleanmaxsolar.com/pdf/BIAL-case-study.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922194708/https://cleanmaxsolar.com/pdf/BIAL-case-study.pdf|archivedate=22 September 2017|access-date=19 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nKempegowda Airport is the [[List of busiest airports in India by passenger traffic|third-busiest airport by passenger traffic]] in the country, behind the airports in [[Indira Gandhi International Airport|Delhi]] and [[Chatrapati Shivaji International Airport|Mumbai]], and is the [[List of the busiest airports in Asia|29th busiest airport in Asia]]. It handled around 33.30 million passengers in the calendar year 2018 with 658 aircraft movements a day. The cargo handled by the airport continues to increase steadily, with the airport handling about {{convert|386849|t|ST}} of cargo between April 2018 and March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aai.aero/sites/default/files/traffic-news/Mar2k18annex4.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501224509/https://www.aai.aero/sites/default/files/traffic-news/Mar2k18annex4.pdf |archivedate=1 May 2018 |title=Wayback Machine |accessdate=20 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe airport consists of two runways and a passenger terminal, which handles both domestic and international operations. The second runway, constructed by [[Larsen & Toubro]], was commissioned on 6 December 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/lt-bags-bengaluru-airport-contract-to-build-terminal-two/articleshow/66054706.cms?from=mdr|newspaper=Economic Times|title=L&T bags Bengaluru airport contract to build terminal two |date=3 October 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=First flight takes off from second runway at Bengaluru airport |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/first-flight-takes-off-from-second-runway-at-bengaluru-airport/article30219423.ece |accessdate=9 December 2019 |work=The Hindu |date=6 December 2019 |language=en-IN}}</ref> A second terminal is in the early stages of construction. Also, there is a cargo village and three cargo terminals. The airport serves as a hub for [[AirAsia India]], [[Alliance Air (India)|Alliance Air]], and [[IndiGo]] and is a focus city for [[Air India]] and [[SpiceJet]].\n\n== History ==\n===Planning (1991\u20132004)===\nThe original airport serving Bangalore was [[HAL Bangalore Airport|HAL Airport]], located {{convert|10|km}} from the city centre. However, as Bangalore grew into the [[Silicon Valley of India]] and passenger traffic to the city rose, the airport was unable to cope.<ref name=\"at\">{{cite web|url=http://www.airport-technology.com/projects/bangalore/|title=Bangalore International Airport, India|website=Airport Technology|access-date=9 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315203449/http://www.airport-technology.com/projects/bangalore/|archivedate=15 March 2016}}</ref> There was no room for expansion and the [[airport apron]] could only park six aircraft.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2005/10/31/stories/2005103117400400.htm|title=Hard times ahead for city airport authorities|date=31 October 2005|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403153630/http://www.thehindu.com/2005/10/31/stories/2005103117400400.htm |archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref> In March 1991, former chairman of the [[Airports Authority of India#History|National Airports Authority of India]] (NAAI) S. Ramanathan convened a panel to select the site for a new airport. The panel decided on [[Devanahalli]], a village about {{convert|40|km}} north of Bangalore.<ref name=\"groundedbypolitics\">{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/wranglings-between-the-centre-and-karnataka-puts-proposed-devanahalli-airport-in-limbo/1/276255.html|title=Grounded by politics|last=David|first=Stephen|date=31 January 1997|work=[[India Today]]|access-date=30 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403153833/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/wranglings-between-the-centre-and-karnataka-puts-proposed-devanahalli-airport-in-limbo/1/276255.html |archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.digitaltoday.in/indiatoday/20051107/cover2.html|title=Cover Story: Bangalore|date=7 November 2005 |work=[[India Today]]|access-date=30 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091001005146/http://archives.digitaltoday.in/indiatoday/20051107/cover2.html|archive-date=1 October 2009}}</ref> The [[Government of Karnataka|State Government]] made a proposal to build the airport with private assistance, which the [[Government of India|Union Government]] approved in 1994.<ref name=\"govt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.idd.kar.nic.in/bail.htm|title=Airport Projects: Bangalore International Airport|website=Infrastructure Development Department, Government of Karnataka|access-date=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310133412/http://www.idd.kar.nic.in/bail.htm|archive-date=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1995, a consortium consisting of [[Tata Group]], [[Raytheon]] and [[Singapore Changi Airport]] signed a [[memorandum of understanding]] with the State Government regarding participation in the project. In June 1998, however, the consortium announced it was pulling out of the project due to delays in government approval. These included disputes over the location of the airport and the fate of HAL Airport.<ref name=\"groundedbypolitics\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/tripped-by-politics-tata-group-airline-project-falls-apart/1/264643.html|title=This flight is delayed|last=Chakravarti|first=Sudeep|date=20 July 1998|work=[[India Today]]|access-date=30 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403154129/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/tripped-by-politics-tata-group-airline-project-falls-apart/1/264643.html|archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1999, the [[Airports Authority of India]] (AAI) and the Karnataka State Industrial and Infrastructure Development Corporation (KSIIDC) of the State Government signed a memorandum of understanding regarding the nature of the project. It would be a [[public\u2013private partnership]], with AAI and KSIIDC having a 26% share and private companies having the remaining 74%.<ref name=\"govt\"/> In January 2001, the State Government created the company Bengaluru International Airport Limited (BIAL) as a [[special purpose entity]] and began searching for partners.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2001/01/10/stories/1410043z.htm |title=Hunt for Devanahalli airport partners begins|last=D. S.|first=Madhumathi|date=9 January 2001|newspaper=[[The Hindu Business Line]]|access-date=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403154257/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2001/01/10/stories/1410043z.htm|archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref> By November, the project had attracted [[Z\u00fcrich Airport|Unique Z\u00fcrich Airport]], [[Siemens Project Ventures]] and [[Larsen & Toubro]].<ref name=\"pp\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2001/nov/01siemen.htm |title=Siemens team wins bid to build international airport in Bangalore: Reuters|date=1 November 2001|work=[[Rediff]]|access-date=22 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024213153/http://www.rediff.com/money/2001/nov/01siemen.htm|archive-date=24 October 2012}}</ref> Construction was expected to begin in October 2002;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2005/05/07/stories/2005050709660500.htm |title=Devanahalli airport work has begun|date=7 May 2005|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=9 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403154427/http://www.thehindu.com/2005/05/07/stories/2005050709660500.htm |archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref> however, governmental delays persisted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Opinion/UlZNfeC5zHuAMc2rWN3eIK/Grounded-at-the-word-go.html|title=Grounded at the word go|last=Ramanathan|first=Ramesh|date=11 February 2008|newspaper=[[Live Mint]]|access-date=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310220155/http://www.livemint.com/Opinion/UlZNfeC5zHuAMc2rWN3eIK/Grounded-at-the-word-go.html|archive-date=10 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2004/03/19/stories/2004031901131700.htm|title=Ministry clears Bangalore airport project \u2013 BIAL seeks review of draft version of concession pact|last=D. S. |first=Madhumathi|date=18 March 2004|newspaper=[[The Hindu Business Line]]|access-date=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050913114523/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2004/03/19/stories/2004031901131700.htm|archive-date=13 September 2005}}</ref> The [[concession (contract)|concession agreement]] between the State Government, the Union Government and BIAL was signed in July 2004.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2004/07/06/stories/2004070606800600.htm|title=Concession agreement for airport signed |date=5 July 2004|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050216222735/http://www.thehindu.com/2004/07/06/stories/2004070606800600.htm|archive-date=16 February 2005}}</ref> In it, BIAL required the closure of HAL Airport.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2004/06/16/stories/2004061615330100.htm |title=All clear now for new Bangalore airport|date=15 June 2004|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=30 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403154641/http://www.thehindu.com/2004/06/16/stories/2004061615330100.htm |archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Construction and opening (2005\u20132008)===\nConstruction finally commenced on 2 July 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-logistics/bangalore-airport-work-to-begin-on-july-2/article2181575.ece|title=Bangalore airport work to begin on July 2|date=27 June 2005 |newspaper=[[The Hindu Business Line]]|access-date=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403154706/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-logistics/bangalore-airport-work-to-begin-on-july-2/article2181575.ece|archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref> When a study predicted the airport would receive 6.7 million passengers in 2008, the airport was redesigned from its initial capacity of 4.5 million passengers to 11 million,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oneindia.com/2006/07/27/siemens-bags-another-order-for-bangalore-airport-1154007595.html|title=Siemens bags another order for Bangalore airport|date=27 July 2006|work=Oneindia |access-date=10 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410031214/http://www.oneindia.com/2006/07/27/siemens-bags-another-order-for-bangalore-airport-1154007595.html|archive-date=10 April 2016}}</ref> with the terminal size expanded and the number of aircraft stands increased. The cost of the airport rose to {{INRConvert|1930|c}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/bial-plans-rail-link-between-devanahalli-airport-and-city/article3136264.ece|title=BIAL plans rail link between Devanahalli airport and city|date=21 May 2006|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=10 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410031322/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/bial-plans-rail-link-between-devanahalli-airport-and-city/article3136264.ece |archive-date=10 April 2016}}</ref> Construction was completed in 32 months, and BIAL set the launch date for 30 March 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-logistics/bangalore-international-airport-launch-set-for-march-30/article1672728.ece|title=Bangalore international airport launch set for March 30|last=D. S.|first=Madhumathi|date=23 October 2007 |newspaper=[[The Hindu Business Line]]|access-date=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403154757/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-logistics/bangalore-international-airport-launch-set-for-march-30/article1672728.ece |archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref> However, due to delays in establishing [[air traffic control]] services at the airport, the launch date was pushed to 11 May<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oneindia.com/2008/03/13/bial-relents-sets-may-11-as-new-date-for-airport-opening-1205422348.html|title=BIAL relents, sets May 11 as new date for airport opening|date=13 March 2008|work=Oneindia|access-date=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310135237/http://www.oneindia.com/2008/03/13/bial-relents-sets-may-11-as-new-date-for-airport-opening-1205422348.html |archive-date=10 March 2016}}</ref> and finally 24 May 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mydigitalfc.com/2008/bengaluru-airport-wait-gets-longer|title=Bengaluru airport wait gets longer|last=Urvashi |first=Jha|date=2008|website=mydigitalfc.com|access-date=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403154925/http://www.mydigitalfc.com/2008/bengaluru-airport-wait-gets-longer|archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs the opening date for the airport approached, public criticism arose, mainly directed toward the closure of HAL Airport. In March 2008, AAI employees conducted a massive strike against the closure of HAL Airport along with [[Begumpet Airport]] in Hyderabad, fearing they would lose their jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/asia/india/slow-take-off-for-airport-stir-1.91196|title=Slow take-off for airport stir|date=13 March 2008|work=Gulf News|access-date=30 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304105007/http://gulfnews.com/news/asia/india/slow-take-off-for-airport-stir-1.91196|archive-date=4 March 2016}}</ref> The Bangalore City Connect Foundation, a group of citizens and businessmen, staged a rally in mid-May, claiming the new airport was too small for the latest demand projections.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/jMGy6T5cnMis3F87KFkqOM/Citizen8217s-body-protests-closure-of-old-Bangalore-airpo.html|title=Citizen's body protests closure of old Bangalore airport|last=Raghu|first=K.|date=17 May 2008|newspaper=[[Live Mint]]|access-date=30 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403155052/http://www.livemint.com/Politics/jMGy6T5cnMis3F87KFkqOM/Citizen8217s-body-protests-closure-of-old-Bangalore-airpo.html|archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7405287.stm|title=Battle over new Bangalore airport|last=Vaswani|first=Karishma|date=16 May 2008|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=30 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521042652/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7405287.stm|archive-date=21 May 2008}}</ref> On 23 May, a hearing was held at the [[Karnataka High Court]] over poor connectivity between the city and the airport. Ultimately, the State Government decided to go ahead with inaugurating the new airport and closing HAL Airport.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2008/may/23airport1.htm|title=Decks cleared for new Bangalore airport|last=Nanjappa|first=Vicky|date=23 May 2008|work=[[Rediff]]|access-date=30 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924132902/http://www.rediff.com/money/2008/may/23airport1.htm|archive-date=24 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe first flight to the airport, [[Air India]] Flight 609 from [[Mumbai]], was allowed to land the previous night as it would be continuing to [[Singapore]] shortly after midnight. The aircraft touched down at 10:40 pm on 23 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2008/may/24airport.htm|title=Bangalore airport takes wings|last=Nanjappa|first=Vicky|date=24 May 2008|work=[[Rediff]]|access-date=9 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080920100513/http://www.rediff.com/money/2008/may/24airport.htm|archive-date=20 September 2008}}</ref> The airport became the third [[greenfield project|greenfield airport]] under a public\u2013private partnership to open in India, after [[Rajiv Gandhi International Airport]] in Hyderabad and [[Cochin International Airport]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://centreforaviation.com/analysis/indias-airport-sector-vibrant-with-tenders-for-six-ppp-concessions-capa-mumbai-summit-34-feb-205433|title=India's airport sector vibrant, with tenders for six PPP concessions: CAPA Mumbai Summit, 3/4 Feb |date=20 January 2015|work=CAPA \u2013 Centre for Aviation|access-date=9 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415144041/http://centreforaviation.com/analysis/indias-airport-sector-vibrant-with-tenders-for-six-ppp-concessions-capa-mumbai-summit-34-feb-205433|archive-date=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Renaming and expansion (2009\u2013Present)===\nThe original name of the airport was Bangalore International Airport.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.anna.aero/2008/05/16/bangalores-new-airport-almost-ready-for-action/|title=Bangalore's new airport almost ready for use|date=16 May 2008|work=anna.aero|access-date=30 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730085521/http://www.anna.aero/2008/05/16/bangalores-new-airport-almost-ready-for-action|archive-date=30 July 2010}}</ref> In February 2009, the State Government sent a proposal to the Union Government to rename the airport after the founder of Bangalore, [[Kempe Gowda I]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Karnataka-govt-proposes-renaming-Bengaluru-International-Airport/articleshow/4201639.cms |title=Karnataka govt proposes renaming Bengaluru International Airport |date=27 February 2009 |newspaper=[[Times of India]] |access-date=14 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403155611/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Karnataka-govt-proposes-renaming-Bengaluru-International-Airport/articleshow/4201639.cms |archive-date= 3 April 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> When no action was taken, the State Government passed a resolution for the name change in December 2011.<ref name=\"bizstandard\">{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/bangalore-airport-named-after-city-founder-kempe-gowda-113071701013_1.html|title=Bangalore airport named after city founder Kempe Gowda|date=17 July 2013|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|access-date=14 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305035047/http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/bangalore-airport-named-after-city-founder-kempe-gowda-113071701013_1.html |archive-date=5 March 2016}}</ref> The Union Government accepted the proposal in 2012<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-04-06/news/31300330_1_kempegowda-bengaluru-international-airport-centre|title=Centre accepts proposal to name Bengaluru International Airport after Kempegowda|date=6 April 2012|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=14 March 2016|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130126135053/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-04-06/news/31300330_1_kempegowda-bengaluru-international-airport-centre|archive-date=26 January 2013}}</ref> and formally approved it in July 2013.<ref name=\"bizstandard\"/> The airport was officially renamed Kempegowda International Airport on 14 December 2013 amid the inauguration of the expanded terminal building.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-11-24/news/44412735_1_kempegowda-international-airport-december-14-bial|title=Bangalore International Airport Ltd will be Kempegowda International Airport from December 14 |date=24 November 2013|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=14 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315113811/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-11-24/news/44412735_1_kempegowda-international-airport-december-14-bial|archive-date=15 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Kingfisher Airlines]] once operated a [[airline hub|hub]] and was one of the largest airlines at Kempegowda Airport. Following its collapse in October 2012, other airlines stepped in to fill the gap in domestic connectivity by adding more flights.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/bangalore-airport-looks-to-woo-domestic-airlines-to-set-up-hub/1140732/|title=Bangalore Airport looks to woo domestic airlines to set up hub|last=Sukumaran|first=Ajay|date=12 July 2013|newspaper=[[Indian Express]]|access-date=31 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403155910/http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/bangalore-airport-looks-to-woo-domestic-airlines-to-set-up-hub/1140732/|archivedate=3 April 2016}}</ref> In addition, [[Air Pegasus]] and [[AirAsia India]] launched hub operations at the airport in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Air-Pegasus-3rd-airline-to-take-off-from-Bangalore/articleshow/29125947.cms |title=Air Pegasus 3rd airline to take off from Bangalore |last=Dhamija |first=Anshul |last2=Kurian |first2=Boby |date=21 January 2014 |newspaper=[[Times of India]] |access-date=31 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121184804/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Air-Pegasus-3rd-airline-to-take-off-from-Bangalore/articleshow/29125947.cms |archive-date=21 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/airasia-launches-india-ops-from-bangalore/article6107551.ece|title=AirAsia launches India ops from Bangalore|date=12 June 2014|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=31 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105155306/http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/airasia-launches-india-ops-from-bangalore/article6107551.ece|archive-date=5 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe first phase of expansion was launched in June 2011 and finished in December 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/bangalore/report-work-on-bangalore-international-airport-expansion-set-to-begin-in-june-1546798|title=Work on Bangalore International Airport expansion set to begin in June|date=24 May 2011|newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|access-date=12 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403161430/http://www.dnaindia.com/bangalore/report-work-on-bangalore-international-airport-expansion-set-to-begin-in-june-1546798|archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"deccan122013\">{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/131215/news-current-affairs/article/new-terminal-inaugurated-airport|title=New terminal inaugurated at airport|last=G.|first=Chandrashekar|date=15 December 2013|newspaper=[[Deccan Chronicle]]|access-date=11 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308003932/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/131215/news-current-affairs/article/new-terminal-inaugurated-airport|archive-date=8 March 2016}}</ref> The {{INRConvert|1500|c}} project doubled the size of the passenger terminal to {{convert|150556|m2}}, involving the construction of additional facilities for check-in, immigration, security and baggage reclaim.<ref name=\"deccan122013\" /><ref name=\"bialupdate\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bengaluruairport.com/ourBusiness/terminalNews.jspx|title=BIA Terminal 1 Expansion Capacity, Design And Construction Update 2012-05-07|date=7 May 2012|work=Kempegowda International Airport Bengaluru|access-date=11 October 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630032038/http://www.bengaluruairport.com/ourBusiness/terminalNews.jspx|archivedate=30 June 2015}}</ref> One domestic gate and three international gates were added as well. A large, sweeping roof connects the original building with the expanded areas.<ref name=\"dhns\">{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/374653/master-plan-develop-airport-real.html|title=Master plan to develop airport real estate|date=14 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=13 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219120243/http://www.deccanherald.com/content/374653/master-plan-develop-airport-real.html|archive-date=19 December 2013}}</ref> The expanded terminal, dubbed \"Terminal 1A\", has raised the annual passenger capacity of the airport to 25 million.<ref name=\"acharjee\">{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/bangalore-kempegowda-international-airport-launched-civil-aviation-minister-ajit-singh-state-chief-minister-siddaramaiah/1/331452.html|title=Bangalore unveils its new international airport terminal|last=Acharjee|first=Sonali|date=16 December 2013|work=[[India Today]]|access-date=11 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222121531/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/bangalore-kempegowda-international-airport-launched-civil-aviation-minister-ajit-singh-state-chief-minister-siddaramaiah/1/331452.html|archive-date=22 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Future plans===\nThe second phase of expansion is underway, which encompasses the construction of a second runway and passenger terminal. When complete, Kempegowda Airport will be able to handle 55 million passengers per year.<ref name=\"at20jan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.airport-technology.com/news/newsindias-bengaluru-airport-to-construct-second-terminal-and-runway-in-2016-4789146|title=India's Bengaluru airport to construct second terminal and runway in 2016|work=Airport Technology|access-date=22 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160122093232/http://www.airport-technology.com/news/newsindias-bengaluru-airport-to-construct-second-terminal-and-runway-in-2016-4789146|archivedate=22 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"bs19jan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/bengaluru-airport-t2-phase-1-by-2021-will-handle-20-mn-more-flyers-116011901213_1.html|title=Bengaluru airport T2 phase-1 by 2021, will handle 20 mn more flyers|date=19 January 2016|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|access-date=21 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126071332/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/bengaluru-airport-t2-phase-1-by-2021-will-handle-20-mn-more-flyers-116011901213_1.html|archivedate=26 January 2016}}</ref> The estimated {{INRConvert|4000|c}} project received clearance from the [[Ministry of Environment and Forests]] in September 2014.<ref name=\"p2updateapr2016\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/work-on-terminal-2-at-kia-begins/article8434676.ece|title=Work on Terminal 2 at KIA begins|last=Peter|first=Petlee|date=5 April 2016|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=8 April 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221104456/http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/work-on-terminal-2-at-kia-begins/article8434676.ece|archivedate=21 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/Clearance-for-Airport-Expansion/2014/09/05/article2415419.ece|title=Clearance for Airport Expansion|date=5 September 2014|newspaper=[[New Indian Express]]|access-date=15 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320071703/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/Clearance-for-Airport-Expansion/2014/09/05/article2415419.ece|archive-date=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nGround work on the second runway began in February 2016 and the runway is expected to be operative by September 2019.<ref name=\"p2updateapr2016\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/bangalore/others/bangalore/others/larsen-and-toubro-to-fast-track-runway-work-at-the-kempegowda-international-airport/articleshow/61824506.cms|title=Larsen and Tubro to fast-track runway work at the Kempegowda International Airport|work=Bangalore Mirror|date=28 October 2017|first=Hemant|last=CS|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102072850/http://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/bangalore/others/bangalore/others/larsen-and-toubro-to-fast-track-runway-work-at-the-kempegowda-international-airport/articleshow/61824506.cms|archivedate=2 January 2018}}</ref> Located south of the original terminal, it will be parallel to runway 09/27 and measure {{convert|4000|x|60|m}}, wider than the original runway so it can accommodate larger aircraft. The new runway will also be [[Category III approach|CAT III]] certified, allowing for landings in fog and other low visibility conditions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bangaloreaviation.com/2016/01/bial-commences-second-runway-construction.html|title=BIAL moves forward on second runway. Target completion in two years|date=21 January 2016|work=Bangalore Aviation|access-date=24 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129064929/http://www.bangaloreaviation.com/2016/01/bial-commences-second-runway-construction.html|archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nA second terminal will be constructed to cater to the airport's growth. Terminal 2 has been designed by [[Skidmore, Owings & Merrill]]. The contract to construct Terminal 2 has also been awarded to [[Larsen & Toubro]] which will be constructed in two phases. In the first phase, the terminal will cater to 25 million passengers annually. Terminal 2 is estimated to cost {{INRConvert|3036.90|c}}.<ref name=\"T2\">{{cite news|title=L&T to construct Terminal 2 of Kempegowda Int'l Airport|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/business/bengaluru-airport-mandates-lt-695973.html|date=3 October 2018|accessdate=15 October 2018|publisher=deccanherald.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015192605/https://www.deccanherald.com/business/bengaluru-airport-mandates-lt-695973.html|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/indl-goods/svs/construction/lt-bags-rs-3036-cr-order-to-build-terminal-2-of-bengaluru-international-airport/articleshow/66050353.cms |title=L&T bags Rs 3,036-cr order to build terminal-2 of Bengaluru international airport \u2013 The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=3 October 2018 |accessdate=15 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015231537/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/indl-goods/svs/construction/lt-bags-rs-3036-cr-order-to-build-terminal-2-of-bengaluru-international-airport/articleshow/66050353.cms |archive-date=15 October 2018 |url-status=live |newspaper=The Economic Times }}</ref>\n\nA third runway, north of the current runway is being planned to cater to the growth of air traffic in the airport which will be situated 1500 meters north of the current runway. Dubbed as the \"New North Parallel Runway,\", the officials hope to ease air traffic congestion with the third runway.<ref>{{cite news|title=With eye on future growth, KIA plans third runway|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/content/640595/with-eye-future-growth-kia.html|date=2 November 2017|accessdate=23 October 2018|publisher=deccanherald.com|author=Kappan, Rasheed|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023120135/https://www.deccanherald.com/content/640595/with-eye-future-growth-kia.html|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[IndiGo]] announced in January 2019, its plan to build a second maintenance repair and overhaul facility at the airport, which is expected to be operational by March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sinha |first1=Saurabh |title=IndiGo to build MRO at Bengaluru airport, its second in India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/indigo-to-build-mro-at-bengaluru-airport-its-second-in-india/articleshow/67770947.cms |accessdate=31 January 2019 |work=Times of India |agency=The Times Group |publisher=ennett, Coleman & Co. |date=31 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131155328/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/indigo-to-build-mro-at-bengaluru-airport-its-second-in-india/articleshow/67770947.cms |archive-date=31 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Ownership ==\nThe airport is owned and operated by Bengaluru International Airport Limited (BIAL), a [[public limited company]]. The Government of India has granted BIAL the right to operate the airport for 30 years, with the option to continue for another 30 years. The company is a [[public\u2013private partnership|public\u2013private consortium]] venture. 26% is held by government entities [[Government of Karnataka|Karnataka State Industrial Investment and Development Corporation]] (13%) and [[Airports Authority of India]] (13%), and 74% is held by private companies [[Fairfax Financial]] (54%) and [[Siemens Project Ventures]] (20%).<ref>{{cite news |date=18 April 2016 |title=Zurich Airport sells 5% stake in Bangalore airport to Fairfax for $48.9 mn |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/zurich-airport-sells-5-stake-in-bangalore-airport-to-faifax-for-489-mn/article8489613.ece |work=[[The Hindu Business Line]] |access-date=3 June 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419152811/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/zurich-airport-sells-5-stake-in-bangalore-airport-to-faifax-for-489-mn/article8489613.ece |archivedate=19 April 2016  }}</ref><ref>[http://GVK%20exits%20B\u2019luru%20airport,%20sells%20residual%2010%%20stake%20to%20Fairfax http://www.freepressjournal.in/business/gvk-exits-bluru-airport-sells-residual-10-stake-to-fairfax/1102576] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5hEoIdeum?url=http://allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:nl08b5t4tsqe |date=2 June 2009 }}</ref>\n<ref>https://s1.q4cdn.com/293822657/files/doc_financials/annual_reports/2018/Website-Fairfax-India-2018-Shareholders-Letter.pdf</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:DutyFree-BLR-Airport.jpg|thumb|Duty Free]]\n\n===Runways===\nKempegowda International Airport has two [[runways]] in use.\n* Runway 09L/27R: {{convert|4000|x|45|m}}, [[Category III approach|CAT I]], [[Instrument landing system|ILS]] equipped.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |date=26 May 2016 |title=VOBL \u2013 Kempegowda Int/ Bengaluru Airport |url=https://skyvector.com/airport/VOBL/Kempegowda-Int-Bengaluru-Airport |work=SkyVector |access-date=3 June 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625145527/https://skyvector.com/airport/VOBL/Kempegowda-Int-Bengaluru-Airport |archivedate=25 June 2016  }}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aai.aero/allAirports/blr_ti.jsp|title=Technical Information|publisher=[[Airports Authority of India]]|access-date=12 March 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313120410/http://www.aai.aero/allAirports/blr_ti.jsp|archivedate=13 March 2016}}</ref>\n*Runway 09R/27L: {{convert|4000|x|60|m|abbr=}}, [[Category III approach|CAT III]], [[Instrument landing system|ILS]] equipped.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFour years after it was laid, the runway was entirely resurfaced because of a serious decline in quality.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunday-guardian.com/business/bangalore-airport-to-close-down-for-repairs|title=Bangalore airport to close down for repairs|last=Taneja|first=Kabir|date=4 March 2012|newspaper=[[Sunday Guardian]]|access-date=12 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313125950/http://www.sunday-guardian.com/business/bangalore-airport-to-close-down-for-repairs|archive-date=13 March 2016}}</ref> From 11 March to 3 April 2012, it was closed daily between 10:30 am and 5:30 pm.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bangalore/No-flights-at-BIA-for-7-hrs-from-today/articleshow/12214910.cms?referral=PM|title=No flights at BIA for 7 hrs from today|date=11 March 2012|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|access-date=12 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331031333/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bangalore/No-flights-at-BIA-for-7-hrs-from-today/articleshow/12214910.cms?referral=PM|archive-date=31 March 2015}}</ref> As a result, BIAL accused construction company [[Larsen & Toubro]] of building the runway poorly.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/bangalore-airport-turns-the-heat-on-l-t-over-runway-112030600004_1.html|title=Bangalore airport turns the heat on L&T over runway|last=Badrinath|first=Raghuvir|date=6 March 2012|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|access-date=12 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313123720/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/bangalore-airport-turns-the-heat-on-l-t-over-runway-112030600004_1.html|archive-date=13 March 2016}}</ref> South of runway 09/27 are a full-length parallel taxiway and the [[airport apron|apron]], which extends from the Blue Dart/DHL terminal to the passenger terminal.\n\nThe second runway has completed construction at the airport, and was officially in use from 6 December 2019, when an Indigo airlines flight (6E 466) to Hyderabad took off from runway 09R.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/state/top-karnataka-stories/first-flight-takes-off-from-second-runway-of-kia-783345.html|title=First flight takes off from second runway of KIA|date=6 December 2019|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=14 December 2019}}</ref> The new runway is however under limited operations until Mar 2020. The runway will cater to all types of aircraft including Code-F aircraft like [[Airbus A380]] and [[Boeing 747-8]] and will be equipped with [[Category III approach|CAT IIIB ILS]]. The runway will also feature an associated parallel taxiway and two cross-field taxiways on the east linking the new runway to the existing north runway and the aprons at Terminal 1 and Terminal 2. The existing runway will also be upgraded as part of the expansion work.<ref>{{cite web|title=KIA begins work on 2nd runway; to be linked to Terminal 2 apron|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/578752/kia-begins-work-2nd-runway.html|website=Deccan Herald|accessdate=17 March 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118161410/http://www.deccanherald.com/content/578752/kia-begins-work-2nd-runway.html|archivedate=18 January 2017|date=November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced in February 2020 that the old runway (Runway 09L/27R) will be closed for seven months (26 March 2020 To 4 November 2020) for installing [[Instrument landing system|CAT-IIIB ILS]] landing systems for guiding pilots to safely land at the airport in poor or low visibility conditions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bengaluru: Old runway at KIA to shut for 7 months {{!}} Bengaluru News - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/bengaluru-old-runway-at-kia-to-shut-for-7-months/articleshow/73947994.cms |accessdate=9 February 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=5 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Terminals ===\n[[File:Bengaluru Airport International Departures.jpg|thumb|International Departures section at Kempegowda International Airport]]\nA single integrated passenger terminal accommodates both domestic and international operations. It covers {{convert|150556|m2|abbr=on}} and can handle 20 million passengers annually.<ref name=\"bialupdate\" /><ref name=\"acharjee\" /> Check-in and baggage reclaim are situated on the lower floor, while departure gates are located on Level-1 and the ground floor. Gates 1, 2, 12\u201318, 28\u201330 on Level-1 are used for domestic departures, gates 31\u201342 on Level-1 are used for International departures, gates 3\u20139 and gates 19\u201325 form the Western and Eastern bus gates respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bengaluruairport.com/shoppingAndFandB/seasonOfSmiles.jspx?_afrLoop=7993680367376496&_afrWindowMode=0&_adf.ctrl-state=15dogiubt_4|title=Information on New Boarding Gates Numbering|work=Kempegowda International Airport Bengaluru}}</ref> Gate 41\u201342 is equipped to serve the world's largest passenger aircraft, the [[Airbus A380]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/bangalore-news/bangalore-airport-named-after-city-founder-kempegowda-544566|title=Bangalore airport named after city founder Kempegowda|date=15 December 2013|work=[[NDTV]]|access-date=15 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319002923/http://www.ndtv.com/bangalore-news/bangalore-airport-named-after-city-founder-kempegowda-544566|archive-date=19 March 2016}}</ref> [[Airport lounge|Lounges]] are provided by Above Ground Level and Plaza Premium Lounge, which also operates a day hotel in the terminal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-06-25/news/63831215_1_kempegowda-international-airport-terminal-gv-sanjay-reddy|title=Kempegowda International Airport set to sport a trendy look by October|last=Nair|first=Athira|date=25 June 2015|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=31 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004072410/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-06-25/news/63831215_1_kempegowda-international-airport-terminal-gv-sanjay-reddy|archive-date=4 October 2015}}</ref> For VIPs there is a separate {{convert|10000|ft2|m2|order=flip|adj=on}} lounge.<ref name=\"dhns\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bangaloremirror.com/bangalore/others/Sri-Lankan-PM-traveled-like-any-ordinary-flier-in-all-humility/articleshow/45102488.cms|title=Sri Lankan PM traveled like any ordinary flier, in all humility|last=Prakash|first=Rakesh|date=10 November 2014|newspaper=[[Bangalore Mirror]]|access-date=31 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128105450/http://www.bangaloremirror.com/bangalore/others/Sri-Lankan-PM-traveled-like-any-ordinary-flier-in-all-humility/articleshow/45102488.cms|archive-date=28 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Expansion===\nUnder the second phase of the airport's expansion, a new terminal called Terminal 2 is being built.<ref name=\"thehindubusinessline1\">{{cite web|last1=Urs|first1=Anil|title=BIAL ropes in US firm to design KIA Terminal 2|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/bial-ropes-in-us-firm-to-design-kia-terminal-2/article9536843.ece|website=The Hindu Business Line|accessdate=17 March 2017|language=en|date=11 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320173458/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/bial-ropes-in-us-firm-to-design-kia-terminal-2/article9536843.ece|archivedate=20 March 2018}}</ref> The new terminal has been designed by renowned architectural firm [[Skidmore, Owings & Merrill]] and is being built by [[Larsen & Toubro]].<ref name=\"thehindubusinessline1\"/> Phase 1 of the new terminal is expected to be ready by 2021 and will cater to an additional 20 million passengers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/bengaluru-airport-t2-phase-1-by-2021-will-handle-20-mn-more-flyers-116011901213_1.html|title=Bengaluru airport T2 phase-1 by 2021, will handle 20 mn more flyers|newspaper=Business Standard India|accessdate=16 February 2020|language=en|date=19 January 2016}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n[[File:Cargo terminals at Kempegowda Airport, July 2016.jpg|thumb|Menzies Aviation Bobba and AISATS cargo terminals viewed from the road to the airport]]\n\n===Aviation fuel services===\nThe airport has a fuel farm, spread over {{convert|11|acre}} west of the cargo village and passenger terminal. It was built by [[Skytanking|IndianOil SkyTanking Ltd (IOSL)]] but is shared by multiple oil companies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2008/aug/19oil.htm|title=Fuel deals: Indian Oil JV eyes Mumbai, Delhi airports|last=Kulkarni|first=Mahesh|date=19 August 2008|work=[[Rediff]]|access-date=12 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110415173317/http://www.rediff.com/money/2008/aug/19oil.htm|archive-date=15 April 2011}}</ref> In October 2008, [[Indian Oil Corporation|Indian Oil]] commissioned a {{convert|36|km|mi|adj=on}} fuel [[pipeline transport|pipeline]] between its storage terminal in Devanagonthi and Kempegowda Airport. Previously, [[jet fuel]] had to be transported to the airport by [[tank truck]]s, which created traffic and pollution problems.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/ioc-does-its-groundwork-for-devanahalli-airport/article1357276.ece|title=IOC does its groundwork for Devanahalli airport|date=15 October 2008|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=12 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403162339/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/ioc-does-its-groundwork-for-devanahalli-airport/article1357276.ece|archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Cargo facilities===\nKempegowda Airport has three cargo terminals. One is operated by [[John Menzies#Aviation|Menzies Aviation]] Bobba Pvt Ltd and has a capacity for {{convert|150000|t|ST}} of cargo;<ref name=\"bsvillage\">{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/cargo-village-takes-off-at-b-39-lore-airport-108121001006_1.html|title=Cargo village takes off at B'lore airport|date=10 December 2008|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|access-date=31 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403162431/http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/cargo-village-takes-off-at-b-39-lore-airport-108121001006_1.html|archive-date=3 April 2016}}</ref> it includes a facility for storing [[pharmaceutical drug|pharmaceuticals]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://aircargoworld.com/menzies-opens-pharma-cold-zone-in-bangalore-9993/|title=Menzies opens pharma cold zone in Bangalore|date=25 August 2014|work=Air Cargo World|access-date=12 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326025459/http://aircargoworld.com/menzies-opens-pharma-cold-zone-in-bangalore-9993/|archive-date=26 March 2015}}</ref> [[Air India]] [[SATS Ltd|SATS]] (AISATS) operates one terminal, which can handle {{convert|200000|t|ST}} of cargo.<ref name=\"bsvillage\" /> AISATS is also constructing the AISATS Coolport, which will be able to hold {{convert|40000|t|ST}} of perishable goods.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Air-India-SATS-to-build-perishable-cargo-handling-centre-at-Bengaluru-airport/articleshow/46493257.cms|title=Air India SATS to build perishable cargo handling centre at Bengaluru airport|last=Dhamija|first=Anshul|date=8 March 2015|newspaper=[[Times of India]]|access-date=12 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507223610/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Air-India-SATS-to-build-perishable-cargo-handling-centre-at-Bengaluru-airport/articleshow/46493257.cms|archivedate=7 May 2016}}</ref> Lastly, [[DHL Aviation|DHL]] and [[Blue Dart Aviation]] jointly operate a {{convert|221000|ft2|m2|order=flip|adj=on|}} terminal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bangaloreaviation.com/2008/11/dhl-and-blue-dart-open-integrated.html|title=DHL and Blue Dart open integrated terminal at Bangalore airport|last=Agarwal|first=Devesh|date=21 November 2008|work=Bangalore Aviation|access-date=31 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412203947/http://www.bangaloreaviation.com/2008/11/dhl-and-blue-dart-open-integrated.html|archivedate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nBIAL inaugurated a separate cargo village in December 2008. The village is spread over {{convert|11|acre}} and includes office space, conference rooms, a cafeteria for staff and parking space for nearly 80 trucks.<ref name=\"bsvillage\" /> It did not open for occupation until 2010 and initially suffered low occupancy, which some cargo agents attributed to the opening delay, high rent and limited infrastructure.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/116589/cargo-village-bia-still-half.html|title=Cargo Village at BIA is still half full|date=28 November 2010|newspaper=[[Deccan Herald]]|access-date=31 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110219110248/http://www.deccanherald.com/content/116589/cargo-village-bia-still-half.html|archive-date=19 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Airlines and destinations ==\n=== Passenger ===\n<!-- WHEN ADDING A NEW ROUTE, OR ADDING AN END DATE FOR A ROUTE PLEASE ADD A REFERENCE, ALSO ADD THE ROUTE AND LINK ON THE CORRESPONDING AIRPORTS ARTICLE AND THE AIRLINES ARTICLE IF IT IS A NEW DESTINATION, ANYTHING WHICH IS NOT REFERENCED WILL BE REMOVED. ALSO WHEN ADDING A NEW ROUTE, A FIRM DATE IS MANDATORY.-->\n\nAll flights (except charter and cargo) are temporarily suspended till 3 May due to [[COVID-19]].\n\n{{Airport destination list\n|[[Air Arabia]]| [[Sharjah International Airport|Sharjah]] \n<!-- -->\n|[[AirAsia]]| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]] \n|[[AirAsia India]]| [[Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel International Airport|Ahmedabad]], [[Bagdogra Airport|Bagdogra]], [[Biju Patnaik Airport|Bhubaneswar]], [[Chandigarh Airport|Chandigarh]], [[Chennai International Airport|Chennai]], [[Indira Gandhi International