h Airlines|Turkish Airlines Cargo]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2018/oct/27/kempegowda-international-airport-will-link-to-seven-more-cities-1890700.html |title=Kempegowda International Airport will link to seven more cities |publisher=The New Indian Express |date=29 October 1947 |accessdate=29 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030035425/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2018/oct/27/kempegowda-international-airport-will-link-to-seven-more-cities-1890700.html |archive-date=30 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Connectivity ==\n[[File:BIAL trumpet interchange.JPG|thumb|right|The [[trumpet interchange]] between [[National Highway 7 (India)(old numbering)|NH 7]] and the road leading from Kempegowda Airport]]\n[[File:BIAL Volvo buses.JPG|thumb|[[Bangalore Metropolitan Transport Corporation|BMTC]] Volvo buses connecting the city to the airport]]\n\n=== Road ===\nKempegowda Airport is connected to the city of Bangalore by [[National Highway 44]] (NH 44). In January 2014, a six-lane [[overpass|flyover]] was completed over NH 44 between [[Hebbal]] and the airport, helping to reduce travel time to and from the city.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Hebbal-to-Kempegowda-International-Airport-in-20-minutes/articleshow/29573300.cms |title=Hebbal to Kempegowda International Airport in 20 minutes |date=30 January 2014 |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=13 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708210631/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Hebbal-to-Kempegowda-International-Airport-in-20-minutes/articleshow/29573300.cms |archive-date= 8 July 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/drive-to-airport-to-be-smoother-by-monthend/article5530974.ece|title=Drive to airport to be smoother by month-end|date=2 January 2014|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=10 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418180205/http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/drive-to-airport-to-be-smoother-by-monthend/article5530974.ece|archive-date=18 April 2014}}</ref> Two alternative routes are under construction and will be completed by March 2017, one through [[Thanisandra]] and the other through Hennur.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/two-alternate-roads-from-the-east-to-bengaluru-airport-by-march-2017/article9231212.ece | title=Two alternate roads from the east to the airport by March 2017 | work=[[The Hindu]] | date=18 October 2016 | accessdate=18 October 2016}}</ref> The airport car park is located at ground level and can hold 2,000 vehicles.<ref name=\"at\" /> The airport is served by several taxi and rental car companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bengaluruairport.com/bial/faces/pages/transport/drivingToAndFromAirport.jspx|title=Driving to and from the Airport|publisher=Bengaluru Airport|access-date=13 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313121620/http://www.bengaluruairport.com/bial/faces/pages/transport/drivingToAndFromAirport.jspx|archivedate=13 March 2016}}</ref> In addition, ride-sharing companies [[Ola Cabs]] and [[Uber]] have their own pick-up zones outside the terminal.<ref>{{cite news |last=Urs |first=Anil |date=19 May 2016 |title=Ola signs pact with Kempegowda international airport |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/ola-signs-pact-with-kempegowda-international-airport/article8620486.ece |work=[[The Hindu Business Line]] |access-date=20 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320173458/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/ola-signs-pact-with-kempegowda-international-airport/article8620486.ece |archivedate=20 March 2018  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ray |first=Aparajita |date=25 May 2016 |title=Uber too, gets space at Bengaluru international airport |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Uber-too-gets-space-at-Bengaluru-international-airport/articleshow/52433360.cms |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=25 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814002747/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Uber-too-gets-space-at-Bengaluru-international-airport/articleshow/52433360.cms |archivedate=14 August 2016  }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Bangalore Metropolitan Transport Corporation]] (BMTC) provides bus transportation to major parts of the city through the ''Vayu Vajra'' ([[Kannada language|Kannada]] for \"Diamond in the Air\") service.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bangaloremirror.com/bangalore/cover-story/Vayu-Vajra-bleeds-BMTC-of-Rs-5-lakh-a-day/articleshow/22364739.cms |title=Vayu Vajra bleeds BMTC of Rs 5 lakh a day |date=3 November 2008 |newspaper=[[Bangalore Mirror]] |access-date=13 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403162738/http://www.bangaloremirror.com/bangalore/cover-story/Vayu-Vajra-bleeds-BMTC-of-Rs-5-lakh-a-day/articleshow/22364739.cms |archive-date= 3 April 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It is operated using a fleet of [[Volvo B7RLE]] buses. In addition, the [[Karnataka State Road Transport Corporation]] (KSRTC) operates a nonstop bus service called \"Flybus\" between Kempegowda Airport and [[Mysore]], as well as a route to [[Manipal]] via [[Mangalore]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Mangalore/ksrtc-to-operate-flybus-between-manipal-and-kia/article7549125.ece|title=KSRTC to operate Flybus between Manipal and KIA|last=Sastry|first=Anil Kumar|date=17 August 2015|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=12 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161217073229/http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Mangalore/ksrtc-to-operate-flybus-between-manipal-and-kia/article7549125.ece|archivedate=17 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Rail ===\nA [[Namma Metro]] link between Bangalore city and the airport is planned with two stations at the airport. It will be an extension of the Gottigere-Nagawara line.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/with-only-six-stations-trust-bengaluru-metro-to-take-you-to-the-airport-faster/articleshow/60908857.cms | title=With only six stations, trust Bengaluru Metro to take you to the airport faster | work=The Economic Times | date=2 October 2017 | accessdate=1 January 2018 | first=Naveen | last=Menezes | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102015751/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/with-only-six-stations-trust-bengaluru-metro-to-take-you-to-the-airport-faster/articleshow/60908857.cms | archivedate=2 January 2018 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> A high-speed rail link was previously considered and went as far as obtaining approval from the Union Government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bangalore/High-speed-rail-to-BIA-gets-green-light-/articleshow/4685478.cms?referral=PM|title=High-speed rail to BIA gets green light|last=S.|first=Kushala|date=22 June 2009|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|access-date=13 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202022414/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bangalore/High-speed-rail-to-BIA-gets-green-light-/articleshow/4685478.cms?referral=PM|archive-date=2 February 2015}}</ref> However, the project was eventually scrapped because of high costs and the lack of stops along the line.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Cost-viability-nix-high-speed-rail-link-to-Bengaluru-International-Airport/articleshow/24355940.cms |title=Cost, viability nix high-speed rail link to Bengaluru International Airport |date=19 October 2013 |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=10 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403162928/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Cost-viability-nix-high-speed-rail-link-to-Bengaluru-International-Airport/articleshow/24355940.cms |archive-date= 3 April 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/fMdx0Ry7eySVsj9bKddQhL/High-speed-rail-line-to-airport-in-Bangalore-may-be-discarde.html|title=High speed rail line to airport in Bangalore may be discarded|last=Yousaf|first=Shamsheer|date=25 September 2012|newspaper=[[Livemint]]|access-date=10 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311133714/http://www.livemint.com/Politics/fMdx0Ry7eySVsj9bKddQhL/High-speed-rail-line-to-airport-in-Bangalore-may-be-discarde.html|archive-date=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nConstruction for a [[Kempegowda International Airport halt railway station|halt]] at the KIA boundary will be completed by February 2020. The train halt will be connected to the airport terminal via short five-minute shuttle busses. On day One of the service, four trains from the city towards [[Devanahalli]] will stop at the KIA halt and four trains heading back. Future plans include hyper electrification of the route to introduce comfortable MEMU trains to the airport. Besides, MEMU trains from [[Mysore]] that terminate at [[Yelahanka]] could be extended upto Devanahalli via the KIA halt station, benefitting airport-bound passengers from Mysore, Ramanagaram and Bidadi.<ref>{{cite news |title=KIA Halt Station: Airport train, finally on track |url=https://www.deccanherald.com/city/bengaluru-infrastructure/kia-halt-station-airport-train-finally-on-track-795672.html |accessdate=24 January 2020 |work=Deccan Herald |date=17 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of airports in Karnataka]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons-inline}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.bengaluruairport.com/}}\n* [http://helperindia.com/vayu-vajra-bus-timings-2017-latest/ Vayu Vajra Bus Timings] to and from BIAL\n\n{{portalbar|India|Aviation|Bangalore}}\n{{Airports in India}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in Bangalore]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 2008]]\n", "name_user": "Lakun.patra", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: upto \u2192 up to", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kempegowda_International_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Rhodes Scholarship", "text_new": "{{short description|An international postgraduate award for students to study at the University of Oxford}}\n{{distinguish|Road Scholar}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n[[Image:Rhodes House Oxford 20040909.jpg|right|thumb|250px|[[Rhodes House]] in [[Oxford]], designed by Sir [[Herbert Baker]]]]\n\nThe '''Rhodes Scholarship''' is an international [[Postgraduate education|postgraduate]] award for students to study at the [[University of Oxford]]. It was established in 1902, making it the first large-scale programme of international scholarship.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://files.www.rhodesscholarshiptrust.com/rhodes-trust/key-governance-documents/Rhodes_Trust_Signed_Accounts_2015.pdf|title=The Rhodes Trust Annual Report and Financial Statements for the Year Ended 30 June 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610184533/http://files.www.rhodesscholarshiptrust.com/rhodes-trust/key-governance-documents/Rhodes_Trust_Signed_Accounts_2015.pdf|archivedate=10 June 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=1 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Rhodes Scholarship was founded by capitalist-imperialist [[Cecil Rhodes|Cecil John Rhodes]], to promote unity between English-speaking nations and instill a sense of civic-minded leadership and moral fortitude in future leaders irrespective of their chosen career paths.<ref name=\"will\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/lastwilltestamen00rhodiala|title=The last will and testament of Cecil John Rhodes: with elucidatory notes to which are added some chapters describing the political and religious ideas of the testator|author=Cecil Rhodes & William Thomas Stead|publisher=\"Review of Reviews\" Office|year=1902}}</ref> Although initially restricted to male applicants from countries that are today within the [[British Commonwealth]], as well as Germany and the United States, today the scholarship is open to applicants from all backgrounds and from across the globe.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Rhodes |first=R. A. W.|date=2017-08-24|title=From Prime Ministerial Power to Core Executive|journal=Oxford Scholarship Online|volume=1|doi=10.1093/oso/9780198786108.003.0009}}</ref> Since its creation, [[Rhodes Scholarship#Controversies|controversy]] has surrounded its former exclusion of women (thus leading to the establishment of the co-educational [[Marshall Scholarship]]).\n\nProminent recipients of the Rhodes Scholarship include politicians, academics, scientists, authors, and entrepreneurs. Notable American political recipients include former President of the United States [[Bill Clinton]], former [[United States National Security Advisor|United States National Security Advisor]] and United States [[Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Susan Rice]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodesscholar.org/news-and-announcements/american-rhodes-scholarship-winners-2017/|title=Home {{!}} The Rhodes Scholarships|website=www.rhodesscholar.org|access-date=2018-07-05}}</ref> former Governor of Louisiana [[Bobby Jindal|Piyush \"Bobby\" Jindal]], former United States Secretary of the Air Force and former Congresswoman [[Heather Wilson]], and former United States Secretary of Health and Human Services [[Sylvia Mathews Burwell|Sylvia Matthews Burwell]]. President of Pakistan [[Wasim Sajjad]]; former Prime Minister of [[Malta]] [[Dom Mintoff]];<ref>''Maltese Biographies of The Twentieth Century'', Michael J. Schiavone, Louis J. Scerri, Malta 1997, page 412</ref> former Australian Prime Ministers [[Tony Abbott]], [[Bob Hawke]], and [[Malcolm Turnbull]]; and the current [[Deputy Prime Minister of Canada|Deputy Prime Minister of Canada]], [[Chrystia Freeland]], are also Rhodes Scholars. Other notable Rhodes Scholars include journalist and American television host [[Rachel Maddow]], author [[Naomi Wolf]], former 2020 [[United States of America|US]] presidential candidate and [[New Jersey]] Senator [[Cory Booker]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/13/795874596/cory-booker-drops-out-of-presidential-race|title=Cory Booker Drops Out Of Presidential Race|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> former 2020 [[United States of America|US]] presidential candidate and former mayor of [[South Bend, Indiana|South Bend]] [[Pete Buttigieg]], former president of Planned Parenthood [[Leana Wen]], Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist [[Ronan Farrow]], and president of the [[Walmart Foundation]] [[Kathleen McLaughlin]]. The current Warden and CEO of the Rhodes Trust, [[Elizabeth Kiss]], is also a Rhodes Scholar.<ref>\"Interview with Elizabeth Kiss\". ''Times Higher Education (THE)''. 2018-03-08. Retrieved 2018-08-03.</ref> \n\nSome people offered this scholarship have not accepted it, including Sir [[Alimuddin Zumla]], who declined the scholarship as a teenager to study medicine.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kirby|first=Tony|date=April 2013|title=Alimuddin Zumla: infectious diseases guru and survivor|journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases|volume=13|issue=4|pages=301|doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(13)70045-8|issn=1474-4457|pmid=23531387}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Founding and motivation ===\nThe [[Rhodes Trust]] established the scholarships in 1902 under the terms laid out in the sixth and final will of Cecil John Rhodes, dated 1 July 1899 and appended by several codicils through March 1902.\n\nThe scholarships were founded for two reasons: to promote unity within the British empire, and to strengthen diplomatic ties between Britain and the United States of America. In Rhodes' own words, \"I ... desire to encourage and foster an appreciation of the advantages which I implicitly believe will result from the union of the English-speaking peoples throughout the world and to encourage in the students from North America who would benefit from the American Scholarships.\"<ref name=\"will\" /> Rhodes also bequeathed scholarships to German students in the hope that, \"a good understanding between England, Germany and the United States of America will secure the peace of the world.\"\n\nRhodes, who attended [[Oriel College, Oxford]], believed the university's residential colleges would be the best venue to nurture diplomatic ties between future world leaders.\n\nTo this day, controversies persist over Rhodes\u2019 Anglo-supremacist beliefs, most of which date back to his 1877 confession of faith.<ref>For an online version, see http://pages.uoregon.edu/kimball/Rhodes-Confession.htm</ref> However, such convictions did not play a part in the final vision for the scholarship. The scholarships are based on Rhodes' final will and testament, which states that \"no student shall be qualified or disqualified for election ... on account of race or religious opinions\".<ref name=\"will\" />\n\nThe Rhodes Scholarships are administered and awarded by the Rhodes Trust, which is located at [[Rhodes House]] in Oxford. The trust has been modified by four acts of Parliament: the Rhodes Estate Act 1916, the Rhodes Trust Act 1929, the Rhodes Trust Act 1946; and most recently by the Rhodes Trust (Modification) Order 1976, a [[statutory instrument]] in accordance with Section 78 (4) of the [[Sex Discrimination Act 1975]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://files.www.rhodesscholarshiptrust.com/rhodes-trust/key-governance-documents/Rhodes_Trust_Signed_Accounts_2015.pdf|title=The Rhodes Trust Annual Report and Financial Statements for the Year Ended 30 June 2015|access-date=1 September 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610184533/http://files.www.rhodesscholarshiptrust.com/rhodes-trust/key-governance-documents/Rhodes_Trust_Signed_Accounts_2015.pdf|archivedate=10 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== After Rhodes' death ===\n\n=== 20th century ===\nIn 1925, the [[Commonwealth Fund Fellowship]]s (later renamed the [[Harkness Fellowship]]s) were established to reciprocate the Rhodes Scholarships by enabling British graduates to study in the United States.<ref name=Harkness>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.ms-ms9258 History of the Harkness Fellowships] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223320/http://nla.gov.au/nla.ms-ms9258 |date=3 March 2016 }}, nla.gov.au</ref> The [[Kennedy Scholarship]] programme, created in 1966 as a memorial to [[John F. Kennedy]], adopts a comparable selection process to the Rhodes Scholarships to allow ten British post-graduate students per year to study at either [[Harvard]] or the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT). It also cooperates with universities in China, BLCC, for example. BLCC offers high-level scholarships for international students who aim to study Chinese in Beijing. In 1953, the Parliament of the United Kingdom created the [[Marshall Scholarship]] as a coeducational alternative to the Rhodes Scholarship that would serve as a \"living gift\" to the United States.\n\nCecil Rhodes wished current scholars and Rhodes alumni (in the words of his will) to have \"opportunities of meeting and discussing their experiences and prospects\". This has been reflected, for example, in the initiation by the first warden (Sir [[Francis Wylie]]), of an annual warden's Christmas letter (now supplemented by Rhodes e-news and other communications); the creation of alumni associations in several countries, most prominently the Association of American Rhodes Scholars (which publishes ''The American Oxonian'', founded in 1914, and oversees the Eastman Professorship); and the holding of reunions for Rhodes Scholars of all countries.\n\nIn recognition of the centenary of the foundation of the Rhodes Trust in 2003, four former Rhodes Scholars were awarded [[honorary degrees]] by the University of Oxford. These were [[John Brademas]], [[Bob Hawke]] (Western Australia and [[University College, Oxford|University]] 1953), [[Rex Nettleford]] and David R. Woods. During the centenary celebrations, the foundation of the Mandela Rhodes Foundation was also marked.\n\n=== 21st century ===\nIn 2013, during the 110th Rhodes anniversary celebrations, [[John MacBain|John McCall MacBain]], Marcy McCall MacBain and the McCall MacBain Foundation donated \u00a375 million towards the fundraising efforts of the Rhodes Trust.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/474bf79c-210f-11e3-8aff-00144feab7de.html#axzz3E7w5pncy |title=McCall MacBain donation }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Rhodes Scholar [[R. W. Johnson]] published a critical account of the decline of the Rhodes Trust under its warden, [[John Rowett]], and commended its recovery under wardens [[Donald Markwell]] and [[Charles R. Conn]].<ref>R. W. Johnson, ''Look Back in Laughter: Oxford's Postwar Golden Age'', Threshold Press, 2015, especially pages 195-220.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/higher-education/feeney-hands-150m-to-rhodes/news-story/4fa2f42023af11946c55bb89650bd215|title=Feeny hands 150m to Rhodes|last=Hare|first=Julie|date=Summer 2016|work=The Australian|access-date=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, due to the introduction of the Global Rhodes Scholarships, the Rhodes Scholarship is open to [[Postgraduate education|postgraduate]] students from anywhere in the world. Many of its greatest scholars have carried out its founder\u2019s later ideal of \u201cequal rights for all civilised men\u201d becoming some of the foremost voices in [[human rights]] and [[social justice]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-320549418.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912204421/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-320549418.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2018-09-12|title=Nicholas D. Kristof to Receive Goldsmith Career Award for Excellence in Journalism |date=2013|work=States News Service|access-date=12 September 2018}}</ref> Some have even engaged in criticism of Cecil Rhodes himself (see [[Rhodes Must Fall|Rhodes must fall]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/mar/16/the-real-meaning-of-rhodes-must-fall|title=The real meaning of Rhodes Must Fall {{!}} Amit Chaudhuri|last=Chaudhuri|first=Amit|date=2016-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2018-09-12|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Because access to further education, particularly post-graduate education, is linked with [[social mobility]] and [[Racial inequality in the United States|racial wealth disparity]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2016/04/the-growing-wealth-gap-in-who-earns-college-degrees/479688/|title=The Stubborn Wealth Gap in Who Earns a College Degree|last=Zinshteyn|first=Mikhail|date=2016-04-25|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-09-12}}</ref> the scholarship (which is for post-graduate students) continues to attract criticism; however, the scholarship's recent partnership with the [[Atlantic Philanthropies]] is intended to help address those issues.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/rhodes-trust-launch-new-institute-and-expand-scholarships|title=Rhodes Trust to launch new institute and expand scholarships|date=2016-06-01|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2018-09-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, [[University of Tennessee]] graduate Hera Jay Brown became the first [[transgender woman]] to be selected for a Rhodes Scholarship. Two [[non-binary]] scholars were also selected for the 2020 class.<ref name=\"guardian-24nov2019\">{{cite news |title=First transgender Rhodes scholar named in diverse 2020 class |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2019/nov/24/first-transgender-rhodes-scholar-2020-class |accessdate=November 24, 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nbc-25nov2019\">{{cite news |last1=Aviles |first1=Gwen |title=Trans woman is first Rhodes scholar in program's 117-year history |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/trans-woman-first-rhodes-scholar-program-s-117-year-history-n1090866 |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Selection and selectivity ==\n\n=== Selection criteria ===\nIn his will, Rhodes specified that he did not want his scholarships to go to \"merely bookworms.\" He wanted candidates assessed in regard to:\n*his literary and scholastic attainments\n*his fondness of and success in manly outdoor sports such as cricket, football and the like\n*his qualities of manhood, truth, courage, devotion to duty, sympathy for the protection of the weak, kindliness, unselfishness, and fellowship\n*his exhibition during school days of moral force of character and of instincts to lead and to take an interest in his schoolmates for those latter attributes will be likely in after-life to guide him to esteem the performance of public duty as his highest aim\n\nTo assess candidates, Rhodes specified a 200-point scale, unequally applied to each of the four areas (3/10 to each of the first and third areas, 2/10 to each of the other two areas). The first area was to be judged by examination, the second and third by ballot from the candidate's fellow students, and the fourth by the headmaster of the candidate's school. The results for each candidate would be sent to the trustees of Rhodes's will, or their appointees, who would then give a final assessment by averaging the marks for each candidate. Except for the candidates submitted by the four schools in southern Africa, the trustees were vested with the final decisions.\n\nRhodes also added that the scholars should be distributed among the Colleges at Oxford, that the trustees could remove any scholar at their discretion, and that the trustees were to host an annual dinner so scholars could discuss their \u201cexperiences and prospects.\u201d The trustees were also encouraged to invite to the dinner other \u201cpersons who have shown sympathy with the views expressed by me in this my Will.\u201d\n\nIn 2018, the same criteria underwent revision, and now specify no gender. They are now:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rhodesscholar.org/applying-for-the-scholarship/frequently-asked-questions/|title=Frequently Asked Questions - The Rhodes Scholarships|author=|date=|website=www.rhodesscholar.org}}</ref>\n\n*literary and scholastic attainments\n*energy to use one's talents to the full\n*truth, courage, devotion to duty, sympathy for and protection of the weak, kindliness, unselfishness and fellowship\n*moral force of character and instincts to lead, and to take an interest in one's fellow beings\n\nEach country's scholarship varies in its selectivity. In the United States, applicants must first pass a university-internal endorsement process, then proceed to one of the 16 U.S. districts committees. In 2016, approximately 2,500 students sought their institution's endorsement for the American Rhodes scholarship, among those 882 from 311 institutions were university-endorsed, of whom 32 were ultimately elected. As such, the American Rhodes Scholarship is more selective than the [[Churchill Scholarship]], [[Truman Scholarship]], [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright Scholarship]], [[Gates Scholarship]], and [[Mitchell Scholarship]], but marginally less selective than the [[Marshall Scholarship]] in terms of university-endorsed applicants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodesscholar.org/news-and-announcements/american-rhodes-scholarship-winners-2017/|title=American Rhodes Scholarships Winners 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=www.rhodesscholar.org|access-date=2017-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/meet-the-2014-rhodes-scholars/2013/11/26/ea276b1a-5600-11e3-835d-e7173847c7cc_story.html|title=Meet the 2014 Rhodes Scholars|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marshallscholarship.org/about/statistics|title=Statistics|website=www.marshallscholarship.org|access-date=2017-04-08}}</ref> In Canada between 1997-2002, there were an average of 234 university-endorsed applicants annually for 11 scholarships, for an acceptance rate of 4.7%. In addition, Canadian provinces differ widely in the number of applications received, with Ontario receiving 58 applications on average for 2 spots (3.4%) and Newfoundland and Labrador receiving 18 applications for 1 spot (5.7%).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yorku.ca/vpstdnts/rhodes/rhodes_background.html|title=York University {{!}} Division of Students {{!}} Rhodes Scholarship|website=www.yorku.ca|access-date=2016-09-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124073554/http://www.yorku.ca/vpstdnts/rhodes/rhodes_background.html|archivedate=24 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to the Rhodes Trust, the overall global acceptance rate stands at 0.7%, making it one of the most competitive scholarships in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://files.www.rhodesscholarshiptrust.com/china-additional-materials/Rhodes_Factsheet_-_FINAL_-_EN.pdf|title=The Rhodes Scholarship Fact Sheet|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415013335/http://files.www.rhodesscholarshiptrust.com/china-additional-materials/Rhodes_Factsheet_-_FINAL_-_EN.pdf|archivedate=15 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAn early change was the elimination of the scholarships for Germany during the [[World War I|First]] and [[World War II|Second]] [[World Wars]]. No German scholars were chosen from 1914 to 1929, nor from 1940 to 1969.<ref name=numbers>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/RhodesScholars.htm |title=Lists of Rhodes Scholars }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Rhodes's bequest was whittled down considerably in the first decades after his death, as various scholarship trustees were forced to pay taxes upon their own deaths.{{citation needed|date=June 2012}} A change occurred in 1929, when an [[Act of Parliament]] established a fund separate from the original proceeds of Rhodes's will and made it possible to expand the number of scholarships. Between 1993 and 1995, scholarships were extended to other countries in the [[European Community]].\n\n=== Scholarship terms ===\nRhodes Scholars may study any full-time postgraduate course offered by the university,<ref>Periodically the Rhodes Trustees include or exclude the MBA from the courses offered.</ref> whether a taught master's programme, a research degree, or a second undergraduate degree (senior status). In the first instance, the scholarship is awarded for two years. However, it may also be held for one year or three years. Applications for a third year are considered during the course of the second year. University and college fees are paid by the [[Rhodes Trust]]. In addition, scholars receive a monthly maintenance [[stipend]] to cover accommodation and living expenses.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Rhodes Trust |year=2009 |url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/section/faqs |title=FAQs about the Scholarships |accessdate=6 December 2010 |quote=In 2009, the stipend was UKPounds 958/month |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716232221/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/section/faqs |archivedate=16 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite pressrelease |first=Elliot F. |last=Gerson |url= http://www.rhodesscholar.org/get/5/2009_Press_Release_For_Website.pdf |title=From the Office of the American Secretary |date=21 November 2009 |accessdate=6 December 2010 |quote=Amongst other things, the press release states that the value of the Rhodes Scholarship varies depending on the academic field and the degree (B.A., master's, doctoral) chosen. For American Rhodes Scholars, Gerson estimates that the total value of the scholarship <u>averages</u> approximately US$50,000 per year, or up to as much as US$175,000 for scholars who remain in Oxford for four years.}}</ref> Although all scholars become affiliated with a [[residential college]] while at Oxford, they also enjoy access to [[Rhodes House]], an early 20th-century mansion with numerous public rooms, gardens, a library, study areas, and other facilities.\n\n== Allocation of scholarships ==\n{{Main|Allocation of Rhodes Scholarships}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:97%; text-align:center\" align=\"right\"\n!Geographic<br />constituency\n!2018<br />allocation<br />\n!1902<br />allocation<br /><ref name=will/><ref name=numbers/>\n|-\n!Australia<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sydney.edu.au/rhodes/ |title=The Rhodes Scholarships in Australia |accessdate=6 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101219160112/http://sydney.edu.au/rhodes/ |archivedate=19 December 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sydney.edu.au/rhodes/ |title=Australian Rhodes Scholarships |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101219160112/http://sydney.edu.au/rhodes/ |archivedate=19 December 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|9 ||6\n|-\n!Bermuda<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodes.bm |title=The Rhodes Scholarships in Bermuda }}</ref>\n|1 ||1\n|-\n!Canada<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canadian-rhodes-scholars.ca/index.html |title=The Canadian Association of Rhodes Scholars |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070706202454/http://www.canadian-rhodes-scholars.ca/index.html |archivedate=6 July 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|11 ||2\n|-\n!China\n|4 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!East Africa \n|1 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!Newfoundland\n|&nbsp;\u2014 ||1\n|-\n!Germany<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodes-deutschland.de |title=The Rhodes Scholarships in Germany }}</ref>\n|2 ||5\n|-\n!Hong Kong\n|1 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!India<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodesscholarships-india.com |title=The Rhodes Scholarships in India |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228182955/http://www.rhodesscholarships-india.com/ |archivedate=28 December 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodesindia.com/ |title=Indian Rhodes Scholarships }}</ref>\n|5 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!Israel\n|2 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!Jamaica & the<br />Commonwealth<br />Caribbean<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodes-caribbean.com |title=The Rhodes Scholarships for Jamaica & the Commonwealth Caribbean }}</ref>\n|2 ||1\n|-\n!Kenya\n|2 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!Malaysia\n|1 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!New Zealand<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzvcc.ac.nz/default.aspx?l=4&p=64 |title=The Rhodes Scholarships in New Zealand |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050830140725/http://www.nzvcc.ac.nz/default.aspx?l=4&p=64 |archivedate=30 August 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzvcc.ac.nz/scholarships/rhodes |title=New Zealand Vice-Chancellors' Committee page on Rhodes Scholarships }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/1966/R/RhodesScholarships/RhodesScholarships/en |title=New Zealand Rhodes Scholars, listed for 1903 to 1964 }}</ref>\n|3 ||1\n|-\n!Pakistan\n|1 ||&nbsp;1\n|-\n!Singapore\n|1 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!Southern Africa<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodestrust.org.za |title=The Rhodes Scholarships in South Africa }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodescentenary.co.za/Mandela_frame.htm |title=The Mandela Rhodes Foundation in South Africa |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031009131713/http://www.rhodescentenary.co.za/Mandela_frame.htm |archivedate=9 October 2003 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|10 ||5\n|-\n!Syria, Jordan,<br />Lebanon & Palestine\n|2 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!United Arab Emirates\n|2 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!United States<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodesscholar.org |title=The Rhodes Trust, USA }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.americanrhodes.org/ |title=Association of American Rhodes Scholars }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usna.edu/Admissions/Notables/RhodesScholars/index.htm/ |title=United States Naval Academy Rhodes Scholars |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070325201935/http://www.usna.edu/Admissions/Notables/RhodesScholars/index.htm/ |archivedate=25 March 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|32 ||32\n|-\n!West Africa\n|2 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!Zambia &<br>Zimbabwe<br><small>(formerly Rhodesia)</small>\n|2<br>2<br>\u2014 ||&nbsp;\u2014<br>\u2014<br>3\n|-\n!Global scholarships\n|2 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n!Total !!100 !!58\n|-\n|}\n\nThere were originally 58 scholarships.<ref name=will/><ref name=numbers/>\n\nFour [[South Africa]]n boys' schools were mentioned in Rhodes' will, each to receive an annual scholarship: the [[Paul Roos Gymnasium|Boys High School]] in [[Stellenbosch]] (today known as Paul Roos Gymnasium); the [[Diocesan College]] (Bishops) in [[Rondebosch]]; the [[South African College Schools]] (SACS) in [[Newlands, Cape Town|Newlands]]; and [[St. Andrew's College (South Africa)|St Andrew's College]] in [[Grahamstown]]. These have subsequently been opened also to former students of their partner schools (girls' or co-educational schools).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/southern-africa|title=The Rhodes Scholarships for Southern Africa (including South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Namibia and Swaziland)|website=The Rhodes Scholarships|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref>\n\nDuring the ensuing 100 years, the trustees have added about another 40 scholarships at one time or another, though not all have continued. Some of these extended the scheme to Commonwealth countries not mentioned in the will.<ref name=\"BriefHistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/history.htm|title=Brief history of the Rhodes Trust|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206130239/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/history.htm|archivedate=6 February 2007}}</ref> A more detailed allocation by region by year can be found at [[Rhodes Scholarship Allocations]]. Very brief summaries of some of the terms and conditions can be found on the trust's website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/faq.htm |title=Rhodes Scholarship FAQ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613000940/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/faq.htm |archivedate=13 June 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/infoscholar.htm |title=Information about the Scholarships |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070305220039/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/infoscholar.htm |archivedate=5 March 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Complete details can be obtained from the nominating countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/countries_complete.htm |title=Country Websites and Information |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702180155/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/countries_complete.htm |archivedate=2 July 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, scholars are selected from over 20 Rhodes constituencies (64 different countries) worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/scholarship/how-to-apply-for-a-rhodes-scholarship/ |title=How to Apply|website=Rhodes Trust|date=2017|author= |accessdate= 17 August 2017}}</ref> In 2015, the Rhodes Scholarship extended into new territories, first with the announcement of a number of scholarships for [[China]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/news/chinalaunch|title=The Rhodes Trust announces the launch of Rhodes Scholarships for China|access-date=2016-09-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226095857/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/news/chinalaunch|archivedate=26 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> later with the announcement of one to two scholarships per year for the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/news/uae-launch|title=Launch of Rhodes Scholarships for the United Arab Emirates Announced|access-date=2016-09-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923223946/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/news/uae-launch|archivedate=23 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The organisation administering the scholarships is preparing to begin naming scholars from China. The move into China is the biggest expansion since women became eligible in the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/31/world/asia/rhodes-scholarships-expanding-to-include-chinese-students.html|title=Rhodes Scholarships Expanding to Include Chinese Students|last=Barboza|first=David|date=2015-03-30|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n=== Exclusion of women ===\nThe Rhodes Scholarship was originally, as per the language used in Rhodes's will, open only to \"male students\".  That stipulation would not change until 1977. Rhodes developed his scholarships partly through conversation with [[William Thomas Stead]], editor of ''[[The Pall Mall Gazette]]'' and confidant of Rhodes, and at one time an executor of the Will who was stricken from the role when he objected to Rhodes's ill-fated effort to seize the [[Transvaal Colony|Transvaal]]. Shortly after Rhodes's death, Stead implied in a published article about the Will that he suggested that Rhodes open the scholarships to women.<ref>William Thomas Stead, \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=h2ZPAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA609&lpg=PA609&dq=mr.+rhodes%27s+will+and+its+genesis+stead&source=bl&ots=dlaGVFpnWK&sig=A4PK-gC5Ui7AitbMuBM-ECRaOqA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiluoqGm7bdAhVHNd8KHRJpBwoQ6AEwAXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=mr.%20rhodes's%20will%20and%20its%20genesis%20stead&f=false Mr. Rhodes\u2019s Will and Its Genesis]\", p. 479, ''The Review of Reviews'' 25, pp. 471\u201382</ref>  But Rhodes refused. Nothing more is said on the matter.\n\nAfter his death, the will was under the control of the Board of Trustees of the Rhodes Trust. In 1916, however, the trustees introduced a bill into the House of Commons that, catering to popular British sentiment during the [[World War I|War]], \"revoked and annulled\" the scholarships for Germans.<ref>See [[Angela Stent]], \"The Women's Bid for a Rhodes\", ''Change'', Vol. 6, No. 5 (June 1974), pp 13.16.</ref> Since then, legal control over the will has resided with Parliament.\n\nIn 1970, the trustees established the Rhodes Visiting Fellowships. Unlike the regular scholarship, a Visiting Fellow was expected to have a doctorate or comparable degree, and to use the two-year funded study to engage in independent research. Only 33 Visiting Fellowships were awarded.<ref>See [http://www.otago.ac.nz/library/exhibitions/rhodes_scholars/rhodes_women.html \"Rhodes Visiting Fellowships for Women\"].</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Parliament passed the [[Sex Discrimination Act 1975|Sex Discrimination Act of 1975]] that banned discrimination based on sex, including in education.  The trustees then applied to the Secretary of State for Education to admit women into the scholarship, and in 1976 the request was granted.<ref>Philip Ziegler, ''Legacy: Cecil Rhodes, the Rhodes Trust and Rhodes Scholarships'', 2008, Yale University Press, p. 221.</ref> In 1977, women were finally admitted to the full scholarship. To a large degree, this change was the result of the advances of the feminist movement as well as the importance of [[Title IX]] legislation in the United States that made illegal sex discrimination in colleges that received federal financial assistance.\n\nBefore Parliament passed the 1975 Act, some universities protested against the exclusion of women by nominating female candidates, who were later disqualified at the state level of the American competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1973/10/6/harvard-endorses-3-women-for-male-restricted/|title=Harvard Endorses 3 Women For Male-Restricted Rhodes {{!}} News {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref> In 1977, the first year women were eligible, 24 women (out of 72 total scholars) were selected worldwide, with 13 women and 19 men selected from the United States.<ref name=WomenScholars>[https://archive.today/20121210090918/http://therhodesproject.wordpress.com/2010/01/29/second-class-citizens-how-women-became-rhodes-scholars/ \"Second-class citizens: How women became Rhodes Scholars\"], 29 January 2010, therhodesproject.wordpress.com</ref> Since then, the average female share of the scholarship in the United States had been around 35 percent.<ref name=WomenScholars/>\n\nIn his 2008 book ''Legacy: Cecil Rhodes, the Rhodes Trust and Rhodes Scholarship'' ([[Yale University Press]]), biographer and historian [[Philip Ziegler]] writes that \"The advent of women does not seem notably to have affected the balance of Scholars among the various professions, though it has reduced the incidence of worldly success.\"  The idea has persisted that women Rhodes Scholars are less successful overall than their male peers. But the Rhodes Project<ref>[http://rhodesproject.com/ The Rhodes Project]</ref> seeks to challenge this idea.<ref>See \"30 Years of Rhodes Women\" (https://www.americanrhodes.org/assets/attachments/347.pdf).</ref>\n\nIn South Africa, the will of Cecil Rhodes expressly allocated scholarships to four all-male private schools. In 1992, one of the four schools partnered with an all-girls school in order to allow female applicants. In 2012, the three remaining schools followed suit to allow women to apply.<ref name=\"rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/news/south-african-schools-scholarships|title=New partnerships for South African schools' Rhodes Scholarships|access-date=2016-09-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123172624/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/news/south-african-schools-scholarships|archivedate=23 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Today, four of the nine scholarships allocated to South Africa are open only to students and alumni of these schools and partner schools.<ref name=\"rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk\"/>\n\n=== Exclusion of black Africans ===\nRhodes clearly specified in the will that \"No student shall be qualified or disqualified for election to a Scholarship on account of his race or religious opinions.\" Rhodes often in his writings used the word \"race\" with reference to black Africans, what he called \"natives\". In the context of the historical era, it would have been entirely out of character for Rhodes, and seen as absurd by the trustees and Oxford, to suggest that some of the scholarships might go to Africans. Furthermore, as Rhodes himself knew, and as Oxford University insisted in the early years of the scholarships, all applicants for the scholarship were required to pass the entrance exam for Oxford, or its equivalent, called [[Responsions]], which included ancient Greek and Latin. It would have been highly unusual for any Africans in that era to be admitted into those European schools in southern Africa that taught such subjects. Rhodes's scholarships intentionally excluded women and Africans, and those stipulations were followed carefully in the implementation<ref>E.g., Tim Nuttall, 2001, \"A Century of South African Rhodes Scholarships\", in A. Kenny, ed., ''The History of the Rhodes Trust 1902\u20131999'', Oxford University Press, pp. 251\u2013314</ref> Nothing in the will or in any of Rhodes' other writings suggests his desire to educate non-Europeans. In fact, the four South African schools named by Rhodes only admitted whites, and would not open their doors to black Africans until the end of [[apartheid]] in the early 1990s.\n\nBeginning in 1970, scholars began protesting against the fact that all Rhodes Scholars from southern Africa were white, with 120 Oxford dons and 80 of the 145 Rhodes Scholars in residence at the time signing a petition calling for non-white scholars to be elected in 1971.<ref name=\"Schaeper\">Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. ''Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite'', 2010. Berghahn Books: New York</ref>{{rp|238}} The case of South Africa was especially difficult to resolve, because in his will establishing the scholarships, unlike for other constituencies, Rhodes specifically allocated four scholarships to alumni of four white-only private secondary schools. According to Schaeper and Schaeper,<ref name=\"Schaeper\" />{{rp|236\u2013237}} the issue became \"explosive\" in the 1970s and 1980s as scholars argued that the scholarship be changed while the trustees argued they were powerless to change the will. Despite such protests, only in 1991 with the rise of the [[African National Congress]] did black South Africans begin to win the scholarships.<ref name=\"Schaeper\" />{{rp|240}}\n\n=== Criticism of Rhodes as colonialist ===\n{{see also|Rhodes Must Fall|Cecil Rhodes#Political Views}}\n\nPublic criticism of the scholarship has also focused on Cecil Rhodes's [[white supremacist]] views. For example, in 1966, regional committees in interviews asked a white American candidate to assure them he would not publicly belittle the scholarship after he referred to its founding on \"blood money\".<ref name=\"Schaeper\" />{{rp|238}} In 2015, a South African Rhodes Scholar, [[Ntokozo Qwabe]], began a campaign to address Rhodes' [[Cecil Rhodes#Political Views|controversial historical and political legacy]], with a focus on Qwabe\u2019s own views which included such statements as \"dismantling the open glorification of colonial genocide in educational and other public spaces \u2013 which makes it easy for British people to believe that these genocides were 'not that bad' \u2013 and props up the continuing structural legacies of British colonialism, neocolonialism, and ongoing imperialism\".<ref name=\"cherwell.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cherwell.org/2015/12/23/oxford-rhodes-scholar-attacked-for-quothypocrisyquot/|title=Oxford Rhodes scholar attacked for \"hypocrisy\"|last=Foxton|first=Hannah|date=2015-12-23|website=Cherwell.org|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref> Among other things, the campaign called for the removal of a statue of Rhodes from Oriel College and changes to Oxford's curriculum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2015/jun/18/oxford-uni-must-decolonise-its-campus-and-curriculum-say-students|title=Oxford Uni must decolonise its campus and curriculum, say students|last=Rhoden-Paul|first=Andr\u00e9|date=2015-06-18|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref> While the college agreed to review the placement of the statue, the Chancellor of the university, Lord Patten, was critical of the accuracy of Qwabe\u2019s statements and warned against \"pandering to contemporary views\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/universityeducation/12094277/Cecil-Rhodes-Oxford-University-students-must-confront-views-they-find-objectionable-says-new-head.html|title=Cecil Rhodes: Lord Patten warns against 'pandering to contemporary views' over statue row|access-date=2016-09-01|date=2016-01-13|last1=Espinoza|first1=Javier}}</ref>\n\nA group of Rhodes Scholars also created the group Redress Rhodes whose mission was to \"attain a more critical, honest, and inclusive reflection of the legacy of Cecil John Rhodes\" and to \"make reparative justice a more central theme for Rhodes Scholars.\" Their demands include, among other things, shifting the Rhodes Scholarships awarded exclusively to previously all-white South African schools (rather than the at-large national pool), dedicating a \"space at Rhodes House for the critical engagement with Cecil Rhodes' legacy, as well as imperial history\", and ending a ceremonial toast Rhodes Scholars make to the founder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/redress-rhodes|title=Redress Rhodes|website=The Rhodes Scholarships|access-date=2016-09-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923213857/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/redress-rhodes|archivedate=23 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While the group does not have a position on the removal of the statue, its co-founder has called for the scholarship to be renamed as it is \"the ultimate form of veneration and colonial apologism; it's a large part of why many continue to understand Rhodes as a benevolent founder and benefactor.\"<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2016/jan/12/cecil-rhodes-scholars-reject-hypocrisy-claims-amid-row-over-oriel-college-statue|title=Oxford scholars reject hypocrisy claims amid row over Cecil Rhodes statue|last=Khomami|first=Nadia|date=2016-01-13|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref>\n\nPublic criticism has also focused on the alleged hypocrisy of applying for and accepting the Rhodes Scholarship while criticizing it, with University of Cambridge academic [[Mary Beard (classicist)|Mary Beard]], writing in ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'', arguing that Scholars \"[could not] have your cake and eat it here: I mean you can't whitewash Rhodes out of history, but go on using his cash.\"<ref name=\"cherwell.org\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/12062808/Rhodes-scholar-branded-hypocrite-for-leading-campaign-to-have-Rhodes-statue-removed-criticised-by-Mary-Beard.html|title=Rhodes scholar branded hypocrite for leading campaign to have Rhodes' statue removed criticised by Mary Beard|access-date=2016-09-01|date=2015-12-21|last1=Espinoza|first1=Javier}}</ref> Reacting to this criticism, Qwabe replied that \"all that [Rhodes] looted must absolutely be returned immediately. I'm no beneficiary of Rhodes. I'm a beneficiary of the resources and labour of my people which Rhodes pillaged and slaved.\"<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/12060780/Oxford-student-who-wants-Rhodes-statue-down-branded-hypocrite-for-taking-money-from-trust.html|title=Oxford student who wants Rhodes statue down branded 'hypocrite' for taking money from trust|access-date=2016-09-01|date=2015-12-21|last1=Espinoza|first1=Javier}}</ref> A group of 198 Rhodes Scholars of various years later signed a statement supporting Qwabe and arguing that there was \"no hypocrisy in being a recipient of a Rhodes scholarship and being publicly critical of Cecil Rhodes and his legacy \u2013 a legacy that continues to alienate, silence, exclude and dehumanise in unacceptable ways. There is no clause that binds us to find 'the good' in Rhodes' character, nor to sanitise the imperialist, colonial agenda he propagated.\"<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/>\n\n=== Criticism over recipients not entering public service ===\nThe tendency of a growing number of Rhodes Scholars to enter business or private law, as opposed to public service for which the scholarship was intended, has been a source of frequent criticism and \"occasional embarrassment\".<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. \"Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite,\" 2010. Berghahn Books: New York, pp. 300-302.</ref> Writing in 2009, the Secretary of the Rhodes Trust criticised the trend of Rhodes Scholars to pursue careers in finance and business, noting that \"more than twice as many [now] went into business in just one year than did in the entire 1970s\", attributing it to \"grotesque\" remuneration offered by such occupations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/11/20/AR2009112003374.html|title=Losing Rhodes scholars to Wall Street's siren call|last=Gerson|first=Elliot|date=2009-11-21|newspaper=The Washington Post|issn=0190-8286|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref> At least \"a half dozen\" 1990s Rhodes Scholars became partners at [[Goldman Sachs]] and, since the 1980s, [[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey]] has had numerous Rhodes Scholars as partners. Similarly, of Rhodes Scholars who became attorneys, about one-third serve as staff attorneys for private corporations, while another third remain in private practice or academic posts.<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. \"Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite,\" 2010. Berghahn Books: New York, p. 302.</ref>\n\nAccording to Schaeper and Schaper,<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. \"Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite,\" 2010. Berghahn Books: New York, p. 280.</ref> \"From 1904 to the present, the programme's critics have had two main themes: first, that too many scholars were content with comfortable, safe jobs in academe, in law, and in business; second, that too few had careers in government or other fields where public service was the number-one goal.\" [[Andrew Sullivan]] wrote in 1988 that \"of the 1,900 or so living American scholars ... about 250 fill middle-rank administrative and professorial positions in middle-rank state colleges and universities ... [while] another 260...have ended up as lawyers.\"<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. \"Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite,\" 2010. Berghahn Books: New York, p. 282.</ref>\n\n=== Quality of post-graduate education at Oxford ===\nIn 2007, an [[op-ed]] in [[The Harvard Crimson]] by two American Rhodes Scholars<ref name=\"DellMylavarapBlues\">{{cite news |last1=Dell |first1=Melissa |last2=Mylavarap |first2=Swati |title=Oxford Blues |url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2007/2/25/oxford-blues-to-all-juniors-out/ |accessdate=7 June 2019 |work=[[The Harvard Crimson]] |date=February 25, 2007}}</ref> caused an \"international row over Oxford's status as a top university\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/news/1234879.Uninspired_scholars_attack_university/|title=Uninspired scholars attack university|website=The Oxford Times}}</ref> when they criticized the university's post-graduate education as \"outdated\" and \"frustrating\" in comparison to their education in the United States, specifically pointing to the perceived low quality of instruction and an insufficient scholarship stipend for living expenses. They also criticized the Rhodes application process itself, arguing that potential applicants should not apply unless they are \"ready to study and live in Oxford.\"<ref name=\"DellMylavarapBlues\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2007/3/16/the-rhodes-and-harvard-opportunity-not/|title=The Rhodes and Harvard: Opportunity, Not Obligation - Opinion - The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com}}</ref>\n\nThe original op-ed<ref name=\"DellMylavarapBlues\"/> spurred responses on both sides of the Atlantic.<ref>{{cite magazine | first=Elizabeth | last=Green | title=Harvard Rhodes Winners are Whiners, say Yale kids | magazine=US News & World Report  | date=9 April 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | first=Elizabeth | last=Green | title=Rhodes Scholars Say Oxford's Overrated | magazine=US News & World Report  | date=February 28, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first=Christine | last=Finn | title=Rhodes scholars give Oxford D-minus | newspaper=The Sunday Times  | date=4 March 2007}}</ref> Other students criticised the authors for their tone of \"ingratitude and entitlement,\" while ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' noted that it fueled the \"long rivalry between Harvard, Cambridge and Oxford\" and existing concerns about the quality of British graduate education. In response, the Rhodes Trust released two statements, one to ''The'' ''Sunday Times'' saying that \"the criticisms ... are unrepresentative of the vast majority of Americans\" studying at Oxford,<ref>{{cite news | first=Elliot | last=Gerson | title=Oxford Popularity - Letter | newspaper=The Sunday Times  | date=11 March 2007}}</ref> and another as a reply to the original op-ed arguing that \"false expectations,\" particularly for those uncertain about their degree choice, and going to Oxford for the \"wrong reasons,\" could contribute to dissatisfaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2007/3/2/oxford-is-about-transitions-and-not/|title=Oxford Is About Transitions And Not For Everyone - Opinion - The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com}}</ref>\n\n== Notable scholars and career trajectories ==\n{{see also|List of Rhodes Scholars}}\nSurveying the history of the Rhodes Scholarship, Schaeper and Schaeper conclude<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. ''Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite'', Berghahn Books: New York, 2010 p. 314.</ref> that while \"few of them have 'changed the world' ... most of them have been a credit to their professions ... and communities\", finding that \"the great majority of Rhodes Scholars have had solid, respectable careers.\" Eight former Rhodes scholars subsequently became heads of government or heads of [[sovereign state|state]], including [[Wasim Sajjad]] (Pakistan), [[Bill Clinton]] (United States), [[Dom Mintoff]] (Malta), [[John Turner]] (Canada), [[Norman Manley]] (Jamaica) and three Australian Prime Ministers: [[Bob Hawke]], [[Tony Abbott]] and [[Malcolm Turnbull]].\n\nFrom 1951 to 1997, 32% of American Rhodes Scholars pursued careers in education and academia, 20% in law, 15% in business and 10% in medicine and science.<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. ''Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite'', Berghahn Books: New York, 2010, p. 279.</ref> Although Cecil Rhodes imagined that scholars would \"pursue a full-time career in government [...] the number of scholars in local, state and federal government has remained at a steady 7 percent\" over the past century. Of the 200 or so scholars who have spent their careers in government, \"most of them have had solid, but undistinguished careers,\" while \"perhaps forty or more can be said to have had a significant, national impact in their particular areas.\"<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. \"Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite,\" 2010. Berghahn Books: New York, p. 311.</ref>\n\nThe highest-ranking career choice for Rhodes Scholars is education and academia, with many becoming deans of law and medical schools and others becoming professors and lecturers. Many of the most distinguished Rhodes Scholars, such as Zambian activist [[Lucy Banda-Sichone|Lucy Banda]], have become prominent members of the civil rights movement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/zambian-activist-lucy-banda-becomes-first-female-rhodes-scholar-to-have-portrait-displayed-at-oxford-a6766946.html|title=The first ever portrait of a female Rhodes scholar has been unveiled|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> In 1990, third-wave feminist author Naomi Wolf put forward ideas about beauty and power with her book ''[[The Beauty Myth]]'', ushering in a new type of feminism that has risen to prominence in the digital age.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/oct/18/classics.shopping|title=Women: A quick reminder ... The Beauty Myth by Naomi Wolf|last=Wilson|first=Emily|date=2005-10-18|website=the Guardian|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\nRhodes Scholars have had a notable impact in the fields of medicine and science. Howard Florey was awarded a Rhodes Scholarship in 1922 after studying medicine at Adelaide Medical school. In 1939 Florey, along with fellow scientist [[Ernst Chain|Ernst Boris Chain]], led the team that successfully isolated and purified penicillin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1945/florey/biographical/|title=The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 1945|website=NobelPrize.org|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Human rights, social justice and advocacy ===\n\n==== Law ====\nChallenging some of the convictions of the scholarship's founder is not a recent occurrence. As early as 1931, [[Afrikaans]]-born anti-apartheid lawyer Bram Fischer and Rhodes Scholar campaigned for equal rights for all South Africans. This led him to join the [[Communist Party of South Africa]]. Fischer was struck off the roll by the Johannesburg Bar Council in 1965 after he skipped bail on charges under the Suppression of Communism Act. He was later arrested and sentenced to life in prison.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nelsonmandela.org/news/entry/bram-fischer-a-hero-born-100-years-ago|title=Bram Fischer: a hero born 100 years ago \u2013 Nelson Mandela Foundation|website=www.nelsonmandela.org|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> Other Rhodes Scholars have taken on difficult social causes with more success. In 1980, former Rhodes Scholar [[Ann Olivarius]] sued Yale University over their mis-handling of on-campus sexual harassment complaints.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/womens-life/11632346/Sex-harassment-in-British-universities-What-date-rape-inventor-thinks.html|title=What the woman who coined the term \u2018date rape\u2019 thinks of British universities|last=Goldhill|first=Olivia|date=2015-05-27|access-date=2018-11-23|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/womens-life/11570529/Revenge-porn-This-sexual-crime-can-be-stopped-with-street-tactics.html|title=Revenge porn: 'Street tactics' can stamp out this industrial scale sexual crime|last=Olivarius|first=Dr Ann|date=2015-05-11|access-date=2018-11-23|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==== Education and child welfare ====\nAfter leaving Oxford to write his first novel, former Rhodes Scholar [[Jonathan Kozol]] volunteered as a teacher in [[Roxbury, Boston]]. He would go on to write ''Death at an Early Age: The Destruction of the Hearts and Minds of Negro Children in the Boston Public Schools,'' after witnessing first-hand the devastating effect educational inequality was having on America.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2007-01-01|title=Kozol, Jonathan|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-2587100047.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124055047/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-2587100047.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2018-11-24}}</ref> Rhodes Scholars Marc Kielburger and Roxanne Joyal conduct similar work with their organisation Free the Children. Together they build schools and educate children in developing countries across Africa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/life/2009/03/09/their_love_is_built_on_helping_others.html|title=Their love is built on helping others {{!}} The Star|work=thestar.com|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Civil and human rights ====\nMuch of the Rhodes Alumni's civil and human rights work has been focussed in Africa, particularly South Africa. South African Justice Edwin Cameron initially focussed his attention on law and employment law, but later worked in the field of LGBT rights as well as co-founding the Aids Consortium. Two-time Pulitzer-winning journalist [[Nicholas Kristof|Nick Kristof]] was pivotal in shedding light on atrocities such as Tiananmen Square and the genocide in Darfur.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/column/nicholas-kristof|title=Nicholas Kristof|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> Professor [[Sandra Fredman]] has also written extensively on anti-discrimination law, human rights law and labour law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://denning.law.ox.ac.uk/members/profile.php?lecturer_code=fredmans|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121223021844/http://denning.law.ox.ac.uk/members/profile.php?lecturer_code=fredmans|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-12-23|title=Oxford Law :: Profile of Sandra Fredman|date=2012-12-23|work=archive.is|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> [[Rhiana Gunn-Wright]] was the creator of the [[Green New Deal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060107485|title=CLIMATE: Meet the scholar crafting the 'Green New Deal'|website=www.eenews.net|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Medical innovation ===\n\n==== Genetics ====\nIn 2014, Iranian Rhodes Scholar and front-person for [[Indie rock|indie-rock]] band Thousand Days, [[Pardis Sabeti]], used genome sequencing and computational genetics to identify the source of the 2014 Ebola outbreak in West Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/news-opinion/ebola-outbreak-strains-sequenced-36944|title=Ebola Outbreak Strains Sequenced|website=The Scientist Magazine\u00ae|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\nAnother Rhodes Scholar working in [[genome]] research is the mathematician and geneticist [[Eric Lander]]. His ideas in human genetics, particularly mapping and sequencing, led to the creation of [[the Cancer Genome Atlas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2018-07/asoh-ahe071018.php|title=ASHG honors Eric S. Lander with William Allan Award|website=EurekAlert!|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Disease and epidemiology ====\nDr Salem Yusef, an Indian scholar, conducted significant research into respiratory health and its relationship to developing economies. He observed that shifts in the developing world, particularly dietary changes and increased urbanisation, lead to higher incidences of heart attacks and strokes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.anzishaprize.org/mentors-judges/yusuf-randera-rees/|title=Celebrating Africa's Youngest Entrepreneurs {{!}} Yusuf Randera-Rees|website=www.anzishaprize.org|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\nIn Zimbabwe, Dr A Tariro Makadzange has researched perinatally infected children with HIV and HIV-positive adults with cryptococcal disease. Since graduating from Oxford, she has set up a new infectious disease laboratory at the University of Zimbabwe in Harare.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ragoninstitute.org/makadzange-opens-new-lab-in-zimbabwe/|title=Makadzange Opens New Lab in Zimbabwe|date=2014-06-24|work=Ragon Institute of MGH, MIT and Harvard|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Surgery ====\nAfter studying at Oxford, surgeon and author [[Atul Gawande]] became an advisor to Bill Clinton and the U.S Department of Health and Human Services.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2008-01-01|title=Gawande, Atul 1965- (Atul A. Gawande)|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3057000057.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124055108/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3057000057.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2018-11-24}}</ref> In recent years he has devised an innovative checklist for a successful surgery.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2011/10/03/personal-best|title=The Coach in the Operating Room|work=The New Yorker|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=122226184|title=Atul Gawande's 'Checklist' For Surgery Success|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> Other surgical innovations brought about by Rhodes Scholars include the GliaSite technique, a device that lowers the risks associated with radiation therapy in brain tumours. Neurosurgeon Griffith Harsh created the GliaSite device.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.stanford.edu/news/2001/november14/gliasite.html|title=New device delivers safer, targeted brain tumor treatment straight to the source: 11/01|website=news.stanford.edu|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== The arts ===\n\n==== Literature ====\nOne of the first recipients of the Rhodes Scholarship was the American poet, educator and critic [[John Crowe Ransom]]. He became a founding member of the influential Fugitive literary group.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rubin|first=Louis D.|date=1974|title=The Wary Fugitive John Crowe Ransom|journal=The Sewanee Review|volume=82|issue=4|pages=583\u2013618|jstor=27542882}}</ref> A contemporary of Ransom's who also became a Rhodes Scholar was [[Robert Penn Warren]]. Warren was lambasted by his peers who told him that the study of English literature was a soft option; seeking to rebut such attacks, he introduced new critical ideas into the study of poetry and fiction, and these ideas went on to change how literature was taught at undergraduate and postgraduate levels, not only in America itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.english.illinois.edu/maps/poets/m_r/ransom/life.htm|title=John Crowe Ransom's Life and Career|website=www.english.illinois.edu|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Hip-hop ====\nIn 2006 (before receiving a Rhodes Scholarship), lawyer and current Democratic Congressman [[Antonio Delgado (politician)|Antonio Delgado]] critiqued capitalism and racial injustice under the name \"AD the Voice\"; arguably, however, his most significant contribution to [[hip-hop]] is not his music but the community outreach work he does in [[New York's 19th congressional district]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/17/us/politics/antonio-delgado-lyrics.html|title=A Congressional Candidate Used to Be a Rapper. Will It Matter?|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\nRoughly 90 years prior, the phrase \u201ckeeping it real\u201d was used by Rhodes scholar [[Alain Locke]] in his book ''The New Negro,'' to describe the pursuit of in the face of mainstream media's portrayal of African American culture.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The New negro|last=Locke|first=Alain|date=1997|publisher=Simon & Schuster|isbn=978-0684838311|edition= 1st Touchstone|location=New York, N.Y.|oclc=37551618}}</ref> Locke's work inspired the [[Harlem Renaissance]] movement, and \u201ckeeping it real\u201d has since become a universally recognised hip-hop ethos.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Price|first=Robert Jr|date=2005|title=Hegemony, Hope, and the Harlem Renaissance: Taking Hip Hop Culture Seriously|url=https://newprairiepress.org/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.com/&httpsredir=1&article=2681&context=aerc|journal=Kansas State University Libraries|volume=|pages=|via=newprairiepress.org}}</ref>\n\n=== Science and technology ===\n\n==== Space exploration ====\nAfter studying ion propulsion at Oxford, Dr. Jennifer Gruber embarked on a career as a space engineer. She is currently coordinating missions between the Johnson Space Center and the International Space Station as an employee of NASA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailynebraskan.com/omaha-native-chosen-as-rhodes-scholar/article_e7feb834-dbc6-5e0f-ad54-1692b7c97538.html|title=Omaha native chosen as Rhodes scholar|last=writer|first=Kim Sweet / Staff|work=The Daily Nebraskan|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Cosmology ====\nRhodes Scholar [[Brian Greene]] co-founded ISCAP, Columbia's Institute for Strings, Cosmology, and Astroparticle Physics. As well as winning a Pulitzer for non-fiction, Greene made some ground-breaking discoveries in the field of superstring theory and was one of the cosmologists to co-discover superstring theory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://codcourier.org/8400/news/theoretical-physicist-brian-greene-proposes-string-theory-as-the-theory-of-everything/|title=Theoretical physicist Brian Greene proposes String Theory as the theory of everything \u2013 The Courier|last=Weslo|first=Joey|website=codcourier.org|access-date=2018-11-23|date=2018-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== Comparison to other post-graduate scholarships ==\n{{see also|Marshall_Scholarship#Comparison to other post-graduate scholarships|label 1 = Comparison of the Marshall Scholarship to other scholarships}}\nAs the first large-scale programme of international scholarships,<ref name=\":1\">The American Rhodes Scholarships: A Review of the First Forty Years, Review author[s]: Harvie Branscomb, The American Historical Review \u00a9 1947 American Historical Association</ref> the Rhodes Scholarship inspired the creation of other awards, including:\n\n* The international [[Fulbright Program]] to teach study and research or teach English in over 150 countries (1946)\n* The [[Marshall Scholarship]] for Americans to study at any university in the United Kingdom (1953), an official British scholarship scheme for Americans\n* The [[Chevening Scholarship]] for citizens from 144 countries and territories to undertake postgraduate studies or courses in universities in the United Kingdom (1983), an official British scholarship scheme for countries other than the United States\n* The Churchill Scholarship for Americans to study at [[Churchill College, Cambridge|Churchill College]] at the [[University of Cambridge]] (1959)\n* The [[Kennedy Scholarship]] for British nationals to study at [[Harvard University]] or the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (1964)\n* The Harkness Fellowship for citizens of nine countries to conduct research related to health policy in the United States (1997)\n* The Mitchell Scholarship for Americans to study at any university in Ireland (2000)\n* The international [[Gates Cambridge Scholarship]] to study at the [[University of Cambridge]] (2000)\n* The [[Clarendon_Fund|Clarendon Scholarship]] for \"the best and brightest minds in any given field\" to pursue post-graduate study at the [[University of Oxford]] (2001)\n* The [[John Monash Scholars]]hip for Australians to study at any university worldwide (2004)\n* The international [[Yenching Scholars]]hip for study at [[Peking University]] (2015)\n* The international [[Schwarzman Scholars]]hip for study at [[Tsinghua University]] (2016)\n* The international [[Knight-Hennessy Scholars]] to study at [[Stanford University]] (2018)\n\nIn structure and selection criteria, the scholarship is most similar to the Gates Cambridge Scholarship, Marshall Scholarship and UK Fulbright Program. Like the Rhodes, the Marshall is a two-stage geographic scholarship organised through districts in selecting countries. Like the Gates Cambridge, the Rhodes is tenable at only one university. In structure, the Marshall Scholarship is more flexible than the Rhodes Scholarship, in that Marshall Scholars can study at any British university and can also attend a different university each year during a scholar's tenure. In addition, a limited number of one-year Marshall scholarships are available. The Marshall Scholarship also places a greater emphasis on academic achievement and potential, requiring a minimum grade point average of 3.7. For example, winners of the Marshall Scholarship from [[Harvard University]] have had average [[Grading in education|GPAs]] of 3.92, while winners of the Rhodes Scholarship from Harvard have had an average GPA of 3.8.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url =http://cabot.harvard.edu/content/Post-Graduate.docx|title =Harvard Post Graduate|publisher =Harvard|url-status =dead|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20141224142940/http://cabot.harvard.edu/content/Post-Graduate.docx|archivedate =24 December 2014|df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Rhodes Scholars]]\n* [[Gates Cambridge Scholarship]]\n* [[Chevening Scholarship]]\n* [[Fulbright Scholarship]]\n* [[Marshall Scholarship]]\n* [[Clarendon Scholarship]]\n* [[Jardine Scholarship]]\n* [[Knight-Hennessy Scholars]]\n* [[Thouron Award]]\n* [[Schwarzman Scholars]]\n* [[Yenching Academy]]\n*[[Rise (education program)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Godfrey Elton, ''The First Fifty Years of The Rhodes Trust and Scholarships, 1903-1953''. London: Blackwell, 1955.\n* R.I. Rotberg, ''The Founder: Cecil Rhodes and the Pursuit of Power''. New York: Oxford University Press, 1988.\n* Philip Ziegler, ''Cecil Rhodes, the Rhodes Trust and Rhodes Scholarships''. New Haven, CT: Yale University Press, 2008.\n* [[R.W. Johnson]], ''Look Back in Laughter: Oxford's Postwar Golden Age''. Threshold Press, 2015\n\n'''Books by former Wardens of Rhodes House, Oxford:'''\n* [[Anthony Kenny]], ''The History of the Rhodes Trust''. Oxford, England: Oxford University Press, 2001.\n* [[Donald Markwell]], ''\"Instincts to Lead\": On Leadership, Peace, and Education'', 2013.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/|Rhodes Trust official website}}\n* [http://www.rhodesproject.com/ Rhodes Project: The first in-depth study of Rhodes women]\n\n{{Global Scholars Group}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rhodes Scholars| ]]\n[[Category:1902 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Awards and prizes of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1902]]\n[[Category:N M Rothschild & Sons]]\n[[Category:Rhodes House|Scholarship]]\n[[Category:Scholarships in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|An international postgraduate award for students to study at the University of Oxford}}\n{{distinguish|Road Scholar}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n[[Image:Rhodes House Oxford 20040909.jpg|right|thumb|250px|[[Rhodes House]] in [[Oxford]], designed by Sir [[Herbert Baker]]]]\n\nThe '''Rhodes Scholarship''' is an international [[Postgraduate education|postgraduate]] award for students to study at the [[University of Oxford]]. It was established in 1902, making it the first large-scale programme of international scholarship.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://files.www.rhodesscholarshiptrust.com/rhodes-trust/key-governance-documents/Rhodes_Trust_Signed_Accounts_2015.pdf|title=The Rhodes Trust Annual Report and Financial Statements for the Year Ended 30 June 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610184533/http://files.www.rhodesscholarshiptrust.com/rhodes-trust/key-governance-documents/Rhodes_Trust_Signed_Accounts_2015.pdf|archivedate=10 June 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=1 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Rhodes Scholarship was founded by English businessman and politician [[Cecil Rhodes|Cecil John Rhodes]], to promote unity between English-speaking nations and instill a sense of civic-minded leadership and moral fortitude in future leaders irrespective of their chosen career paths.<ref name=\"will\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/lastwilltestamen00rhodiala|title=The last will and testament of Cecil John Rhodes: with elucidatory notes to which are added some chapters describing the political and religious ideas of the testator|author=Cecil Rhodes & William Thomas Stead|publisher=\"Review of Reviews\" Office|year=1902}}</ref> Although initially restricted to male applicants from countries that are today within the [[British Commonwealth]], as well as Germany and the United States, today the scholarship is open to applicants from all backgrounds and from across the globe.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Rhodes |first=R. A. W.|date=2017-08-24|title=From Prime Ministerial Power to Core Executive|journal=Oxford Scholarship Online|volume=1|doi=10.1093/oso/9780198786108.003.0009}}</ref> Since its creation, [[Rhodes Scholarship#Controversies|controversy]] has surrounded its former exclusion of women (thus leading to the establishment of the co-educational [[Marshall Scholarship]]).\n\nProminent recipients of the Rhodes Scholarship include politicians, academics, scientists, authors, and entrepreneurs. Notable American political recipients include former President of the United States [[Bill Clinton]], former [[United States National Security Advisor|United States National Security Advisor]] and United States [[Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Susan Rice]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodesscholar.org/news-and-announcements/american-rhodes-scholarship-winners-2017/|title=Home {{!}} The Rhodes Scholarships|website=www.rhodesscholar.org|access-date=2018-07-05}}</ref> former Governor of Louisiana [[Bobby Jindal|Piyush \"Bobby\" Jindal]], former United States Secretary of the Air Force and former Congresswoman [[Heather Wilson]], and former United States Secretary of Health and Human Services [[Sylvia Mathews Burwell|Sylvia Matthews Burwell]]. President of Pakistan [[Wasim Sajjad]]; former Prime Minister of [[Malta]] [[Dom Mintoff]];<ref>''Maltese Biographies of The Twentieth Century'', Michael J. Schiavone, Louis J. Scerri, Malta 1997, page 412</ref> former Australian Prime Ministers [[Tony Abbott]], [[Bob Hawke]], and [[Malcolm Turnbull]]; and the current [[Deputy Prime Minister of Canada|Deputy Prime Minister of Canada]], [[Chrystia Freeland]], are also Rhodes Scholars. Other notable Rhodes Scholars include journalist and American television host [[Rachel Maddow]], author [[Naomi Wolf]], former 2020 [[United States of America|US]] presidential candidate and [[New Jersey]] Senator [[Cory Booker]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/13/795874596/cory-booker-drops-out-of-presidential-race|title=Cory Booker Drops Out Of Presidential Race|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> former 2020 [[United States of America|US]] presidential candidate and former mayor of [[South Bend, Indiana|South Bend]] [[Pete Buttigieg]], former president of Planned Parenthood [[Leana Wen]], Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist [[Ronan Farrow]], and president of the [[Walmart Foundation]] [[Kathleen McLaughlin]]. The current Warden and CEO of the Rhodes Trust, [[Elizabeth Kiss]], is also a Rhodes Scholar.<ref>\"Interview with Elizabeth Kiss\". ''Times Higher Education (THE)''. 2018-03-08. Retrieved 2018-08-03.</ref> \n\nSome people offered this scholarship have not accepted it, including Sir [[Alimuddin Zumla]], who declined the scholarship as a teenager to study medicine.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kirby|first=Tony|date=April 2013|title=Alimuddin Zumla: infectious diseases guru and survivor|journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases|volume=13|issue=4|pages=301|doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(13)70045-8|issn=1474-4457|pmid=23531387}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Founding and motivation ===\nThe [[Rhodes Trust]] established the scholarships in 1902 under the terms laid out in the sixth and final will of Cecil John Rhodes, dated 1 July 1899 and appended by several codicils through March 1902.\n\nThe scholarships were founded for two reasons: to promote unity within the British empire, and to strengthen diplomatic ties between Britain and the United States of America. In Rhodes' own words, \"I ... desire to encourage and foster an appreciation of the advantages which I implicitly believe will result from the union of the English-speaking peoples throughout the world and to encourage in the students from North America who would benefit from the American Scholarships.\"<ref name=\"will\" /> Rhodes also bequeathed scholarships to German students in the hope that, \"a good understanding between England, Germany and the United States of America will secure the peace of the world.\"\n\nRhodes, who attended [[Oriel College, Oxford]], believed the university's residential colleges would be the best venue to nurture diplomatic ties between future world leaders.\n\nTo this day, controversies persist over Rhodes\u2019 Anglo-supremacist beliefs, most of which date back to his 1877 confession of faith.<ref>For an online version, see http://pages.uoregon.edu/kimball/Rhodes-Confession.htm</ref> However, such convictions did not play a part in the final vision for the scholarship. The scholarships are based on Rhodes' final will and testament, which states that \"no student shall be qualified or disqualified for election ... on account of race or religious opinions\".<ref name=\"will\" />\n\nThe Rhodes Scholarships are administered and awarded by the Rhodes Trust, which is located at [[Rhodes House]] in Oxford. The trust has been modified by four acts of Parliament: the Rhodes Estate Act 1916, the Rhodes Trust Act 1929, the Rhodes Trust Act 1946; and most recently by the Rhodes Trust (Modification) Order 1976, a [[statutory instrument]] in accordance with Section 78 (4) of the [[Sex Discrimination Act 1975]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://files.www.rhodesscholarshiptrust.com/rhodes-trust/key-governance-documents/Rhodes_Trust_Signed_Accounts_2015.pdf|title=The Rhodes Trust Annual Report and Financial Statements for the Year Ended 30 June 2015|access-date=1 September 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610184533/http://files.www.rhodesscholarshiptrust.com/rhodes-trust/key-governance-documents/Rhodes_Trust_Signed_Accounts_2015.pdf|archivedate=10 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== After Rhodes' death ===\n\n=== 20th century ===\nIn 1925, the [[Commonwealth Fund Fellowship]]s (later renamed the [[Harkness Fellowship]]s) were established to reciprocate the Rhodes Scholarships by enabling British graduates to study in the United States.<ref name=Harkness>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.ms-ms9258 History of the Harkness Fellowships] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223320/http://nla.gov.au/nla.ms-ms9258 |date=3 March 2016 }}, nla.gov.au</ref> The [[Kennedy Scholarship]] programme, created in 1966 as a memorial to [[John F. Kennedy]], adopts a comparable selection process to the Rhodes Scholarships to allow ten British post-graduate students per year to study at either [[Harvard]] or the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT). It also cooperates with universities in China, BLCC, for example. BLCC offers high-level scholarships for international students who aim to study Chinese in Beijing. In 1953, the Parliament of the United Kingdom created the [[Marshall Scholarship]] as a coeducational alternative to the Rhodes Scholarship that would serve as a \"living gift\" to the United States.\n\nCecil Rhodes wished current scholars and Rhodes alumni (in the words of his will) to have \"opportunities of meeting and discussing their experiences and prospects\". This has been reflected, for example, in the initiation by the first warden (Sir [[Francis Wylie]]), of an annual warden's Christmas letter (now supplemented by Rhodes e-news and other communications); the creation of alumni associations in several countries, most prominently the Association of American Rhodes Scholars (which publishes ''The American Oxonian'', founded in 1914, and oversees the Eastman Professorship); and the holding of reunions for Rhodes Scholars of all countries.\n\nIn recognition of the centenary of the foundation of the Rhodes Trust in 2003, four former Rhodes Scholars were awarded [[honorary degrees]] by the University of Oxford. These were [[John Brademas]], [[Bob Hawke]] (Western Australia and [[University College, Oxford|University]] 1953), [[Rex Nettleford]] and David R. Woods. During the centenary celebrations, the foundation of the Mandela Rhodes Foundation was also marked.\n\n=== 21st century ===\nIn 2013, during the 110th Rhodes anniversary celebrations, [[John MacBain|John McCall MacBain]], Marcy McCall MacBain and the McCall MacBain Foundation donated \u00a375 million towards the fundraising efforts of the Rhodes Trust.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/474bf79c-210f-11e3-8aff-00144feab7de.html#axzz3E7w5pncy |title=McCall MacBain donation }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Rhodes Scholar [[R. W. Johnson]] published a critical account of the decline of the Rhodes Trust under its warden, [[John Rowett]], and commended its recovery under wardens [[Donald Markwell]] and [[Charles R. Conn]].<ref>R. W. Johnson, ''Look Back in Laughter: Oxford's Postwar Golden Age'', Threshold Press, 2015, especially pages 195-220.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/higher-education/feeney-hands-150m-to-rhodes/news-story/4fa2f42023af11946c55bb89650bd215|title=Feeny hands 150m to Rhodes|last=Hare|first=Julie|date=Summer 2016|work=The Australian|access-date=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, due to the introduction of the Global Rhodes Scholarships, the Rhodes Scholarship is open to [[Postgraduate education|postgraduate]] students from anywhere in the world. Many of its greatest scholars have carried out its founder\u2019s later ideal of \u201cequal rights for all civilised men\u201d becoming some of the foremost voices in [[human rights]] and [[social justice]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-320549418.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912204421/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-320549418.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2018-09-12|title=Nicholas D. Kristof to Receive Goldsmith Career Award for Excellence in Journalism |date=2013|work=States News Service|access-date=12 September 2018}}</ref> Some have even engaged in criticism of Cecil Rhodes himself (see [[Rhodes Must Fall|Rhodes must fall]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/mar/16/the-real-meaning-of-rhodes-must-fall|title=The real meaning of Rhodes Must Fall {{!}} Amit Chaudhuri|last=Chaudhuri|first=Amit|date=2016-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2018-09-12|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Because access to further education, particularly post-graduate education, is linked with [[social mobility]] and [[Racial inequality in the United States|racial wealth disparity]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2016/04/the-growing-wealth-gap-in-who-earns-college-degrees/479688/|title=The Stubborn Wealth Gap in Who Earns a College Degree|last=Zinshteyn|first=Mikhail|date=2016-04-25|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-09-12}}</ref> the scholarship (which is for post-graduate students) continues to attract criticism; however, the scholarship's recent partnership with the [[Atlantic Philanthropies]] is intended to help address those issues.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/rhodes-trust-launch-new-institute-and-expand-scholarships|title=Rhodes Trust to launch new institute and expand scholarships|date=2016-06-01|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2018-09-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, [[University of Tennessee]] graduate Hera Jay Brown became the first [[transgender woman]] to be selected for a Rhodes Scholarship. Two [[non-binary]] scholars were also selected for the 2020 class.<ref name=\"guardian-24nov2019\">{{cite news |title=First transgender Rhodes scholar named in diverse 2020 class |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2019/nov/24/first-transgender-rhodes-scholar-2020-class |accessdate=November 24, 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=November 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nbc-25nov2019\">{{cite news |last1=Aviles |first1=Gwen |title=Trans woman is first Rhodes scholar in program's 117-year history |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/trans-woman-first-rhodes-scholar-program-s-117-year-history-n1090866 |accessdate=November 25, 2019 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Selection and selectivity ==\n\n=== Selection criteria ===\nIn his will, Rhodes specified that he did not want his scholarships to go to \"merely bookworms.\" He wanted candidates assessed in regard to:\n*his literary and scholastic attainments\n*his fondness of and success in manly outdoor sports such as cricket, football and the like\n*his qualities of manhood, truth, courage, devotion to duty, sympathy for the protection of the weak, kindliness, unselfishness, and fellowship\n*his exhibition during school days of moral force of character and of instincts to lead and to take an interest in his schoolmates for those latter attributes will be likely in after-life to guide him to esteem the performance of public duty as his highest aim\n\nTo assess candidates, Rhodes specified a 200-point scale, unequally applied to each of the four areas (3/10 to each of the first and third areas, 2/10 to each of the other two areas). The first area was to be judged by examination, the second and third by ballot from the candidate's fellow students, and the fourth by the headmaster of the candidate's school. The results for each candidate would be sent to the trustees of Rhodes's will, or their appointees, who would then give a final assessment by averaging the marks for each candidate. Except for the candidates submitted by the four schools in southern Africa, the trustees were vested with the final decisions.\n\nRhodes also added that the scholars should be distributed among the Colleges at Oxford, that the trustees could remove any scholar at their discretion, and that the trustees were to host an annual dinner so scholars could discuss their \u201cexperiences and prospects.\u201d The trustees were also encouraged to invite to the dinner other \u201cpersons who have shown sympathy with the views expressed by me in this my Will.\u201d\n\nIn 2018, the same criteria underwent revision, and now specify no gender. They are now:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rhodesscholar.org/applying-for-the-scholarship/frequently-asked-questions/|title=Frequently Asked Questions - The Rhodes Scholarships|author=|date=|website=www.rhodesscholar.org}}</ref>\n\n*literary and scholastic attainments\n*energy to use one's talents to the full\n*truth, courage, devotion to duty, sympathy for and protection of the weak, kindliness, unselfishness and fellowship\n*moral force of character and instincts to lead, and to take an interest in one's fellow beings\n\nEach country's scholarship varies in its selectivity. In the United States, applicants must first pass a university-internal endorsement process, then proceed to one of the 16 U.S. districts committees. In 2016, approximately 2,500 students sought their institution's endorsement for the American Rhodes scholarship, among those 882 from 311 institutions were university-endorsed, of whom 32 were ultimately elected. As such, the American Rhodes Scholarship is more selective than the [[Churchill Scholarship]], [[Truman Scholarship]], [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright Scholarship]], [[Gates Scholarship]], and [[Mitchell Scholarship]], but marginally less selective than the [[Marshall Scholarship]] in terms of university-endorsed applicants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodesscholar.org/news-and-announcements/american-rhodes-scholarship-winners-2017/|title=American Rhodes Scholarships Winners 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=www.rhodesscholar.org|access-date=2017-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/meet-the-2014-rhodes-scholars/2013/11/26/ea276b1a-5600-11e3-835d-e7173847c7cc_story.html|title=Meet the 2014 Rhodes Scholars|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marshallscholarship.org/about/statistics|title=Statistics|website=www.marshallscholarship.org|access-date=2017-04-08}}</ref> In Canada between 1997-2002, there were an average of 234 university-endorsed applicants annually for 11 scholarships, for an acceptance rate of 4.7%. In addition, Canadian provinces differ widely in the number of applications received, with Ontario receiving 58 applications on average for 2 spots (3.4%) and Newfoundland and Labrador receiving 18 applications for 1 spot (5.7%).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yorku.ca/vpstdnts/rhodes/rhodes_background.html|title=York University {{!}} Division of Students {{!}} Rhodes Scholarship|website=www.yorku.ca|access-date=2016-09-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124073554/http://www.yorku.ca/vpstdnts/rhodes/rhodes_background.html|archivedate=24 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to the Rhodes Trust, the overall global acceptance rate stands at 0.7%, making it one of the most competitive scholarships in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://files.www.rhodesscholarshiptrust.com/china-additional-materials/Rhodes_Factsheet_-_FINAL_-_EN.pdf|title=The Rhodes Scholarship Fact Sheet|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415013335/http://files.www.rhodesscholarshiptrust.com/china-additional-materials/Rhodes_Factsheet_-_FINAL_-_EN.pdf|archivedate=15 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAn early change was the elimination of the scholarships for Germany during the [[World War I|First]] and [[World War II|Second]] [[World Wars]]. No German scholars were chosen from 1914 to 1929, nor from 1940 to 1969.<ref name=numbers>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/RhodesScholars.htm |title=Lists of Rhodes Scholars }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Rhodes's bequest was whittled down considerably in the first decades after his death, as various scholarship trustees were forced to pay taxes upon their own deaths.{{citation needed|date=June 2012}} A change occurred in 1929, when an [[Act of Parliament]] established a fund separate from the original proceeds of Rhodes's will and made it possible to expand the number of scholarships. Between 1993 and 1995, scholarships were extended to other countries in the [[European Community]].\n\n=== Scholarship terms ===\nRhodes Scholars may study any full-time postgraduate course offered by the university,<ref>Periodically the Rhodes Trustees include or exclude the MBA from the courses offered.</ref> whether a taught master's programme, a research degree, or a second undergraduate degree (senior status). In the first instance, the scholarship is awarded for two years. However, it may also be held for one year or three years. Applications for a third year are considered during the course of the second year. University and college fees are paid by the [[Rhodes Trust]]. In addition, scholars receive a monthly maintenance [[stipend]] to cover accommodation and living expenses.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Rhodes Trust |year=2009 |url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/section/faqs |title=FAQs about the Scholarships |accessdate=6 December 2010 |quote=In 2009, the stipend was UKPounds 958/month |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716232221/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/section/faqs |archivedate=16 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite pressrelease |first=Elliot F. |last=Gerson |url= http://www.rhodesscholar.org/get/5/2009_Press_Release_For_Website.pdf |title=From the Office of the American Secretary |date=21 November 2009 |accessdate=6 December 2010 |quote=Amongst other things, the press release states that the value of the Rhodes Scholarship varies depending on the academic field and the degree (B.A., master's, doctoral) chosen. For American Rhodes Scholars, Gerson estimates that the total value of the scholarship <u>averages</u> approximately US$50,000 per year, or up to as much as US$175,000 for scholars who remain in Oxford for four years.}}</ref> Although all scholars become affiliated with a [[residential college]] while at Oxford, they also enjoy access to [[Rhodes House]], an early 20th-century mansion with numerous public rooms, gardens, a library, study areas, and other facilities.\n\n== Allocation of scholarships ==\n{{Main|Allocation of Rhodes Scholarships}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:97%; text-align:center\" align=\"right\"\n!Geographic<br />constituency\n!2018<br />allocation<br />\n!1902<br />allocation<br /><ref name=will/><ref name=numbers/>\n|-\n!Australia<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sydney.edu.au/rhodes/ |title=The Rhodes Scholarships in Australia |accessdate=6 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101219160112/http://sydney.edu.au/rhodes/ |archivedate=19 December 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sydney.edu.au/rhodes/ |title=Australian Rhodes Scholarships |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101219160112/http://sydney.edu.au/rhodes/ |archivedate=19 December 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|9 ||6\n|-\n!Bermuda<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodes.bm |title=The Rhodes Scholarships in Bermuda }}</ref>\n|1 ||1\n|-\n!Canada<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canadian-rhodes-scholars.ca/index.html |title=The Canadian Association of Rhodes Scholars |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070706202454/http://www.canadian-rhodes-scholars.ca/index.html |archivedate=6 July 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|11 ||2\n|-\n!China\n|4 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!East Africa \n|1 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!Newfoundland\n|&nbsp;\u2014 ||1\n|-\n!Germany<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodes-deutschland.de |title=The Rhodes Scholarships in Germany }}</ref>\n|2 ||5\n|-\n!Hong Kong\n|1 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!India<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodesscholarships-india.com |title=The Rhodes Scholarships in India |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228182955/http://www.rhodesscholarships-india.com/ |archivedate=28 December 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodesindia.com/ |title=Indian Rhodes Scholarships }}</ref>\n|5 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!Israel\n|2 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!Jamaica & the<br />Commonwealth<br />Caribbean<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodes-caribbean.com |title=The Rhodes Scholarships for Jamaica & the Commonwealth Caribbean }}</ref>\n|2 ||1\n|-\n!Kenya\n|2 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!Malaysia\n|1 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!New Zealand<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzvcc.ac.nz/default.aspx?l=4&p=64 |title=The Rhodes Scholarships in New Zealand |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050830140725/http://www.nzvcc.ac.nz/default.aspx?l=4&p=64 |archivedate=30 August 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzvcc.ac.nz/scholarships/rhodes |title=New Zealand Vice-Chancellors' Committee page on Rhodes Scholarships }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/1966/R/RhodesScholarships/RhodesScholarships/en |title=New Zealand Rhodes Scholars, listed for 1903 to 1964 }}</ref>\n|3 ||1\n|-\n!Pakistan\n|1 ||&nbsp;1\n|-\n!Singapore\n|1 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!Southern Africa<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodestrust.org.za |title=The Rhodes Scholarships in South Africa }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodescentenary.co.za/Mandela_frame.htm |title=The Mandela Rhodes Foundation in South Africa |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031009131713/http://www.rhodescentenary.co.za/Mandela_frame.htm |archivedate=9 October 2003 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|10 ||5\n|-\n!Syria, Jordan,<br />Lebanon & Palestine\n|2 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!United Arab Emirates\n|2 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!United States<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodesscholar.org |title=The Rhodes Trust, USA }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.americanrhodes.org/ |title=Association of American Rhodes Scholars }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usna.edu/Admissions/Notables/RhodesScholars/index.htm/ |title=United States Naval Academy Rhodes Scholars |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070325201935/http://www.usna.edu/Admissions/Notables/RhodesScholars/index.htm/ |archivedate=25 March 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|32 ||32\n|-\n!West Africa\n|2 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n!Zambia &<br>Zimbabwe<br><small>(formerly Rhodesia)</small>\n|2<br>2<br>\u2014 ||&nbsp;\u2014<br>\u2014<br>3\n|-\n!Global scholarships\n|2 ||&nbsp;\u2014\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n!Total !!100 !!58\n|-\n|}\n\nThere were originally 58 scholarships.<ref name=will/><ref name=numbers/>\n\nFour [[South Africa]]n boys' schools were mentioned in Rhodes' will, each to receive an annual scholarship: the [[Paul Roos Gymnasium|Boys High School]] in [[Stellenbosch]] (today known as Paul Roos Gymnasium); the [[Diocesan College]] (Bishops) in [[Rondebosch]]; the [[South African College Schools]] (SACS) in [[Newlands, Cape Town|Newlands]]; and [[St. Andrew's College (South Africa)|St Andrew's College]] in [[Grahamstown]]. These have subsequently been opened also to former students of their partner schools (girls' or co-educational schools).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/southern-africa|title=The Rhodes Scholarships for Southern Africa (including South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Namibia and Swaziland)|website=The Rhodes Scholarships|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref>\n\nDuring the ensuing 100 years, the trustees have added about another 40 scholarships at one time or another, though not all have continued. Some of these extended the scheme to Commonwealth countries not mentioned in the will.<ref name=\"BriefHistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/history.htm|title=Brief history of the Rhodes Trust|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206130239/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/history.htm|archivedate=6 February 2007}}</ref> A more detailed allocation by region by year can be found at [[Rhodes Scholarship Allocations]]. Very brief summaries of some of the terms and conditions can be found on the trust's website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/faq.htm |title=Rhodes Scholarship FAQ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613000940/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/faq.htm |archivedate=13 June 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/infoscholar.htm |title=Information about the Scholarships |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070305220039/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/infoscholar.htm |archivedate=5 March 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Complete details can be obtained from the nominating countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/countries_complete.htm |title=Country Websites and Information |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702180155/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/countries_complete.htm |archivedate=2 July 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, scholars are selected from over 20 Rhodes constituencies (64 different countries) worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/scholarship/how-to-apply-for-a-rhodes-scholarship/ |title=How to Apply|website=Rhodes Trust|date=2017|author= |accessdate= 17 August 2017}}</ref> In 2015, the Rhodes Scholarship extended into new territories, first with the announcement of a number of scholarships for [[China]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/news/chinalaunch|title=The Rhodes Trust announces the launch of Rhodes Scholarships for China|access-date=2016-09-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161226095857/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/news/chinalaunch|archivedate=26 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> later with the announcement of one to two scholarships per year for the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/news/uae-launch|title=Launch of Rhodes Scholarships for the United Arab Emirates Announced|access-date=2016-09-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923223946/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/news/uae-launch|archivedate=23 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The organisation administering the scholarships is preparing to begin naming scholars from China. The move into China is the biggest expansion since women became eligible in the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/31/world/asia/rhodes-scholarships-expanding-to-include-chinese-students.html|title=Rhodes Scholarships Expanding to Include Chinese Students|last=Barboza|first=David|date=2015-03-30|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n=== Exclusion of women ===\nThe Rhodes Scholarship was originally, as per the language used in Rhodes's will, open only to \"male students\".  That stipulation would not change until 1977. Rhodes developed his scholarships partly through conversation with [[William Thomas Stead]], editor of ''[[The Pall Mall Gazette]]'' and confidant of Rhodes, and at one time an executor of the Will who was stricken from the role when he objected to Rhodes's ill-fated effort to seize the [[Transvaal Colony|Transvaal]]. Shortly after Rhodes's death, Stead implied in a published article about the Will that he suggested that Rhodes open the scholarships to women.<ref>William Thomas Stead, \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=h2ZPAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA609&lpg=PA609&dq=mr.+rhodes%27s+will+and+its+genesis+stead&source=bl&ots=dlaGVFpnWK&sig=A4PK-gC5Ui7AitbMuBM-ECRaOqA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiluoqGm7bdAhVHNd8KHRJpBwoQ6AEwAXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=mr.%20rhodes's%20will%20and%20its%20genesis%20stead&f=false Mr. Rhodes\u2019s Will and Its Genesis]\", p. 479, ''The Review of Reviews'' 25, pp. 471\u201382</ref>  But Rhodes refused. Nothing more is said on the matter.\n\nAfter his death, the will was under the control of the Board of Trustees of the Rhodes Trust. In 1916, however, the trustees introduced a bill into the House of Commons that, catering to popular British sentiment during the [[World War I|War]], \"revoked and annulled\" the scholarships for Germans.<ref>See [[Angela Stent]], \"The Women's Bid for a Rhodes\", ''Change'', Vol. 6, No. 5 (June 1974), pp 13.16.</ref> Since then, legal control over the will has resided with Parliament.\n\nIn 1970, the trustees established the Rhodes Visiting Fellowships. Unlike the regular scholarship, a Visiting Fellow was expected to have a doctorate or comparable degree, and to use the two-year funded study to engage in independent research. Only 33 Visiting Fellowships were awarded.<ref>See [http://www.otago.ac.nz/library/exhibitions/rhodes_scholars/rhodes_women.html \"Rhodes Visiting Fellowships for Women\"].</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Parliament passed the [[Sex Discrimination Act 1975|Sex Discrimination Act of 1975]] that banned discrimination based on sex, including in education.  The trustees then applied to the Secretary of State for Education to admit women into the scholarship, and in 1976 the request was granted.<ref>Philip Ziegler, ''Legacy: Cecil Rhodes, the Rhodes Trust and Rhodes Scholarships'', 2008, Yale University Press, p. 221.</ref> In 1977, women were finally admitted to the full scholarship. To a large degree, this change was the result of the advances of the feminist movement as well as the importance of [[Title IX]] legislation in the United States that made illegal sex discrimination in colleges that received federal financial assistance.\n\nBefore Parliament passed the 1975 Act, some universities protested against the exclusion of women by nominating female candidates, who were later disqualified at the state level of the American competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1973/10/6/harvard-endorses-3-women-for-male-restricted/|title=Harvard Endorses 3 Women For Male-Restricted Rhodes {{!}} News {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref> In 1977, the first year women were eligible, 24 women (out of 72 total scholars) were selected worldwide, with 13 women and 19 men selected from the United States.<ref name=WomenScholars>[https://archive.today/20121210090918/http://therhodesproject.wordpress.com/2010/01/29/second-class-citizens-how-women-became-rhodes-scholars/ \"Second-class citizens: How women became Rhodes Scholars\"], 29 January 2010, therhodesproject.wordpress.com</ref> Since then, the average female share of the scholarship in the United States had been around 35 percent.<ref name=WomenScholars/>\n\nIn his 2008 book ''Legacy: Cecil Rhodes, the Rhodes Trust and Rhodes Scholarship'' ([[Yale University Press]]), biographer and historian [[Philip Ziegler]] writes that \"The advent of women does not seem notably to have affected the balance of Scholars among the various professions, though it has reduced the incidence of worldly success.\"  The idea has persisted that women Rhodes Scholars are less successful overall than their male peers. But the Rhodes Project<ref>[http://rhodesproject.com/ The Rhodes Project]</ref> seeks to challenge this idea.<ref>See \"30 Years of Rhodes Women\" (https://www.americanrhodes.org/assets/attachments/347.pdf).</ref>\n\nIn South Africa, the will of Cecil Rhodes expressly allocated scholarships to four all-male private schools. In 1992, one of the four schools partnered with an all-girls school in order to allow female applicants. In 2012, the three remaining schools followed suit to allow women to apply.<ref name=\"rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/news/south-african-schools-scholarships|title=New partnerships for South African schools' Rhodes Scholarships|access-date=2016-09-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123172624/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/news/south-african-schools-scholarships|archivedate=23 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Today, four of the nine scholarships allocated to South Africa are open only to students and alumni of these schools and partner schools.<ref name=\"rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk\"/>\n\n=== Exclusion of black Africans ===\nRhodes clearly specified in the will that \"No student shall be qualified or disqualified for election to a Scholarship on account of his race or religious opinions.\" Rhodes often in his writings used the word \"race\" with reference to black Africans, what he called \"natives\". In the context of the historical era, it would have been entirely out of character for Rhodes, and seen as absurd by the trustees and Oxford, to suggest that some of the scholarships might go to Africans. Furthermore, as Rhodes himself knew, and as Oxford University insisted in the early years of the scholarships, all applicants for the scholarship were required to pass the entrance exam for Oxford, or its equivalent, called [[Responsions]], which included ancient Greek and Latin. It would have been highly unusual for any Africans in that era to be admitted into those European schools in southern Africa that taught such subjects. Rhodes's scholarships intentionally excluded women and Africans, and those stipulations were followed carefully in the implementation<ref>E.g., Tim Nuttall, 2001, \"A Century of South African Rhodes Scholarships\", in A. Kenny, ed., ''The History of the Rhodes Trust 1902\u20131999'', Oxford University Press, pp. 251\u2013314</ref> Nothing in the will or in any of Rhodes' other writings suggests his desire to educate non-Europeans. In fact, the four South African schools named by Rhodes only admitted whites, and would not open their doors to black Africans until the end of [[apartheid]] in the early 1990s.\n\nBeginning in 1970, scholars began protesting against the fact that all Rhodes Scholars from southern Africa were white, with 120 Oxford dons and 80 of the 145 Rhodes Scholars in residence at the time signing a petition calling for non-white scholars to be elected in 1971.<ref name=\"Schaeper\">Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. ''Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite'', 2010. Berghahn Books: New York</ref>{{rp|238}} The case of South Africa was especially difficult to resolve, because in his will establishing the scholarships, unlike for other constituencies, Rhodes specifically allocated four scholarships to alumni of four white-only private secondary schools. According to Schaeper and Schaeper,<ref name=\"Schaeper\" />{{rp|236\u2013237}} the issue became \"explosive\" in the 1970s and 1980s as scholars argued that the scholarship be changed while the trustees argued they were powerless to change the will. Despite such protests, only in 1991 with the rise of the [[African National Congress]] did black South Africans begin to win the scholarships.<ref name=\"Schaeper\" />{{rp|240}}\n\n=== Criticism of Rhodes as colonialist ===\n{{see also|Rhodes Must Fall|Cecil Rhodes#Political Views}}\n\nPublic criticism of the scholarship has also focused on Cecil Rhodes's [[white supremacist]] views. For example, in 1966, regional committees in interviews asked a white American candidate to assure them he would not publicly belittle the scholarship after he referred to its founding on \"blood money\".<ref name=\"Schaeper\" />{{rp|238}} In 2015, a South African Rhodes Scholar, [[Ntokozo Qwabe]], began a campaign to address Rhodes' [[Cecil Rhodes#Political Views|controversial historical and political legacy]], with a focus on Qwabe\u2019s own views which included such statements as \"dismantling the open glorification of colonial genocide in educational and other public spaces \u2013 which makes it easy for British people to believe that these genocides were 'not that bad' \u2013 and props up the continuing structural legacies of British colonialism, neocolonialism, and ongoing imperialism\".<ref name=\"cherwell.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cherwell.org/2015/12/23/oxford-rhodes-scholar-attacked-for-quothypocrisyquot/|title=Oxford Rhodes scholar attacked for \"hypocrisy\"|last=Foxton|first=Hannah|date=2015-12-23|website=Cherwell.org|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref> Among other things, the campaign called for the removal of a statue of Rhodes from Oriel College and changes to Oxford's curriculum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2015/jun/18/oxford-uni-must-decolonise-its-campus-and-curriculum-say-students|title=Oxford Uni must decolonise its campus and curriculum, say students|last=Rhoden-Paul|first=Andr\u00e9|date=2015-06-18|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref> While the college agreed to review the placement of the statue, the Chancellor of the university, Lord Patten, was critical of the accuracy of Qwabe\u2019s statements and warned against \"pandering to contemporary views\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/universityeducation/12094277/Cecil-Rhodes-Oxford-University-students-must-confront-views-they-find-objectionable-says-new-head.html|title=Cecil Rhodes: Lord Patten warns against 'pandering to contemporary views' over statue row|access-date=2016-09-01|date=2016-01-13|last1=Espinoza|first1=Javier}}</ref>\n\nA group of Rhodes Scholars also created the group Redress Rhodes whose mission was to \"attain a more critical, honest, and inclusive reflection of the legacy of Cecil John Rhodes\" and to \"make reparative justice a more central theme for Rhodes Scholars.\" Their demands include, among other things, shifting the Rhodes Scholarships awarded exclusively to previously all-white South African schools (rather than the at-large national pool), dedicating a \"space at Rhodes House for the critical engagement with Cecil Rhodes' legacy, as well as imperial history\", and ending a ceremonial toast Rhodes Scholars make to the founder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/redress-rhodes|title=Redress Rhodes|website=The Rhodes Scholarships|access-date=2016-09-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923213857/http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/redress-rhodes|archivedate=23 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While the group does not have a position on the removal of the statue, its co-founder has called for the scholarship to be renamed as it is \"the ultimate form of veneration and colonial apologism; it's a large part of why many continue to understand Rhodes as a benevolent founder and benefactor.\"<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2016/jan/12/cecil-rhodes-scholars-reject-hypocrisy-claims-amid-row-over-oriel-college-statue|title=Oxford scholars reject hypocrisy claims amid row over Cecil Rhodes statue|last=Khomami|first=Nadia|date=2016-01-13|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref>\n\nPublic criticism has also focused on the alleged hypocrisy of applying for and accepting the Rhodes Scholarship while criticizing it, with University of Cambridge academic [[Mary Beard (classicist)|Mary Beard]], writing in ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'', arguing that Scholars \"[could not] have your cake and eat it here: I mean you can't whitewash Rhodes out of history, but go on using his cash.\"<ref name=\"cherwell.org\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/12062808/Rhodes-scholar-branded-hypocrite-for-leading-campaign-to-have-Rhodes-statue-removed-criticised-by-Mary-Beard.html|title=Rhodes scholar branded hypocrite for leading campaign to have Rhodes' statue removed criticised by Mary Beard|access-date=2016-09-01|date=2015-12-21|last1=Espinoza|first1=Javier}}</ref> Reacting to this criticism, Qwabe replied that \"all that [Rhodes] looted must absolutely be returned immediately. I'm no beneficiary of Rhodes. I'm a beneficiary of the resources and labour of my people which Rhodes pillaged and slaved.\"<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/12060780/Oxford-student-who-wants-Rhodes-statue-down-branded-hypocrite-for-taking-money-from-trust.html|title=Oxford student who wants Rhodes statue down branded 'hypocrite' for taking money from trust|access-date=2016-09-01|date=2015-12-21|last1=Espinoza|first1=Javier}}</ref> A group of 198 Rhodes Scholars of various years later signed a statement supporting Qwabe and arguing that there was \"no hypocrisy in being a recipient of a Rhodes scholarship and being publicly critical of Cecil Rhodes and his legacy \u2013 a legacy that continues to alienate, silence, exclude and dehumanise in unacceptable ways. There is no clause that binds us to find 'the good' in Rhodes' character, nor to sanitise the imperialist, colonial agenda he propagated.\"<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/>\n\n=== Criticism over recipients not entering public service ===\nThe tendency of a growing number of Rhodes Scholars to enter business or private law, as opposed to public service for which the scholarship was intended, has been a source of frequent criticism and \"occasional embarrassment\".<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. \"Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite,\" 2010. Berghahn Books: New York, pp. 300-302.</ref> Writing in 2009, the Secretary of the Rhodes Trust criticised the trend of Rhodes Scholars to pursue careers in finance and business, noting that \"more than twice as many [now] went into business in just one year than did in the entire 1970s\", attributing it to \"grotesque\" remuneration offered by such occupations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/11/20/AR2009112003374.html|title=Losing Rhodes scholars to Wall Street's siren call|last=Gerson|first=Elliot|date=2009-11-21|newspaper=The Washington Post|issn=0190-8286|access-date=2016-09-01}}</ref> At least \"a half dozen\" 1990s Rhodes Scholars became partners at [[Goldman Sachs]] and, since the 1980s, [[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey]] has had numerous Rhodes Scholars as partners. Similarly, of Rhodes Scholars who became attorneys, about one-third serve as staff attorneys for private corporations, while another third remain in private practice or academic posts.<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. \"Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite,\" 2010. Berghahn Books: New York, p. 302.</ref>\n\nAccording to Schaeper and Schaper,<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. \"Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite,\" 2010. Berghahn Books: New York, p. 280.</ref> \"From 1904 to the present, the programme's critics have had two main themes: first, that too many scholars were content with comfortable, safe jobs in academe, in law, and in business; second, that too few had careers in government or other fields where public service was the number-one goal.\" [[Andrew Sullivan]] wrote in 1988 that \"of the 1,900 or so living American scholars ... about 250 fill middle-rank administrative and professorial positions in middle-rank state colleges and universities ... [while] another 260...have ended up as lawyers.\"<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. \"Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite,\" 2010. Berghahn Books: New York, p. 282.</ref>\n\n=== Quality of post-graduate education at Oxford ===\nIn 2007, an [[op-ed]] in [[The Harvard Crimson]] by two American Rhodes Scholars<ref name=\"DellMylavarapBlues\">{{cite news |last1=Dell |first1=Melissa |last2=Mylavarap |first2=Swati |title=Oxford Blues |url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2007/2/25/oxford-blues-to-all-juniors-out/ |accessdate=7 June 2019 |work=[[The Harvard Crimson]] |date=February 25, 2007}}</ref> caused an \"international row over Oxford's status as a top university\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/news/1234879.Uninspired_scholars_attack_university/|title=Uninspired scholars attack university|website=The Oxford Times}}</ref> when they criticized the university's post-graduate education as \"outdated\" and \"frustrating\" in comparison to their education in the United States, specifically pointing to the perceived low quality of instruction and an insufficient scholarship stipend for living expenses. They also criticized the Rhodes application process itself, arguing that potential applicants should not apply unless they are \"ready to study and live in Oxford.\"<ref name=\"DellMylavarapBlues\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2007/3/16/the-rhodes-and-harvard-opportunity-not/|title=The Rhodes and Harvard: Opportunity, Not Obligation - Opinion - The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com}}</ref>\n\nThe original op-ed<ref name=\"DellMylavarapBlues\"/> spurred responses on both sides of the Atlantic.<ref>{{cite magazine | first=Elizabeth | last=Green | title=Harvard Rhodes Winners are Whiners, say Yale kids | magazine=US News & World Report  | date=9 April 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | first=Elizabeth | last=Green | title=Rhodes Scholars Say Oxford's Overrated | magazine=US News & World Report  | date=February 28, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first=Christine | last=Finn | title=Rhodes scholars give Oxford D-minus | newspaper=The Sunday Times  | date=4 March 2007}}</ref> Other students criticised the authors for their tone of \"ingratitude and entitlement,\" while ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' noted that it fueled the \"long rivalry between Harvard, Cambridge and Oxford\" and existing concerns about the quality of British graduate education. In response, the Rhodes Trust released two statements, one to ''The'' ''Sunday Times'' saying that \"the criticisms ... are unrepresentative of the vast majority of Americans\" studying at Oxford,<ref>{{cite news | first=Elliot | last=Gerson | title=Oxford Popularity - Letter | newspaper=The Sunday Times  | date=11 March 2007}}</ref> and another as a reply to the original op-ed arguing that \"false expectations,\" particularly for those uncertain about their degree choice, and going to Oxford for the \"wrong reasons,\" could contribute to dissatisfaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2007/3/2/oxford-is-about-transitions-and-not/|title=Oxford Is About Transitions And Not For Everyone - Opinion - The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com}}</ref>\n\n== Notable scholars and career trajectories ==\n{{see also|List of Rhodes Scholars}}\nSurveying the history of the Rhodes Scholarship, Schaeper and Schaeper conclude<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. ''Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite'', Berghahn Books: New York, 2010 p. 314.</ref> that while \"few of them have 'changed the world' ... most of them have been a credit to their professions ... and communities\", finding that \"the great majority of Rhodes Scholars have had solid, respectable careers.\" Eight former Rhodes scholars subsequently became heads of government or heads of [[sovereign state|state]], including [[Wasim Sajjad]] (Pakistan), [[Bill Clinton]] (United States), [[Dom Mintoff]] (Malta), [[John Turner]] (Canada), [[Norman Manley]] (Jamaica) and three Australian Prime Ministers: [[Bob Hawke]], [[Tony Abbott]] and [[Malcolm Turnbull]].\n\nFrom 1951 to 1997, 32% of American Rhodes Scholars pursued careers in education and academia, 20% in law, 15% in business and 10% in medicine and science.<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. ''Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite'', Berghahn Books: New York, 2010, p. 279.</ref> Although Cecil Rhodes imagined that scholars would \"pursue a full-time career in government [...] the number of scholars in local, state and federal government has remained at a steady 7 percent\" over the past century. Of the 200 or so scholars who have spent their careers in government, \"most of them have had solid, but undistinguished careers,\" while \"perhaps forty or more can be said to have had a significant, national impact in their particular areas.\"<ref>Schaeper, Thomas and Kathleen Schaeper. \"Rhodes Scholars: Oxford, and the Creation of an American Elite,\" 2010. Berghahn Books: New York, p. 311.</ref>\n\nThe highest-ranking career choice for Rhodes Scholars is education and academia, with many becoming deans of law and medical schools and others becoming professors and lecturers. Many of the most distinguished Rhodes Scholars, such as Zambian activist [[Lucy Banda-Sichone|Lucy Banda]], have become prominent members of the civil rights movement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/zambian-activist-lucy-banda-becomes-first-female-rhodes-scholar-to-have-portrait-displayed-at-oxford-a6766946.html|title=The first ever portrait of a female Rhodes scholar has been unveiled|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> In 1990, third-wave feminist author Naomi Wolf put forward ideas about beauty and power with her book ''[[The Beauty Myth]]'', ushering in a new type of feminism that has risen to prominence in the digital age.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/oct/18/classics.shopping|title=Women: A quick reminder ... The Beauty Myth by Naomi Wolf|last=Wilson|first=Emily|date=2005-10-18|website=the Guardian|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\nRhodes Scholars have had a notable impact in the fields of medicine and science. Howard Florey was awarded a Rhodes Scholarship in 1922 after studying medicine at Adelaide Medical school. In 1939 Florey, along with fellow scientist [[Ernst Chain|Ernst Boris Chain]], led the team that successfully isolated and purified penicillin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1945/florey/biographical/|title=The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 1945|website=NobelPrize.org|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Human rights, social justice and advocacy ===\n\n==== Law ====\nChallenging some of the convictions of the scholarship's founder is not a recent occurrence. As early as 1931, [[Afrikaans]]-born anti-apartheid lawyer Bram Fischer and Rhodes Scholar campaigned for equal rights for all South Africans. This led him to join the [[Communist Party of South Africa]]. Fischer was struck off the roll by the Johannesburg Bar Council in 1965 after he skipped bail on charges under the Suppression of Communism Act. He was later arrested and sentenced to life in prison.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nelsonmandela.org/news/entry/bram-fischer-a-hero-born-100-years-ago|title=Bram Fischer: a hero born 100 years ago \u2013 Nelson Mandela Foundation|website=www.nelsonmandela.org|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> Other Rhodes Scholars have taken on difficult social causes with more success. In 1980, former Rhodes Scholar [[Ann Olivarius]] sued Yale University over their mis-handling of on-campus sexual harassment complaints.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/womens-life/11632346/Sex-harassment-in-British-universities-What-date-rape-inventor-thinks.html|title=What the woman who coined the term \u2018date rape\u2019 thinks of British universities|last=Goldhill|first=Olivia|date=2015-05-27|access-date=2018-11-23|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/womens-life/11570529/Revenge-porn-This-sexual-crime-can-be-stopped-with-street-tactics.html|title=Revenge porn: 'Street tactics' can stamp out this industrial scale sexual crime|last=Olivarius|first=Dr Ann|date=2015-05-11|access-date=2018-11-23|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==== Education and child welfare ====\nAfter leaving Oxford to write his first novel, former Rhodes Scholar [[Jonathan Kozol]] volunteered as a teacher in [[Roxbury, Boston]]. He would go on to write ''Death at an Early Age: The Destruction of the Hearts and Minds of Negro Children in the Boston Public Schools,'' after witnessing first-hand the devastating effect educational inequality was having on America.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2007-01-01|title=Kozol, Jonathan|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-2587100047.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124055047/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-2587100047.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2018-11-24}}</ref> Rhodes Scholars Marc Kielburger and Roxanne Joyal conduct similar work with their organisation Free the Children. Together they build schools and educate children in developing countries across Africa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/life/2009/03/09/their_love_is_built_on_helping_others.html|title=Their love is built on helping others {{!}} The Star|work=thestar.com|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Civil and human rights ====\nMuch of the Rhodes Alumni's civil and human rights work has been focussed in Africa, particularly South Africa. South African Justice Edwin Cameron initially focussed his attention on law and employment law, but later worked in the field of LGBT rights as well as co-founding the Aids Consortium. Two-time Pulitzer-winning journalist [[Nicholas Kristof|Nick Kristof]] was pivotal in shedding light on atrocities such as Tiananmen Square and the genocide in Darfur.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/column/nicholas-kristof|title=Nicholas Kristof|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> Professor [[Sandra Fredman]] has also written extensively on anti-discrimination law, human rights law and labour law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://denning.law.ox.ac.uk/members/profile.php?lecturer_code=fredmans|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121223021844/http://denning.law.ox.ac.uk/members/profile.php?lecturer_code=fredmans|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-12-23|title=Oxford Law :: Profile of Sandra Fredman|date=2012-12-23|work=archive.is|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> [[Rhiana Gunn-Wright]] was the creator of the [[Green New Deal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060107485|title=CLIMATE: Meet the scholar crafting the 'Green New Deal'|website=www.eenews.net|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Medical innovation ===\n\n==== Genetics ====\nIn 2014, Iranian Rhodes Scholar and front-person for [[Indie rock|indie-rock]] band Thousand Days, [[Pardis Sabeti]], used genome sequencing and computational genetics to identify the source of the 2014 Ebola outbreak in West Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/news-opinion/ebola-outbreak-strains-sequenced-36944|title=Ebola Outbreak Strains Sequenced|website=The Scientist Magazine\u00ae|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\nAnother Rhodes Scholar working in [[genome]] research is the mathematician and geneticist [[Eric Lander]]. His ideas in human genetics, particularly mapping and sequencing, led to the creation of [[the Cancer Genome Atlas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2018-07/asoh-ahe071018.php|title=ASHG honors Eric S. Lander with William Allan Award|website=EurekAlert!|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Disease and epidemiology ====\nDr Salem Yusef, an Indian scholar, conducted significant research into respiratory health and its relationship to developing economies. He observed that shifts in the developing world, particularly dietary changes and increased urbanisation, lead to higher incidences of heart attacks and strokes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.anzishaprize.org/mentors-judges/yusuf-randera-rees/|title=Celebrating Africa's Youngest Entrepreneurs {{!}} Yusuf Randera-Rees|website=www.anzishaprize.org|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\nIn Zimbabwe, Dr A Tariro Makadzange has researched perinatally infected children with HIV and HIV-positive adults with cryptococcal disease. Since graduating from Oxford, she has set up a new infectious disease laboratory at the University of Zimbabwe in Harare.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ragoninstitute.org/makadzange-opens-new-lab-in-zimbabwe/|title=Makadzange Opens New Lab in Zimbabwe|date=2014-06-24|work=Ragon Institute of MGH, MIT and Harvard|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Surgery ====\nAfter studying at Oxford, surgeon and author [[Atul Gawande]] became an advisor to Bill Clinton and the U.S Department of Health and Human Services.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2008-01-01|title=Gawande, Atul 1965- (Atul A. Gawande)|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3057000057.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124055108/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3057000057.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2018-11-24}}</ref> In recent years he has devised an innovative checklist for a successful surgery.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2011/10/03/personal-best|title=The Coach in the Operating Room|work=The New Yorker|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=122226184|title=Atul Gawande's 'Checklist' For Surgery Success|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> Other surgical innovations brought about by Rhodes Scholars include the GliaSite technique, a device that lowers the risks associated with radiation therapy in brain tumours. Neurosurgeon Griffith Harsh created the GliaSite device.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.stanford.edu/news/2001/november14/gliasite.html|title=New device delivers safer, targeted brain tumor treatment straight to the source: 11/01|website=news.stanford.edu|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n=== The arts ===\n\n==== Literature ====\nOne of the first recipients of the Rhodes Scholarship was the American poet, educator and critic [[John Crowe Ransom]]. He became a founding member of the influential Fugitive literary group.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rubin|first=Louis D.|date=1974|title=The Wary Fugitive John Crowe Ransom|journal=The Sewanee Review|volume=82|issue=4|pages=583\u2013618|jstor=27542882}}</ref> A contemporary of Ransom's who also became a Rhodes Scholar was [[Robert Penn Warren]]. Warren was lambasted by his peers who told him that the study of English literature was a soft option; seeking to rebut such attacks, he introduced new critical ideas into the study of poetry and fiction, and these ideas went on to change how literature was taught at undergraduate and postgraduate levels, not only in America itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.english.illinois.edu/maps/poets/m_r/ransom/life.htm|title=John Crowe Ransom's Life and Career|website=www.english.illinois.edu|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Hip-hop ====\nIn 2006 (before receiving a Rhodes Scholarship), lawyer and current Democratic Congressman [[Antonio Delgado (politician)|Antonio Delgado]] critiqued capitalism and racial injustice under the name \"AD the Voice\"; arguably, however, his most significant contribution to [[hip-hop]] is not his music but the community outreach work he does in [[New York's 19th congressional district]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/17/us/politics/antonio-delgado-lyrics.html|title=A Congressional Candidate Used to Be a Rapper. Will It Matter?|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\nRoughly 90 years prior, the phrase \u201ckeeping it real\u201d was used by Rhodes scholar [[Alain Locke]] in his book ''The New Negro,'' to describe the pursuit of in the face of mainstream media's portrayal of African American culture.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The New negro|last=Locke|first=Alain|date=1997|publisher=Simon & Schuster|isbn=978-0684838311|edition= 1st Touchstone|location=New York, N.Y.|oclc=37551618}}</ref> Locke's work inspired the [[Harlem Renaissance]] movement, and \u201ckeeping it real\u201d has since become a universally recognised hip-hop ethos.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Price|first=Robert Jr|date=2005|title=Hegemony, Hope, and the Harlem Renaissance: Taking Hip Hop Culture Seriously|url=https://newprairiepress.org/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.com/&httpsredir=1&article=2681&context=aerc|journal=Kansas State University Libraries|volume=|pages=|via=newprairiepress.org}}</ref>\n\n=== Science and technology ===\n\n==== Space exploration ====\nAfter studying ion propulsion at Oxford, Dr. Jennifer Gruber embarked on a career as a space engineer. She is currently coordinating missions between the Johnson Space Center and the International Space Station as an employee of NASA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailynebraskan.com/omaha-native-chosen-as-rhodes-scholar/article_e7feb834-dbc6-5e0f-ad54-1692b7c97538.html|title=Omaha native chosen as Rhodes scholar|last=writer|first=Kim Sweet / Staff|work=The Daily Nebraskan|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Cosmology ====\nRhodes Scholar [[Brian Greene]] co-founded ISCAP, Columbia's Institute for Strings, Cosmology, and Astroparticle Physics. As well as winning a Pulitzer for non-fiction, Greene made some ground-breaking discoveries in the field of superstring theory and was one of the cosmologists to co-discover superstring theory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://codcourier.org/8400/news/theoretical-physicist-brian-greene-proposes-string-theory-as-the-theory-of-everything/|title=Theoretical physicist Brian Greene proposes String Theory as the theory of everything \u2013 The Courier|last=Weslo|first=Joey|website=codcourier.org|access-date=2018-11-23|date=2018-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== Comparison to other post-graduate scholarships ==\n{{see also|Marshall_Scholarship#Comparison to other post-graduate scholarships|label 1 = Comparison of the Marshall Scholarship to other scholarships}}\nAs the first large-scale programme of international scholarships,<ref name=\":1\">The American Rhodes Scholarships: A Review of the First Forty Years, Review author[s]: Harvie Branscomb, The American Historical Review \u00a9 1947 American Historical Association</ref> the Rhodes Scholarship inspired the creation of other awards, including:\n\n* The international [[Fulbright Program]] to teach study and research or teach English in over 150 countries (1946)\n* The [[Marshall Scholarship]] for Americans to study at any university in the United Kingdom (1953), an official British scholarship scheme for Americans\n* The [[Chevening Scholarship]] for citizens from 144 countries and territories to undertake postgraduate studies or courses in universities in the United Kingdom (1983), an official British scholarship scheme for countries other than the United States\n* The Churchill Scholarship for Americans to study at [[Churchill College, Cambridge|Churchill College]] at the [[University of Cambridge]] (1959)\n* The [[Kennedy Scholarship]] for British nationals to study at [[Harvard University]] or the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (1964)\n* The Harkness Fellowship for citizens of nine countries to conduct research related to health policy in the United States (1997)\n* The Mitchell Scholarship for Americans to study at any university in Ireland (2000)\n* The international [[Gates Cambridge Scholarship]] to study at the [[University of Cambridge]] (2000)\n* The [[Clarendon_Fund|Clarendon Scholarship]] for \"the best and brightest minds in any given field\" to pursue post-graduate study at the [[University of Oxford]] (2001)\n* The [[John Monash Scholars]]hip for Australians to study at any university worldwide (2004)\n* The international [[Yenching Scholars]]hip for study at [[Peking University]] (2015)\n* The international [[Schwarzman Scholars]]hip for study at [[Tsinghua University]] (2016)\n* The international [[Knight-Hennessy Scholars]] to study at [[Stanford University]] (2018)\n\nIn structure and selection criteria, the scholarship is most similar to the Gates Cambridge Scholarship, Marshall Scholarship and UK Fulbright Program. Like the Rhodes, the Marshall is a two-stage geographic scholarship organised through districts in selecting countries. Like the Gates Cambridge, the Rhodes is tenable at only one university. In structure, the Marshall Scholarship is more flexible than the Rhodes Scholarship, in that Marshall Scholars can study at any British university and can also attend a different university each year during a scholar's tenure. In addition, a limited number of one-year Marshall scholarships are available. The Marshall Scholarship also places a greater emphasis on academic achievement and potential, requiring a minimum grade point average of 3.7. For example, winners of the Marshall Scholarship from [[Harvard University]] have had average [[Grading in education|GPAs]] of 3.92, while winners of the Rhodes Scholarship from Harvard have had an average GPA of 3.8.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url =http://cabot.harvard.edu/content/Post-Graduate.docx|title =Harvard Post Graduate|publisher =Harvard|url-status =dead|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20141224142940/http://cabot.harvard.edu/content/Post-Graduate.docx|archivedate =24 December 2014|df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Rhodes Scholars]]\n* [[Gates Cambridge Scholarship]]\n* [[Chevening Scholarship]]\n* [[Fulbright Scholarship]]\n* [[Marshall Scholarship]]\n* [[Clarendon Scholarship]]\n* [[Jardine Scholarship]]\n* [[Knight-Hennessy Scholars]]\n* [[Thouron Award]]\n* [[Schwarzman Scholars]]\n* [[Yenching Academy]]\n*[[Rise (education program)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Godfrey Elton, ''The First Fifty Years of The Rhodes Trust and Scholarships, 1903-1953''. London: Blackwell, 1955.\n* R.I. Rotberg, ''The Founder: Cecil Rhodes and the Pursuit of Power''. New York: Oxford University Press, 1988.\n* Philip Ziegler, ''Cecil Rhodes, the Rhodes Trust and Rhodes Scholarships''. New Haven, CT: Yale University Press, 2008.\n* [[R.W. Johnson]], ''Look Back in Laughter: Oxford's Postwar Golden Age''. Threshold Press, 2015\n\n'''Books by former Wardens of Rhodes House, Oxford:'''\n* [[Anthony Kenny]], ''The History of the Rhodes Trust''. Oxford, England: Oxford University Press, 2001.\n* [[Donald Markwell]], ''\"Instincts to Lead\": On Leadership, Peace, and Education'', 2013.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/|Rhodes Trust official website}}\n* [http://www.rhodesproject.com/ Rhodes Project: The first in-depth study of Rhodes women]\n\n{{Global Scholars Group}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rhodes Scholars| ]]\n[[Category:1902 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Awards and prizes of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1902]]\n[[Category:N M Rothschild & Sons]]\n[[Category:Rhodes House|Scholarship]]\n[[Category:Scholarships in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "BulgeUwU", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhodes_Scholarship"}
{"title_page": "2019 Philippines Beechcraft King Air crash", "text_new": "{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| image = Beechcraft King Air 350 PR-OTG (15905068624).jpg\n| image_upright = 1.2\n| alt = \n| caption = A Beechcraft King Air 350 similar to the aircraft involved in the accident\n| occurrence_type = Accident\n| date = {{start date|2019|09|01|df=y}}\n| summary = Crashed during a medevac flight; under investigation\n| site = Agojo Resort, [[Pansol]], [[Calamba, Laguna]], [[Philippines]]\n| coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LON|type:event|display = inline,title}} -->\n| total_fatalities = 9\n| total_injuries = 2\n| occupants = 9\n| passengers = 7\n| crew = 2\n| fatalities = 9\n| survivors = 0\n| aircraft_type = [[Beechcraft Super King Air|Beechcraft B300 King Air 350]]\n| aircraft_name = \n| operator = [[Lionair (Philippines)]]\n| tail_number = RP-C2296<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ranter |first1=Harro |url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20190901-0 |title=Accident Description for RP-C2296 |website=[[Aviation Safety Network]] |date=1 September 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref>\n| origin = [[Dipolog Airport]], [[Zamboanga del Norte]], [[Philippines]]\n| destination = [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]], [[Manila]], [[Philippines]]\n| ground_injuries = 2\n}}\n\nOn 1 September 2019, a [[Beechcraft Super King Air|Beechcraft King Air 350]] operated by [[Lionair (Philippines)|Lionair]] crashed into a private resort in [[Calamba, Laguna]], [[Philippines]] while performing a [[medevac]] flight from [[Dipolog City, Zamboanga del Norte]], [[Philippines]] to [[Manila, Philippines]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/09/01/19/plane-crashes-in-calamba-laguna |title=Several killed as plane crashes in Calamba, Laguna |work=<!--Not stated--> |date=1 September 2019 |agency=[[ABS-CBN News]] |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref> All nine occupants aboard were killed in the crash.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gulfnews.com/amp/world/asia/philippines/9-killed-in-philippines-air-ambulance-crash-near-manila-authorities-1.1567341864411 |work=<!--Not stated--> |title=9 killed in Philippines air-ambulance crash near Manila: authorities |date=1 September 2019 |agency=[[Gulf News]] |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== Accident ==\n\nAccording to the [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]], the aircraft, which originated from the [[Dipolog Airport]] in [[Zamboanga del Norte]], was on a medevac flight to [[Manila]] when it disappeared on radar at around 3 p.m. while flying 25 nautical miles from Manila.<ref name=\"rappler.com\"/> Witnesses nearby reported that the aircraft circled at a low altitude before plummeting onto the ground.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2019/09/02/1948378/laguna-plane-crash-9-dead |title=Laguna plane crash: 9 dead |work=Ed Amoroso, Emmanuel Tupas |date=2 September 2019 |agency=[[The Philippine Star]] |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref> It crashed into the privately-owned Agojo Resort in [[Pansol, Calamba]], Laguna, killing all nine occupants aboard and injuring two others; it resulted in a fire which was put under control within two hours of the crash.<ref name=\"rappler.com\">{{cite news |url=https://rappler.com/nation/239047-light-plane-crash-calamba-laguna-september-1-2019 |work=<!--Not stated--> |title=9 dead as small plane crashes into Calamba resort in Laguna |date=1 September 2019 |agency=[[Rappler]] |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref> Among the dead were a patient being transported and his wife.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://globalnation.inquirer.net/179643/new-zealand-couple-among-dead-in-laguna-lightplane-crash/amp |work=<!--Not stated--> |title=New Zealand couple among dead in Laguna lightplane crash |date=1 September 2019 |agency=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n\nFollowing another aircraft crash of an [[IAI Westwind|IAI Westwind II]] at the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]] in just months after the accident, the CAAP grounded the entire [[Lionair (Philippines)|Lionair]] fleet while both crashes were still under investigation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/88437-caap-grounds-philippines-lionair-after-crash |title=CAAP grounds Philippines' Lionair after crash |website=ch-aviation.com |date=1 April 2020 |accessdate=25 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== Investigation ==\n\nThe [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]] and the Aircraft Accident Investigation and Inquiry Board started an investigation into the accident. The CAAP said that it has substantial information to determine the cause, but according to plane crash investigator Harry Pandero, there is a possibility that the crash was caused by either pilot error or the inclement weather at that time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mindanaodailynews.com/news/front-page/todays-top-stories/pilot-error-bad-weather-eyed-in-laguna-plane-crash-probe |title=Pilot error, bad weather eyed in Laguna plane crash probe |work=<!--Not stated--> |date=4 September 2019 |agency=Mindanao Daily News |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2019/9/1/plane-crash-Pansol-Laguna.html |title=9 fatalities in air ambulance plane crash in Laguna resort named |work=<!--Not stated-->  |date=1 September 2019 |agency=[[CNN Philippines]] |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2019 in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 2019]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| image = Beechcraft King Air 350 PR-OTG (15905068624).jpg\n| image_upright = 1.2\n| alt = \n| caption = A Beechcraft King Air 350 similar to the aircraft involved in the accident\n| occurrence_type = Accident\n| date = {{start date|2019|09|01|df=y}}\n| summary = Crashed during a medevac flight; under investigation\n| site = Agojo Resort, [[Pansol]], [[Calamba, Laguna]], [[Philippines]]\n| coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LON|type:event|display = inline,title}} -->\n| total_fatalities = 9\n| total_injuries = 2\n| occupants = 9\n| passengers = 7\n| crew = 2\n| fatalities = 9\n| survivors = 0\n| aircraft_type = [[Beechcraft Super King Air|Beechcraft B300 King Air 350]]\n| aircraft_name = \n| operator = [[Lionair (Philippines)]]\n| tail_number = RP-C2296<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ranter |first1=Harro |url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20190901-0 |title=Accident Description for RP-C2296 |website=[[Aviation Safety Network]] |date=1 September 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref>\n| origin = [[Dipolog Airport]], [[Zamboanga del Norte]], [[Philippines]]\n| destination = [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]], [[Manila]], [[Philippines]]\n| ground_injuries = 2\n}}\n\nOn 1 September 2019, a [[Beechcraft Super King Air|Beechcraft King Air 350]] operated by [[Lionair (Philippines)|Lionair]] crashed into a private resort in [[Calamba, Laguna]], [[Philippines]] while performing a [[medevac]] flight from [[Dipolog City, Zamboanga del Norte]], [[Philippines]] to [[Manila, Philippines]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/09/01/19/plane-crashes-in-calamba-laguna |title=Several killed as plane crashes in Calamba, Laguna |work=<!--Not stated--> |date=1 September 2019 |agency=[[ABS-CBN News]] |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref> All nine occupants aboard were killed in the crash.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gulfnews.com/amp/world/asia/philippines/9-killed-in-philippines-air-ambulance-crash-near-manila-authorities-1.1567341864411 |work=<!--Not stated--> |title=9 killed in Philippines air-ambulance crash near Manila: authorities |date=1 September 2019 |agency=[[Gulf News]] |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== Accident ==\n\nAccording to the [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]], the aircraft, which originated from the [[Dipolog Airport]] in [[Zamboanga del Norte]], was on a medevac flight to [[Manila]] when it disappeared on radar at around 3 p.m. while flying 25 nautical miles from Manila.<ref name=\"rappler.com\"/> Witnesses nearby reported that the aircraft circled at a low altitude before plummeting onto the ground.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2019/09/02/1948378/laguna-plane-crash-9-dead |title=Laguna plane crash: 9 dead |work=Ed Amoroso, Emmanuel Tupas |date=2 September 2019 |agency=[[The Philippine Star]] |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref> It crashed into the privately-owned Agojo Resort in [[Pansol, Calamba]], Laguna, killing all nine occupants aboard and injuring two others; it resulted in a fire which was put under control within two hours of the crash.<ref name=\"rappler.com\">{{cite news |url=https://rappler.com/nation/239047-light-plane-crash-calamba-laguna-september-1-2019 |work=<!--Not stated--> |title=9 dead as small plane crashes into Calamba resort in Laguna |date=1 September 2019 |agency=[[Rappler]] |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref> Among the dead were a patient being transported and his wife.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://globalnation.inquirer.net/179643/new-zealand-couple-among-dead-in-laguna-lightplane-crash/amp |work=<!--Not stated--> |title=New Zealand couple among dead in Laguna lightplane crash |date=1 September 2019 |agency=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== Investigation ==\n\nThe [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]] and the Aircraft Accident Investigation and Inquiry Board started an investigation into the accident. The CAAP said that it has substantial information to determine the cause, but according to plane crash investigator Harry Pandero, there is a possibility that the crash was caused by either pilot error or the inclement weather at that time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mindanaodailynews.com/news/front-page/todays-top-stories/pilot-error-bad-weather-eyed-in-laguna-plane-crash-probe |title=Pilot error, bad weather eyed in Laguna plane crash probe |work=<!--Not stated--> |date=4 September 2019 |agency=Mindanao Daily News |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2019/9/1/plane-crash-Pansol-Laguna.html |title=9 fatalities in air ambulance plane crash in Laguna resort named |work=<!--Not stated-->  |date=1 September 2019 |agency=[[CNN Philippines]] |accessdate=24 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2019 in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 2019]]\n", "name_user": "K Magz", "label": "safe", "comment": "Refs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Philippines_Beechcraft_King_Air_crash"}
{"title_page": "K9 Thunder", "text_new": "{{short description|South Korean self-propelled 155 mm howitzer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox weapon|name=K9 Thunder\n|image=[[File:Rajnath Singh in the K9 VAJRA-T on January 16, 2020.jpg|border|300px]]\n|caption=Indian variant K9 Vajra-T\n|type= [[Self-propelled artillery]]\n|origin=South Korea\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged=yes\n|is_bladed=no\n|is_explosive=no\n|is_artillery=yes\n|is_vehicle=yes\n|is_missile=no\n|service=K9: 1999\u2013present<br>K9A1: 2018\u2013present\n|wars=[[Bombardment of Yeonpyeong]]\n|is_UK=\n|used_by= See ''[[K9 Thunder#Operators|Operators]]''\n|designer=[[Agency for Defense Development]]<br>[[Hanwha Defense|Samsung Aerospace Industries]]\n|design_date=1989\u20131998\n|manufacturer= Hanwha Defense <small>(current)</small><br>Hanwha Land Systems <small>(2017-2019)</small><br>Hanwha Techwin <small>(2015-2017)</small><br>Samsung Techwin <small>(2000-2015)</small><br>Samsung Aerospace Industries <small>(1999-2000)</small>\n|unit_cost=$3.9 million\n|production_date=K9: 1999\u20132019<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goldlion.donga.com/NEWS/article/all/20190514/95516701/1/%EB%AA%85%ED%92%88-K9-%EC%9E%90%EC%A3%BC%ED%8F%AC-%ED%95%9C%EA%B5%AD%E8%BB%8D-%EB%82%A9%ED%92%88-%EB%81%9D-%ED%95%9C%ED%99%94-%EC%9D%BC%EA%B0%90%EC%A0%88%EB%B2%BD-%EB%A7%89%EC%9E%90-%EC%88%98%EC%B6%9C-%EC%B4%9D%EB%A0%A5 |website=THE DONG-A ILBO |title=\uba85\ud488 K9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec \ud55c\uad6d\u8ecd \ub0a9\ud488 \ub05d\u2026\ud55c\ud654 \"\uc77c\uac10\uc808\ubcbd \ub9c9\uc790, \uc218\ucd9c \ucd1d\ub825\" |date=2019-05-14}}</ref><br>K9A1: 2018\u2013present\n|variants=K10 ARV<br>[[T-155 Firtina]]\n|range=\n|max_range=18 km (M107, HE)<br />30 km (M549A1, HE-RAP)<br />36 km (K310, BB/DP-ICM)<br />40 km (K307, BB/HE)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bemil.chosun.com/nbrd/bbs/view.html?b_bbs_id=10002&pn=5&num=1645|title=[\uad70\uc218\ud488 \ub3cb\ubcf4\uae30] K307 155\u339c \uace1\uc0ac\ud3ec\uc6a9 \ud56d\ub825\uac10\uc18c \uace0\ud3ed\ud0c4|last=BEMIL|access-date=2017-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912233741/http://bemil.chosun.com/nbrd/bbs/view.html?b_bbs_id=10002&pn=5&num=1645|archive-date=2017-09-12|url-status=live}}</ref><br />52 km (K315, HE-RAP)<br />100+ km (GGAM, in development)\n| 1 round/min (Maximum)\n|       length=12 m\n|        width=3.4 m\n|       height=2.73 m\n|       weight= 47 tonnes\n|   suspension= [[Hydropneumatic suspension|hydropneumatic]]\n|   speed= 67 km/h\n|        vehicle_range= 480 km\n|      primary_armament= Hyundai WIA 155 mm 52 caliber\n|    secondary_armament= 12.7 mm (.50 caliber) K6 HMG\n|       armour=\n|       engine= [[MTU Friedrichshafen]] MT 881 Ka-500 [[8-cylinder]] [[water-cooled]] [[diesel engine]]\n| transmission= [[S&T Dynamics]] X1100-5A3\n|         crew=5 (Commander, Driver, Gunner, 2 Loaders)\n|    engine_power=1000 hp\n|        pw_ratio= 21 hp/ton\n\n}}\nThe '''K9 Thunder''' is a South Korean self-propelled [[155 mm]] [[howitzer]] designed and developed by the [[Agency for Defense Development]] and [[Hanwha Defense|Samsung Aerospace Industries]] for the [[Republic of Korea Armed Forces]], and is now manufactured by [[Hanwha Defense]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://defenceandtechnology.com/2018/01/02/norway-buys-k9-thunder-from-hanwha/|title=Norway buys K9 Thunder from Hanwha|date=2 January 2018|work=Defence and Technology|accessdate=31 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731031409/http://defenceandtechnology.com/2018/01/02/norway-buys-k9-thunder-from-hanwha/|archive-date=31 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> K9 howitzers operate in groups with the '''K10''' automatic ammunition resupply vehicle variant. The entire K9 fleet operated by the ROK Armed Forces is now undergoing upgrades to K9A1 standard, and a further development of a K9A2 variant is in process.\n\n==History==\n===Development===\nIn 1980s, the ROK Armed Forces came in need of new artillery system to contest North Korean equipment. The armed forces operated [[M107 self-propelled gun]] and [[M109 howitzer|K55 self-propelled howitzer]]; however, they had shorter firing range compared to [[Koksan (artillery)|M-1978 Koksan]] and were outnumbered by various North Korean artillery. With the success of designing and manufacturing KH-178 and KH-179 towed artillery, and experience gained by license producing K55 (KM109A2), the Ministry of Defense ordered to develop new system that has longer firing range, faster firing rate, and high mobility. The development started in 1989 and was led by the [[Agency for Defense Development]] (ADD) and Samsung Aerospace Industries (now Hanwha Defense).<ref name=\"K9 Developer Interview (1)\">{{cite AV media |date=2015-09-16 |title=[\ucca8\ub2e8\uad6d\uac00\uc758 \ucd08\uc11d, \ubc29\uc704\uc0b0\uc5c5] \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\uc758 \uc0c8 \ucc28\uc6d0\uc744 \uc5f4\ub2e4 - K-9 \ucc9c\ub465(1\ubd80) |language=Korean |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F2tivketAK0 |publisher=\uad6d\ubc29TV}}</ref>\n\nThe ADD first offered upgrades on existing K55, inspired by the United States' M109 Howitzer Improvement Program (HIP), but was rejected by the [[Republic of Korea Army]]. As a result, the ADD determined to create new weapon system and worked on conceptual model till 1991. Early concept requested by the military includes river crossing capability and installation of [[M61 Vulcan]] as anti-air weapon, which were removed due to unnecessity for such long-range weapon.<ref name=\"K9 Developer Interview (1)\" />\n\nIn 1992, the Ground System Division of United Defense LP (now BAE Systems Land and Armaments) invited members of the ADD for its first M109A6 Paladin release ceremony and expressed interest in participating Korea's self-propelled howitzer program by upgrading K55 to Paladin standard, which was rejected by South Korea.<ref name=\"K9 Developer Interview (2)\">{{cite AV media |date=2015-10-15 |title=[\ucca8\ub2e8\uad6d\uac00\uc758 \ucd08\uc11d, \ubc29\uc704\uc0b0\uc5c5] \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\uc758 \uc0c8 \ucc28\uc6d0\uc744 \uc5f4\ub2e4 - K-9 \ucc9c\ub465(2\ubd80) |language=Korean |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lh_CVAm3XNo |publisher=\uad6d\ubc29TV}}</ref>\n\nBy late 1990s, internal review showed localization of 107 out of 235 (45.5%) technologies required to build the artillery. After the review, South Korea decided to continue developing domestic main system, main gun, 155&nbsp;mm ammunition, fire control system, structure, and autoloader. On the other hand, engine, transmission, and INS were chosen to be imported from foreign partners, and license produce hydropneumatic suspension to boost up localization by 70%. The engineers faced biggest challenge on designing main gun and suspension due to lack of experience; while licensing the K55, its main gun was brought as finished product and suspension was produced under knowledge base from the United States.<ref name=\"K9 Developer Interview (2)\" />\n\nThe turret servo electrohydraulic system is a derive from that of [[K1 88-Tank|K1 MBT]]. Automatic fire control system enabled rapid aiming, faster shooting, and improvement to accuracy.<ref name=\"K9 Developer Interview (3)\">{{cite AV media |date=2015-10-15 |title=[\ucca8\ub2e8\uad6d\uac00\uc758 \ucd08\uc11d, \ubc29\uc704\uc0b0\uc5c5] \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\uc758 \uc0c8 \ucc28\uc6d0\uc744 \uc5f4\ub2e4 - K-9 \ucc9c\ub465(3\ubd80) |language=Korean |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yXvZZ9eowMs |publisher=\uad6d\ubc29TV}}</ref> Originally, Air-Log hydropneumatic suspension, which was being used for British [[AS-90]], was chosen for test for license produce, but failed to absorb shock from much bigger 52 caliber gun. Later, South Korea developed domestic hydropneumatic suspension and sold to Britain.<ref>{{cite web |date=2018-10-04 |title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] K-9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec, \uc601\uad6d \uc218\ucd9c\uae38 \uc624\ub974\ub098 |language=Korean |url=http://www.bizhankook.com/bk/article/16344 |publisher=\ube44\uc988\ud55c\uad6d}}</ref>\n\nA total of two prototypes were built and performed first open trial in 1996. During the test, the prototypes succeeded to fire distance of 40&nbsp;km and 6 rounds per minutes but failed to fire three rounds in 15 seconds. In 5 December 1997, one of prototypes was damaged by fire after testing 18 rounds in 3 minutes due to failing complete combustion, which resulted death of one researcher among three wounded.<ref name=\"E Daily\">{{cite web |date=2016-01-03 |title=[e-\ubb34\uae30]34\uc138 \uc5f0\uad6c\uc6d0\uc758 \ud76c\uc0dd \ub51b\uace0 \ud0c4\uc0dd\ud55c 'K-9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec' |language=Korean |url=https://www.edaily.co.kr/news/read?newsId=01134886612514112&mediaCodeNo=257 |publisher=E Daily}}</ref> However, damaged prototype's internal system survived the fire, thus was repaired for further use. Two prototypes fired a total of 4,100 rounds and underwent 13,800&nbsp;km driving test including in extreme temperature conditions.<ref name=\"K9 Developer Interview (3)\" /> The localization rate reached 87% by the end of the development.<ref name=\"ROK Defense Media Agency\">{{cite web |date=2015-08-10 |title=\uad70\uc778\uc758 \ubb3c\uac74 \uad70\uc218\ud488 \ub3cb\ubcf4\uae30 <15> K9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\uc640 K10 \ud0c4\uc57d\uc6b4\ubc18\ucc28 |language=Korean |url=https://demaclub.tistory.com/2743 |publisher=Republic of Korea Armed Forces Defense Media Agency}}</ref>\n\nThe contract for the K9 artillery system was awarded to Samsung Aerospace Industries in 22 December 1998. The first vehicle was rolled out in 17 December 1999, and was fielded to the [[Republic of Korea Marine Corps]] in [[Yeonpyeongdo|Yeonpyeong Island]].<ref name=\"E Daily\" /><ref name=\"ROK Defense Media Agency\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Khan|first1=Bilal|title=South Korea markets K9 Thunder SP howitzer at Eurosatory 2016|url=http://quwa.org/2016/06/14/south-korea-markets-k9-thunder-sp-howitzer-eurosatory/|website=Quwa|accessdate=18 September 2016|date=14 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918162202/http://quwa.org/2016/06/14/south-korea-markets-k9-thunder-sp-howitzer-eurosatory/|archive-date=18 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Good as New! Finland to Buy Second-Hand Howitzers from South Korea|url=https://sputniknews.com/military/20160704/1042391782/finland-south-korea-howitzer.html|website=Sputnik|accessdate=18 September 2016|date=4 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918160719/https://sputniknews.com/military/20160704/1042391782/finland-south-korea-howitzer.html|archive-date=18 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=S. Korea poised to sign deal to export K9 howitzer to Asian country|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/business/2016/06/15/0501000000AEN20160615007800315.html|website=Yonhap News Agency|accessdate=18 September 2016|date=15 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922085109/http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/business/2016/06/15/0501000000AEN20160615007800315.html|archive-date=22 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Operational history===\nThe K9 Thunder saw its first combat during the [[bombardment of Yeonpyeong]] on November 23, 2010.  Six [[Republic of Korea Marine Corps|ROKMC]] howitzers engaged against the surprise attack from the North Korean artillery.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2010/11/23/skorea-nkorea-fires-artillery-island/|title=North Korea Fires On Island in South, 2 Dead|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Fox News Channel]]|date=2010-11-23|accessdate=2010-11-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101123062722/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2010/11/23/skorea-nkorea-fires-artillery-island/|archive-date=2010-11-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2010/11/113_77022.html |title=Extent of NK damage remains uncertain |newspaper=The Korea Times |date=26 November 2010 |access-date=26 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430013729/http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2010/11/113_77022.html |archive-date=30 April 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Prior to the battle, the howitzers returned from a scheduled firing exercise, using most of the shells stored within the howitzer. In addition, one howitzer experienced a problem during the exercise when a shell became stuck in the barrel, disabling it. Two units received slight damage to their firing control systems during the initial North Korean attack, meaning only three out of the six units were able to counterattack. Eventually, the howitzer that had barrel problems joined the second counterattack after receiving field repairs. The K9s fired only one shell every 1.5 minutes, because the marines had to carry the shells from the armory and manually load the howitzer under heavy fire after exhausting B/L rounds.<ref>[http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=214&aid=0000161667 \"K-9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\uc5d0 \ud3ec\ud0c4 \ud55c \ubc1c\ub3c4 \uc5c6\uc5c8\ub2e4\"], MBC, 27. November 2010. Retrieved October 18, 2015</ref><ref>[http://m.mnd.go.kr/user/boardList.action?command=view&page=21&boardId=I_42745&boardSeq=o_52000000000069&titleId=&siteId=mnd&id=mnd_020500000000 MBC, 'K-9 \ud145 \ube44\uc5b4 \uc788\uc5c8\ub2e4' \ubcf4\ub3c4 \uad00\ub828 \uad6d\ubc29\ubd80 \uc785\uc7a5\uc785\ub2c8\ub2e4] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917164407/http://m.mnd.go.kr/user/boardList.action?command=view&page=21&boardId=I_42745&boardSeq=o_52000000000069&titleId=&siteId=mnd&id=mnd_020500000000 |date=2016-09-17 }}, Ministry of National Defense, 28. November 2010. Retrieved October 18, 2015</ref>\n\n==General characteristics==\nK9 is an indigenous system of an all-welded steel armour construction which is rated to withstand  14.5&nbsp;mm armour piercing rounds, 152&nbsp;mm shell fragments, and anti-personnel mines.<ref name=protection>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/06.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061101045200/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/06.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-11-01|title=K9 Features: Protection|publisher=Samsung Techwin}}</ref> The main armament consists of a 155&nbsp;mm/52 caliber ordnance with a maximum firing range of 40&nbsp;km;<ref name=firepower>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/03.html|title=K9 Features: Superior firepower|publisher=Samsung Techwin|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20061101045148/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/03.html|archivedate=2006-11-01}}</ref> the K307 BB-HE projectile propelled by the K676 top charge has a muzzle velocity of {{convert|928|m/s|ft/s|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"sputnik28june16\">[http://sputniknews.com/asia/20160628/1042052434/south-korean-government-developing-howlitzers.html South Korean Government Develops Remote Controlled Howitzers] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629155537/http://sputniknews.com/asia/20160628/1042052434/south-korean-government-developing-howlitzers.html |date=2016-06-29 }} \u2013 Sputniknews.com, 28 June 2016</ref> State-of-the-art mobility subsystems include a {{convert|1000|hp}} engine with potential for growth and [[hydropneumatic suspension]] unit, a requirement for Korea's rugged mountainous terrain.<ref name=mobility>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/05.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061101045133/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/05.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-11-01|title=K9 Features: Higher Mobility|publisher=Samsung Techwin}}</ref>\n\nIt was designed to give the artillery arm of the [[Republic of Korea Army]] a significant improvement in capability. With a claimed range of 75&nbsp;km, it offers greater mobility, longer range, higher rate of fire, and increased battlefield survivability, as it can quickly be brought into action, open fire, and come out of action. It is less likely to be engaged by counter-battery fire, by relying on [[shoot-and-scoot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/04.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061101045136/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/04.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-11-01|title=K9 Features: Shoot-and-scoot|publisher=Samsung Techwin}}</ref> The unit also supports full [[Chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear|CBRN]] protection.<ref name=protection />\n\nIn June 2016, the [[Defense Acquisition Program Administration]] (DAPA) revealed they were designing a new fully automatic projectile-and-charge loading system that will be retrofitted to the K9, essentially giving it a robotic turret.  The purpose is to reduce the crew needed to operate the vehicle to two in order to mitigate personnel losses expected to be suffered during North Korean attacks.<ref name=\"sputnik28june16\"/>\n\n=== MRSI ===\nThe K9 has the ability to fire its shells in [[Multiple Rounds Simultaneous Impact|MRSI]] mode (Multiple Rounds Simultaneous Impact). In the MRSI mode, the K9 is able to fire three shells in under 15 seconds\u20141 shell every 5 seconds\u2014each in different trajectories so that all of the shells will arrive on their target at the same time.<ref name=firepower/>\n\n===K10 Ammunition Resupply Vehicle (ARV)===\n[[Image:K10 ARV.jpg|thumb|left|K10 Ammunition Resupply Vehicle]]\n\nThe K10 is an automatic ammunition resupply vehicle built on the K9 platform, part of the K9 Thunder system. It shares the same chassis as K9, preserving K9's mobility, and can follow the main artillery battery without lagging behind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k10_e_new/02.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713213611/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k10_e_new/02.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2007-07-13|title=K10 Features: Higher Mobility&Common Chassis|publisher=Samsung Techwin}}</ref> Maximum transfer rate of shells is 12 rounds per minute, and maximum load of shells is 104 rounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/prd/pro_view.asp?pro_uid=1630&cat_uid=68&cat_biz=DEP&cat_lev=A|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218183858/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/prd/pro_view.asp?pro_uid=1630&cat_uid=68&cat_biz=DEP&cat_lev=A|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-02-18|title=K10 ARV|publisher=Samsung Techwin}}</ref>\n\nThe reloading process is fully automated. The reloading is done through a munition bridge on the K10 that extends out to lock itself into a reception hole located at the rear of the K9. This allows the unit to rearm itself under harsh combat conditions without the crew having to expose themselves to the combat environment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k10_e_new/05.html|title=K10 Features: Automatic Control System|publisher=Samsung Techwin|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20071111024607/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k10_e_new/05.html|archivedate=2007-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Export==\n\n===Turkey===\nWith technical support from ADD and Samsung Aerospace Industries, Turkey started designing the structure of its self-propelled howitzer based on the K9 in 1999.<ref name=\"DongA\">{{cite web |date=2001-07-20 |title=\uad6d\uc0b0 K9\uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec \uccab \uc218\ucd9c\u2026\ud130\ud0a4\uc5d0 1\uc8703000\uc5b5 \uaddc\ubaa8 |language=Korean |url=http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20010720/7717206/1 |publisher=The Dong-A Ilbo}}</ref> On 4 May 2000, the [[Ministry of National Defense (South Korea)|Ministry of National Defense of the Republic of Korea]] and Turkish Land Forces Command signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU) to supply K9 subsystems till 2011.<ref name=\"ROK Defense Media Agency\" /> A formal contract was signed by Samsung Techwin (formerly Samsung Aerospace Industries) and the Embassy of the Republic of Turkey in Seoul on 20 July 2001 worth an initial amount of $60 million\u2014a total deal of $1 billion, including technology transfer and license to produce, for 350 vehicles through 2011.<ref name=\"DongA\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/rok/k9.htm|title=K9 155mm self-propelled howitzer|first=John|last=Pike|access-date=2007-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070320052724/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/rok/k9.htm|archive-date=2007-03-20|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=2014-12-16 |title=\uc0bc\uc131\ud14c\ud06c\uc708, \ud3f4\ub780\ub4dc\uc5d0 'K-9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec' \uc218\ucd9c...2017\ub144\ubd80\ud130 \uc9c1\uc811 \uacf5\uae09 |url=http://www.newsway.co.kr/news/view?tp=1&ud=2014121622273349811 |language=Korean |publisher=News Way}}</ref> The Turkish variant self-propelled howitzer was named [[T-155 Firtina]] and to be assembled in Turkey.\n\n===Australia===\nThe K9 was a contender for Phase 1C of Australia's Land 17 Artillery Replacement Program prior to that phase of the project being cancelled in May 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-05-03/defence-white-paper-now-due-in-2013/3987042|title=Rethink of Defence projects to save billions|publisher=[[ABC Online]]|date=May 3, 2012|accessdate=May 3, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503202448/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-05-03/defence-white-paper-now-due-in-2013/3987042|archive-date=May 3, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn May the 14th, 2019, despite the earlier refusal of Australia to purchase this system in 2012, the Prime Minister of Australia announced that 30 K-9 howitzers and associated support equipment would be acquired for the ADF. No time frame has been given for the purchase.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Australian Army to receive massive boost in firepower with 155mm SPH purchase|last=|first=|date=June 2019|work=Australian Pacific Defense Reporter|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===India===\nHanwha Techwin joined hand with Indian conglomerate [[Larsen and Toubro|Larsen and Toubro Limited]] to supply 100 K9-T guns (known in India as K-9 Vajra)for the Indian Army Howitzer competition.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/indl-goods-/-svs/engineering/lt-samsung-join-hands-for-indias-howitzer-artillery/articleshow/12457051.cms | work=The Times Of India | title=L&T, Samsung join hands for India's Howitzer artillery | date=29 March 2012 | access-date=30 March 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222153015/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/indl-goods-/-svs/engineering/lt-samsung-join-hands-for-indias-howitzer-artillery/articleshow/12457051.cms | archive-date=22 December 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, [[Larsen & Toubro|Larsen and Toubro]] emerged as the finalist for a US$800 million contract to supply 100 self-propelled howitzers to the [[Indian Army]].<ref>{{cite web|title = India's Newest Gun: Fast and Deadly|url = http://thediplomat.com/2015/10/indias-newest-gun-fast-and-deadly/|website = The Diplomat|accessdate = 2015-10-09|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151011181059/http://thediplomat.com/2015/10/indias-newest-gun-fast-and-deadly/|archive-date = 2015-10-11|url-status = live}}</ref> The vehicle is the K9 VAJRA-T, a variant of the K9 specially designed for operation in the desert areas bordering Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Global|first=IndraStra|title=Indian Army Inducts Two New Artillery Systems|url=https://www.indrastra.com/2018/11/Indian-Army-s-New-Artillery-Systems-004-11-2018-0021.html|journal=IndraStra|issn=2381-3652|access-date=2018-11-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118164856/https://www.indrastra.com/2018/11/Indian-Army-s-New-Artillery-Systems-004-11-2018-0021.html|archive-date=2018-11-18|url-status=live}}</ref>  India has not had any new artillery pieces since the 1980s and several rounds of modernization plans since 1999 had failed to select a gun.  India has been at a distinct disadvantage against Pakistan  regarding [[self propelled artillery]] since the United States supplied them with 115 [[M109 Paladin|M109A5]] cannon in 2009.  The final process to sign the contract could take up to six more months.<ref>[http://armyrecognition.com/september_2015_global_defense_security_news_uk/larsen_and_toubro_selected_to_supply_100_self-propelled_howitzers_to_the_indian_army_23009152.html Larsen and Toubro selected to supply 100 self-propelled howitzers to the Indian Army] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002133151/http://www.armyrecognition.com/september_2015_global_defense_security_news_uk/larsen_and_toubro_selected_to_supply_100_self-propelled_howitzers_to_the_indian_army_23009152.html |date=2015-10-02 }} \u2013 Armyrecognition.com, 30 September 2015</ref>\nIn 2017, Indian Defence Ministry signed the contract with private sector defence manufacturer Larsen & Toubro and by January 2020, the company was able to deliver more than half of K-9 Vajra guns in the Indian army ahead of schedule.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.defencestar.in/defence-industry/defence-news-india-rajnath-singh-flags-off-larsen-troubo-hanwha-defense-hanwha-techwins-51st-homemade-self-propelled-howitzer-gun-k9-vajra-ahead-of-schedule/?amp |title = Defence minister Rajnath Singh flags off 51st homemade K9 Vajra Gun ahead of schedule |newspaper = Defence Star|date = 16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Finland===\nIn July 2016, the Finnish Ministry of Defence announced that an undisclosed number of used K9s have been selected to be acquired from the Republic of Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defmin.fi/ajankohtaista/tiedotteet/maavoimien_tykistokaluston_uusiminen_etenee.7898.news|title=Maavoimien tykist\u00f6kaluston uusiminen etenee|access-date=2016-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705051603/http://www.defmin.fi/ajankohtaista/tiedotteet/maavoimien_tykistokaluston_uusiminen_etenee.7898.news|archive-date=2016-07-05|url-status=live}}</ref> The acquisition is claimed to be biggest of the decade for the Land Forces, whose both mobile and towed artillery face mass outdating in the 2020s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reservilainen.fi/uutiset/maavoimien_etsikkoaikaa_eletaan_parhaillaan|title=Maavoimien etsikkoaikaa elet\u00e4\u00e4n parhaillaan|date=26 February 2016|access-date=1 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608153559/http://www.reservilainen.fi/uutiset/maavoimien_etsikkoaikaa_eletaan_parhaillaan|archive-date=8 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2017, the Ministry of Defence announced that Finland will acquire 48 used K9s over a period of seven years starting in 2018, with conscript training on the equipment commencing in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/3-9466486|title=Suomi ostaa 48 k\u00e4ytetty\u00e4 panssarihaupitsia Etel\u00e4-Koreasta|website=Yle Uutiset|access-date=2017-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217152142/http://yle.fi/uutiset/3-9466486|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Estonia===\nEstonia has also confirmed its decision to purchase K9 Thunders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreadefence.net/detail.php?number=3887&thread=22r06|title=\uc5d0\uc2a4\ud1a0\ub2c8\uc544, K-9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec \ub3c4\uc785 \uacb0\uc815 - \uc790\uc8fc\uad6d\ubc29\ub124\ud2b8\uc6cc\ud06c-|website=koreadefence.net|access-date=2017-02-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204170833/http://koreadefence.net/detail.php?number=3887&thread=22r06|archive-date=2017-02-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> According to other sources Estonia is teaming up with Finland in the procurement of the K9 and will order 12 howitzers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/baltic_states/?doc=127392|title=Estonia to team up with Finland to procure K9 Thunder howitzers|first=The Baltic Course - \u0411\u0430\u043b\u0442\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439|last=\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441|access-date=2017-02-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203191818/http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/baltic_states/?doc=127392|archive-date=2017-02-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\nAt the end of June 2018 Rauno Sirk, the director of the Estonian military procurement agency, said in a statement, that Estonia will buy K9 Thunder howitzers, the first of the twelve will arrive in the country in 2020.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://estonianworld.com/security/estonia-to-buy-artillery-from-south-korea-for-e46-million/|title=Estonia to buy artillery from South Korea for \u20ac46 million|last=Hankewitz|first=Sten|date=June 26, 2018|work=Estonian World|access-date=June 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628055638/http://estonianworld.com/security/estonia-to-buy-artillery-from-south-korea-for-e46-million/|archive-date=June 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Norway===\nOn August 24, 2016 the Norwegian Defence Materiel Agency published their intention to continue negotiations with [[Hanwha Techwin]] and Swiss [[RUAG]], which has offered their [[M109 howitzer#M109 \"KAWEST\"|M109 \"KAWEST\"]] upgrade. At the same time, the NDMA said that negotiations concerning the [[Krauss-Maffei Wegmann|KMW]] made [[Panzerhaubitze 2000]] and the [[CAESAR self-propelled howitzer|Nexter Caesar]] had been put \"on hold\". Unnamed sources in the Norwegian Army had previously stated that the K9 was a leading candidate in the competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tu.no/artikler/haeren-ligger-an-til-a-fa-koreanske-kanoner/350619 |author=Per Erlien Dall\u00f8kken |title=H\u00e6ren ligger an til \u00e5 f\u00e5 koreanske kanoner |trans-title=The army is likely to get Korean cannons |language=Norwegian |publisher=tu.no |date=August 24, 2016 |access-date=August 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825165759/http://www.tu.no/artikler/haeren-ligger-an-til-a-fa-koreanske-kanoner/350619 |archive-date=August 25, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn December 20, 2017, a contract was signed between Hanwha Land Systems and Norwegian Defence Materiel Agency for \u20a9245.2 billion to supply 24 K9 Thunder and 6 K10 ARV by 2020. K9 outperformed competitors in various weather and terrain conditions according Norwegian military officials during trials.<ref>{{cite web |date=2017-12-21 |title=\ud55c\ud654, K-9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\u00b7K10 \uc7a5\uac11\ucc28 \ub178\ub974\uc6e8\uc774 \uc218\ucd9c\u20262452\uc5b5\uc6d0 \uaddc\ubaa8 |language=Korean |url=https://biz.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2017/12/21/2017122100835.html |publisher=Chosun Ilbo}}</ref>\n\nNorwegian variant was named as K9 VIDAR (Versatile InDirect ARtillery system), and is based on K9 PIP configuration. It uses Norwegian ODIN fire support system and radio communication systems.<ref name=\"Defense Times\">{{cite web |date=2019-10-05 |title=K9A1 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\uc758 \uc2dc\uc791 |language=Korean |url=http://defensetimes.kr/article/view.php?&ss[fc]=4&bbs_id=DefenceTimes_news&doc_num=1754 |publisher=Defense Times}}</ref>\n\n===Egypt===\nIn April 2017, it was reported that [[Hanwha Techwin]] was in negotiations with Egypt to export its K9 Thunder self-propelled howitzer.<ref name=\"businesspost.co.kr\">{{cite news |url= http://www.businesspost.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=46398 |title= Hanwha Techwin to improve earnings due to K9 Thunder exports |date= 5 April 2017 |language= korean |access-date= 24 August 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170825020136/http://www.businesspost.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=46398 |archive-date= 25 August 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref> The K9 Thunder is one of the contenders for supplying Egypt with new artillery systems, other howitzers competing with the K9 include those from Russia, South Africa and France, specifically the [[CAESAR self-propelled howitzer]].<ref name=\"defenceweb.co.za\">{{cite news |url= http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48661 |title= Egypt evaluating new artillery |date= 24 July 2017 |language= english |access-date= 24 August 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170825020846/http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48661 |archive-date= 25 August 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref> South Korea's K9 self-propelled howitzer began performance evaluation tests in Egypt at the end of July 2017. A K9 howitzer arrived in Egypt earlier that month for test-firing at a range located west of Cairo. Egypt plans to complete performance evaluations of the howitzer by the end of the year and sign a contract in early 2018.<ref name=\"koreatimes.co.kr\">{{cite news |url= http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2017/07/205_233677.html |title= Egypt interested in buying K-9 howitzer |date= 26 July 2017 |language= english |access-date= 24 August 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170824221609/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2017/07/205_233677.html |archive-date= 24 August 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Variants and upgrades==\n* '''XK9:''' Experimental prototype.\n* '''K9 Thunder:''' First-production variant.\n** '''AS9 \"Aussie Thunder\":''' Offered Australian variant of the K9 in 2012.\n** '''AS9 \"Huntsman\":''' Offered Australian variant of the K9 in 2019 inline with Hanhwa's proposal of the AS21 \"Redback\" IFV offering for LAND 400 Phase 3.\n** '''K9 VAJRA-T (Lightning):''' Indian variant of the K9. Manufactured by [[Larsen & Toubro]] under license, consisting 50% component (by value) including 14 major sub-systems developed by Indian companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/defence/indian-army-gets-more-firepower-rajnath-singh-flags-off-51st-k9-vajra-t-gun/1825430/|title=Indian army gets more firepower! Rajnath Singh flags off 51st K9 VAJRA-T Gun|date=2020-01-16|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> It has been customised as per [[Desert|desert conditions]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/army-inducts-new-artillery-guns-after-three-decades/article25452662.ece|title=Army fire power gets booster shot|last=Peri|first=Dinakar|date=2018-11-09|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-20|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n** '''K9FIN Moukari (Sledge-hammer):''' Finnish variant of the K9 with APU.\n* '''K9A1:''' First enhanced variant. Added APU, GPS navigator, driver's thermal periscope, rear surveillance camera, and improved fire control system. A1 upgrade also allows to use new extended range ammunition, increasing its firing range.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hanwhatechwin.co.kr/product/product_05_01.asp|title=\ud654\ub825\uccb4\uacc4 : \ud55c\ud654\ud14c\ud06c\uc708 \uc81c\ud488\uc18c\uac1c|website=www.hanwhatechwin.co.kr|access-date=2017-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707104914/http://hanwhatechwin.co.kr/product/product_05_01.asp|archive-date=2017-07-07|url-status=live}}</ref> First K9A1 rolled out and is in service of the [[Republic of Korea Army]] since 2018. All K-9 operated by the [[Republic of Korea Armed Forces|ROK Armed Forces]] will be upgraded to A1 by 2030.\n** '''K9 VIDAR (Versatile InDirect ARtillery):''' Norwegian variant of the K9A1.\n* '''K9A2:''' Under development. A2 variant will apply auto-loader, increased firing rate, 3 operators, remote control directly from BTCS.\n* '''K10:''' Ammunition resupply vehicle using the K9 chassis.\n** '''AS10:''' Offered Australian variant of the K10.\n* '''[[T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na]]:''' Turkish version with modified turret, chassis, electronics and navigation system.\n* '''[[AHS Krab]]:''' Polish self-propelled howitzer, using the K9 chassis and [[AS-90]] turret.\n\n==Operators==\n[[File:K9 operators.png|thumb|400px|Map with K9 operators in blue and parts or subsystems operators in cyan]]\n[[File:Lippujuhlan p\u00e4iv\u00e4n 2017 paraati 104 K9 Thunder.JPG|thumb|K9 in Finnish Defence Forces' Flag Day parade]]\n[[File:AHS Krab in Kyiv 01.jpg|thumb|Polish AHS Krab using K9 chassis at Arms and Security 2017 exhibition]]\n\n===Current operators===\n; {{flag|Estonia}}\n\nOn 26 June 2018, Estonia signed an agreement with South Korea for the procurement of 12 K9 self-propelled howitzers, with a reported option for 12 additional artillery systems. The agreement also includes training, maintenance and spare parts. Deliveries to start in 2020. The purchase of additional 6 howitzers was announced in October 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kund |first1=Oliver |title=Uus tulej\u00f5ud lisab kaitsev\u00e4ele rammu |url=https://www.postimees.ee/4509552/uus-tulejoud-lisab-kaitsevaele-rammu |website=www.postimees.ee |accessdate=2018-06-26 |language=et |date=2018-06-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626015751/https://www.postimees.ee/4509552/uus-tulejoud-lisab-kaitsevaele-rammu |archive-date=2018-06-26 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Vahtla |first1=Aili |title=Gallery: Estonia, South Korea sign artillery purchase agreement |url=https://news.err.ee/842341/gallery-estonia-south-korea-sign-artillery-purchase-agreement |website=news.err.ee |publisher=ERR |accessdate=2018-06-26 |date=2018-06-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626164043/https://news.err.ee/842341/gallery-estonia-south-korea-sign-artillery-purchase-agreement |archive-date=2018-06-26 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.err.ee/987854/paper-more-military-equipment-to-be-bought-from-south-korea|title=Paper: More military equipment to be bought from South Korea|last=ERR|first=ERR News {{!}}|date=2019-10-03|website=ERR|language=en|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref>\n\n;{{flag|Finland}}\nThe [[Finnish Defence Forces]] announced on 17 February 2017 that they will buy 48 used K9s, with the deliveries starting in 2017.<ref>[http://www.iltasanomat.fi/kotimaa/art-2000005092507.html Suomi hankkii 48 k\u00e4ytetty\u00e4 panssarihaupitsia Etel\u00e4-Koreasta] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217144716/http://www.iltasanomat.fi/kotimaa/art-2000005092507.html |date=2017-02-17 }} iltasanomat.fi, February 17, 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Larrinaga, de |first1=Nicholas |title=Finland buys K9 howitzers from South Korea |url=http://www.janes.com/article/67827/ |website=IHS Jane's 360 |accessdate=18 February 2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170218122710/http://www.janes.com/article/67827/finland-buys-k9-howitzers-from-south-korea |archivedate=18 February 2017 |location=London |date=18 February 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n;{{flag|India}}\n10 units were brought from South Korea and assembled by L&T in India, were to be handed over to the Indian Army during Defexpo 2018. Rest of the 100 will be produced by [[Larsen & Toubro]] for the Indian Army.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/article/55127/k9-selected-for-indian-army-sph-requirement|title=K9 selected for Indian Army SPH requirement \u2013 IHS Jane's 360|access-date=2015-10-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009203112/http://www.janes.com/article/55127/k9-selected-for-indian-army-sph-requirement|archive-date=2015-10-09|url-status=live}}</ref> The first batch of 25 units was delivered to the Indian Army in May 2018. As on 17 January 2019 51 units have been delivered by the local manufacturer, L&T.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/rajnath-singh-flags-off-51st-k-9-vajra-at-l-t-gun-making-facility-11579175814226.html|title=First batch of K9 Vajra-T 155mm self-propelled howitzers delivered to Indian army|last=|first=|date=9 May 2018|website=Army Recognition|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512201516/http://www.armyrecognition.com/may_2018_global_defense_security_army_news_industry/first_batch_of_k9_vajra-t_self-propelled_155mm_howitzers_delivered_to_indian_army.html|archivedate=12 May 2018|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n;{{flag|Republic of Korea}}\nTotal production of 1,136 K9s and 179 K10s were fielded by 2019. All K9 will be upgraded to K9A1 by 2030, and K9A2 variant development is ongoing.\n;{{flag|Norway}}\nNorway has selected the K9 Thunder in its bid to replace the [[M109 howitzer|M109A3GNM]] SPHs that have been in service since the 1960s. 24 K9 and 6 K10 have been purchased, with an option for another 24 K9 and additional K10. Deliveries are scheduled to begin in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yeo|first1=Mike|title=Norway orders K9 howitzers in latest win for South Korean arms industry|url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2017/12/20/norway-orders-k9-howitzers-in-latest-win-for-south-korean-arms-industry/|website=Defense News|accessdate=26 December 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171220162835/https://www.defensenews.com/land/2017/12/20/norway-orders-k9-howitzers-in-latest-win-for-south-korean-arms-industry/|archivedate=20 December 2017|location=Melbourne|date=20 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Grevatt|first1=Jon|title=Hanwha confirms K9 export to Norway|url=http://www.janes.com/article/76637|website=IHS Jane's 360|accessdate=26 December 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171226214449/http://www.janes.com/article/76637/hanwha-confirms-k9-export-to-norway|archivedate=26 December 2017|date=22 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Erlien Dall\u00f8kken|first1=Per|title=N\u00e5 er det klart: Dette blir Norges nye artilleri|url=https://www.tu.no/artikler/na-er-det-klart-dette-blir-norges-nye-artilleri/414850|website=Teknisk Ukeblad|accessdate=26 December 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171226213704/https://www.tu.no/artikler/na-er-det-klart-dette-blir-norges-nye-artilleri/414850|archivedate=26 December 2017|language=Norwegian|date=20 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n;{{flag|Poland}}\n120 K9 chassis will be produced as part of the [[AHS Krab]] program.<ref>[http://www.armyrecognition.com/december_2014_global_defense_security_news_uk/samsung_techwin_signs_deal_for_delivering_120_k9_thunder_self-propelled_howitzers_to_poland.html Samsung Techwin signs deal for delivering 120 K9 Thunder self-propelled howitzers to Poland] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923180802/http://www.armyrecognition.com/december_2014_global_defense_security_news_uk/samsung_techwin_signs_deal_for_delivering_120_k9_thunder_self-propelled_howitzers_to_poland.html |date=2015-09-23 }} armyrecognition.com, December 17, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Grevatt|first1=Jon|title=South Korea's Hanwha secures Polish K9 export|url=http://www.janes.com/article/66310/|website=IHS Jane's 360|accessdate=16 December 2016|location=Bangkok|date=16 December 2016}}</ref>\n;{{flag|Turkey}}\nTurkey is guaranteed to build 350 [[T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na]] under license for US$1.6 million per vehicle including right to export and modify.<ref>https://m.dcinside.com/board/war/275137</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.joins.com/article/23542876 |website=Korea Joongang Daily |title=\uc120\uc9c4\uad6d\uc774 \uc7a5\uc545\ud55c \ubb34\uae30\uc2dc\uc7a5, \uac00\uaca9 \uacbd\uc7c1\ub825\uc73c\ub85c \ub6ab\ub294\ub2e4 |date=2019-08-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news2day.co.kr/128214 |website=News2Day |title=[\uc218\ucd9c \ubc29\uc0b0 \uba85\ud488](2) \ud55c\ud654\ub514\ud39c\uc2a4\uc758 'K9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec' 2\uc870\uc6d0 \uaddc\ubaa8 \uc218\ucd9c |date=2019-05-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://quwa.org/2016/06/14/south-korea-markets-k9-thunder-sp-howitzer-eurosatory/ |website=Quwa Defence News & Analysis Group |title=SOUTH KOREA MARKETS K9 THUNDER SP HOWITZER AT EUROSATORY 2016 |date=2016-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.g-enews.com/view.php?ud=20190531102258736c63242687e_1&md=20190531130605_M |website=Global Economics |title=[\uae00\ub85c\ubc8c-Biz 24] \ud130\ud0a4, \ud55c\uad6d \uba85\ud488\ubb34\uae30 'K9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec' \ubcc0\ud615\ud55c 'T-155 \ud504\ub974\ud2b8\ub098' \uac1c\ubc1c...\ud615\uc81c\uc758 \ub09c? |date=2019-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.armyrecognition.com/turkey_army_artillery_vehicle_weapon_systems_uk/t-155_firtina_155mm_self-propelled_howitzer_technical_data_sheet_specifications_pictures_video.html |website=Army Recognition |title=T-155 Firtina 155mm 52 caliber self-propelled howitzer |date=2018-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/meet-k-9-thunder-south-koreas-giant-artillery-gun-aimed-north-korea-91431 |website=National Interest |title=Meet the K-9 Thunder: South Korea's Giant Artillery Gun (Aimed at North Korea) |date=2019-10-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/defense/2018/01/27/domestically-produced-defense-systems-deployed-in-afrin-offensive |website=Daily Sabah |title=Domestically produced defense systems deployed in Afrin offensive|date=2018-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-hit-syria-with-s-korean-designed-howitzers-31653 |website=Hurriyet Daily News |title=Turkey hit Syria with S. Korean-designed howitzers |date=2012-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hanwha-defense.co.kr/kor/products/firearms-system-k9.do |website=Hanwha Defense |title=K9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defensenews.com/global/europe/2014/12/16/south-korea-to-export-k-9-howitzers-to-poland/ |website=Defense News |title=South Korea To Export K-9 Howitzers to Poland |date=2014-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bulgarianmilitary.com/2019/12/07/the-norwegian-armed-forces-received-self-propelled-howitzers-k9/ |website=BulgarianMilitary.com |title=The Norwegian Armed Forces received self-propelled howitzers K9 |date=2019-12-07}}</ref> The first 8 units were built in South Korea.\n[[File:T-155F\u0131rt\u0131na (1).jpg|thumb|Turkish variant [[T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na]]]]\n\n===Potential operators===\n;{{flag|Egypt}}\nThe [[Egyptian Army]] is currently performing evaluation tests for the K9 howitzer in Egypt. Final contract is expected to be signed in early 2018.<ref name=\"koreatimes.co.kr\"/>\n\n== Related developments ==\n* [[AHS Krab]]\n* [[T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[M109 howitzer|M109]]\n* [[AS-90]]\n* [[PzH 2000]]\n* [[SSPH1]]\n* [[Type 99 155 mm Self-propelled howitzer|Type 99]]\n* [[PLZ-05]]\n* [[2S35 Koalitsiya-SV]]\n* [[Bhim self-propelled howitzer|Bhim]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|K9 Thunder}}\n* [https://www.hanwha-defense.co.kr/eng/products/firearms-system-k9.do K9 Thunder Self-propelled Howitzer - Artillery Systems - Hanwha Defense]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/rok/k9.htm Global Security on K-9 Howitzer]\n* [http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4425860 Defense News]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n[[Category:Self-propelled artillery of South Korea]]\n[[Category:155 mm artillery]]\n[[Category:Tracked self-propelled howitzers]]\n[[Category:Self-propelled howitzers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South Korean self-propelled 155 mm howitzer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox weapon|name=K9 Thunder\n|image=[[File:Rajnath Singh in the K9 VAJRA-T on January 16, 2020.jpg|border|300px]]\n|caption=Indian variant K9 Vajra-T\n|type= [[Self-propelled artillery]]\n|origin=South Korea\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged=yes\n|is_bladed=no\n|is_explosive=no\n|is_artillery=yes\n|is_vehicle=yes\n|is_missile=no\n|service=K9: 1999\u2013present<br>K9A1: 2018\u2013present\n|wars=[[Bombardment of Yeonpyeong]]\n|is_UK=\n|used_by= See ''[[K9 Thunder#Operators|Operators]]''\n|designer=[[Agency for Defense Development]]<br>[[Hanwha Defense|Samsung Aerospace Industries]]\n|design_date=1989\u20131998\n|manufacturer= Hanwha Defense <small>(current)</small><br>Hanwha Land Systems <small>(2017-2019)</small><br>Hanwha Techwin <small>(2015-2017)</small><br>Samsung Techwin <small>(2000-2015)</small><br>Samsung Aerospace Industries <small>(1999-2000)</small>\n|unit_cost=$3.9 million\n|production_date=K9: 1999\u20132019<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goldlion.donga.com/NEWS/article/all/20190514/95516701/1/%EB%AA%85%ED%92%88-K9-%EC%9E%90%EC%A3%BC%ED%8F%AC-%ED%95%9C%EA%B5%AD%E8%BB%8D-%EB%82%A9%ED%92%88-%EB%81%9D-%ED%95%9C%ED%99%94-%EC%9D%BC%EA%B0%90%EC%A0%88%EB%B2%BD-%EB%A7%89%EC%9E%90-%EC%88%98%EC%B6%9C-%EC%B4%9D%EB%A0%A5 |website=THE DONG-A ILBO |title=\uba85\ud488 K9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec \ud55c\uad6d\u8ecd \ub0a9\ud488 \ub05d\u2026\ud55c\ud654 \"\uc77c\uac10\uc808\ubcbd \ub9c9\uc790, \uc218\ucd9c \ucd1d\ub825\" |date=2019-05-14}}</ref><br>K9A1: 2018\u2013present\n|variants=K10 ARV<br>[[T-155 Firtina]]\n|range=\n|max_range=18 km (M107, HE)<br />30 km (M549A1, HE-RAP)<br />36 km (K310, BB/DP-ICM)<br />40 km (K307, BB/HE)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bemil.chosun.com/nbrd/bbs/view.html?b_bbs_id=10002&pn=5&num=1645|title=[\uad70\uc218\ud488 \ub3cb\ubcf4\uae30] K307 155\u339c \uace1\uc0ac\ud3ec\uc6a9 \ud56d\ub825\uac10\uc18c \uace0\ud3ed\ud0c4|last=BEMIL|access-date=2017-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912233741/http://bemil.chosun.com/nbrd/bbs/view.html?b_bbs_id=10002&pn=5&num=1645|archive-date=2017-09-12|url-status=live}}</ref><br />52 km (K315, HE-RAP)<br />100+ km (GGAM, in development)\n| 1 round/min (Maximum)\n|       length=12 m\n|        width=3.4 m\n|       height=2.73 m\n|       weight= 47 tonnes\n|   suspension= [[Hydropneumatic suspension|hydropneumatic]]\n|   speed= 67 km/h\n|        vehicle_range= 480 km\n|      primary_armament= Hyundai WIA 155 mm 52 caliber\n|    secondary_armament= 12.7 mm (.50 caliber) K6 HMG\n|       armour=\n|       engine= [[MTU Friedrichshafen]] MT 881 Ka-500 [[8-cylinder]] [[water-cooled]] [[diesel engine]]\n| transmission= [[S&T Dynamics]] X1100-5A3\n|         crew=5 (Commander, Driver, Gunner, 2 Loaders)\n|    engine_power=1000 hp\n|        pw_ratio= 21 hp/ton\n\n}}\nThe '''K9 Thunder''' is a South Korean self-propelled [[155 mm]] [[howitzer]] designed and developed by the [[Agency for Defense Development]] and [[Hanwha Defense|Samsung Aerospace Industries]] for the [[Republic of Korea Armed Forces]], and is now manufactured by [[Hanwha Defense]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://defenceandtechnology.com/2018/01/02/norway-buys-k9-thunder-from-hanwha/|title=Norway buys K9 Thunder from Hanwha|date=2 January 2018|work=Defence and Technology|accessdate=31 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731031409/http://defenceandtechnology.com/2018/01/02/norway-buys-k9-thunder-from-hanwha/|archive-date=31 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> K9 howitzers operate in groups with the '''K10''' automatic ammunition resupply vehicle variant. The entire K9 fleet operated by the ROK Armed Forces is now undergoing upgrades to K9A1 standard, and a further development of a K9A2 variant is in process.\n\n==History==\n===Development===\nIn 1980s, the ROK Armed Forces came in need of new artillery system to contest North Korean equipment. The armed forces operated [[M107 self-propelled gun]] and [[M109 howitzer|K55 self-propelled howitzer]]; however, they had shorter firing range compared to [[Koksan (artillery)|M-1978 Koksan]] and were outnumbered by various North Korean artillery. With the success of designing and manufacturing KH-178 and KH-179 towed artillery, and experience gained by license producing K55 (KM109A2), the Ministry of Defense ordered to develop new system that has longer firing range, faster firing rate, and high mobility. The development started in 1989 and was led by the [[Agency for Defense Development]] (ADD) and Samsung Aerospace Industries (now Hanwha Defense).<ref name=\"K9 Developer Interview (1)\">{{cite AV media |date=2015-09-16 |title=[\ucca8\ub2e8\uad6d\uac00\uc758 \ucd08\uc11d, \ubc29\uc704\uc0b0\uc5c5] \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\uc758 \uc0c8 \ucc28\uc6d0\uc744 \uc5f4\ub2e4 - K-9 \ucc9c\ub465(1\ubd80) |language=Korean |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F2tivketAK0 |publisher=\uad6d\ubc29TV}}</ref>\n\nThe ADD first offered upgrades on existing K55, inspired by the United States' M109 Howitzer Improvement Program (HIP), but was rejected by the [[Republic of Korea Army]]. As a result, the ADD determined to create new weapon system and worked on conceptual model till 1991. Early concept requested by the military includes river crossing capability and installation of [[M61 Vulcan]] as anti-air weapon, which were removed due to unnecessity for such long-range weapon.<ref name=\"K9 Developer Interview (1)\"></ref>\n\nIn 1992, the Ground System Division of United Defense LP (now BAE Systems Land and Armaments) invited members of the ADD for its first M109A6 Paladin release ceremony and expressed interest in participating Korea's self-propelled howitzer program by upgrading K55 to Paladin standard, which was rejected by South Korea.<ref name=\"K9 Developer Interview (2)\">{{cite AV media |date=2015-10-15 |title=[\ucca8\ub2e8\uad6d\uac00\uc758 \ucd08\uc11d, \ubc29\uc704\uc0b0\uc5c5] \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\uc758 \uc0c8 \ucc28\uc6d0\uc744 \uc5f4\ub2e4 - K-9 \ucc9c\ub465(2\ubd80) |language=Korean |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lh_CVAm3XNo |publisher=\uad6d\ubc29TV}}</ref>\n\nBy late 1990s, internal review showed localization of 107 out of 235 (45.5%) technologies required to build the artillery. After the review, South Korea decided to continue developing domestic main system, main gun, 155 mm ammunition, fire control system, structure, and autoloader. On the other hand, engine, transmission, and INS were chosen to be imported from foreign partners, and license produce hydropneumatic suspension to boost up localization by 70%. The engineers faced biggest challenge on designing main gun and suspension due to lack of experience; while licensing the K55, its main gun was brought as finished product and suspension was produced under knowledge base from the United States.<ref name=\"K9 Developer Interview (2)\"></ref>\n\nThe turret servo electrohydraulic system is a derive from that of [[K1 88-Tank|K1 MBT]]. Automatic fire control system enabled rapid aiming, faster shooting, and improvement to accuracy.<ref name=\"K9 Developer Interview (3)\">{{cite AV media |date=2015-10-15 |title=[\ucca8\ub2e8\uad6d\uac00\uc758 \ucd08\uc11d, \ubc29\uc704\uc0b0\uc5c5] \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\uc758 \uc0c8 \ucc28\uc6d0\uc744 \uc5f4\ub2e4 - K-9 \ucc9c\ub465(3\ubd80) |language=Korean |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yXvZZ9eowMs |publisher=\uad6d\ubc29TV}}</ref> Originally, Air-Log hydropneumatic suspension, which was being used for British [[AS-90]], was chosen for test for license produce, but failed to absorb shock from much bigger 52 caliber gun. Later, South Korea developed domestic hydropneumatic suspension and sold to Britain.<ref>{{cite web |date=2018-10-04 |title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] K-9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec, \uc601\uad6d \uc218\ucd9c\uae38 \uc624\ub974\ub098 |language=Korean |url=http://www.bizhankook.com/bk/article/16344 |publisher=\ube44\uc988\ud55c\uad6d}}</ref>\n\nA total of two prototypes were built and performed first open trial in 1996. During the test, the prototypes succeeded to fire distance of 40 km and 6 rounds per minutes but failed to fire three rounds in 15 seconds. In 5 December 1997, one of prototypes was damaged by fire after testing 18 rounds in 3 minutes due to failing complete combustion, which resulted death of one researcher among three wounded.<ref name=\"E Daily\">{{cite web |date=2016-01-03 |title=[e-\ubb34\uae30]34\uc138 \uc5f0\uad6c\uc6d0\uc758 \ud76c\uc0dd \ub51b\uace0 \ud0c4\uc0dd\ud55c 'K-9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec' |language=Korean |url=https://www.edaily.co.kr/news/read?newsId=01134886612514112&mediaCodeNo=257 |publisher=E Daily}}</ref> However, damaged prototype's internal system survived the fire, thus was repaired for further use. Two prototypes fired a total of 4,100 rounds and underwent 13,800 km driving test including in extreme temperature conditions.<ref name=\"K9 Developer Interview (3)\"></ref> The localization rate reached 87% by the end of the development.<ref name=\"ROK Defense Media Agency\">{{cite web |date=2015-08-10 |title=\uad70\uc778\uc758 \ubb3c\uac74 \uad70\uc218\ud488 \ub3cb\ubcf4\uae30 <15> K9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\uc640 K10 \ud0c4\uc57d\uc6b4\ubc18\ucc28 |language=Korean |url=https://demaclub.tistory.com/2743 |publisher=Republic of Korea Armed Forces Defense Media Agency}}</ref>\n\nThe contract for the K9 artillery system was awarded to Samsung Aerospace Industries in 22 December 1998. The first vehicle was rolled out in 17 December 1999, and was fielded to the [[Republic of Korea Marine Corps]] in [[Yeonpyeongdo|Yeonpyeong Island]].<ref name=\"E Daily\"></ref><ref name=\"ROK Defense Media Agency\"></ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Khan|first1=Bilal|title=South Korea markets K9 Thunder SP howitzer at Eurosatory 2016|url=http://quwa.org/2016/06/14/south-korea-markets-k9-thunder-sp-howitzer-eurosatory/|website=Quwa|accessdate=18 September 2016|date=14 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918162202/http://quwa.org/2016/06/14/south-korea-markets-k9-thunder-sp-howitzer-eurosatory/|archive-date=18 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Good as New! Finland to Buy Second-Hand Howitzers from South Korea|url=https://sputniknews.com/military/20160704/1042391782/finland-south-korea-howitzer.html|website=Sputnik|accessdate=18 September 2016|date=4 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918160719/https://sputniknews.com/military/20160704/1042391782/finland-south-korea-howitzer.html|archive-date=18 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=S. Korea poised to sign deal to export K9 howitzer to Asian country|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/business/2016/06/15/0501000000AEN20160615007800315.html|website=Yonhap News Agency|accessdate=18 September 2016|date=15 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922085109/http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/business/2016/06/15/0501000000AEN20160615007800315.html|archive-date=22 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Operational history===\nThe K9 Thunder saw its first combat during the [[bombardment of Yeonpyeong]] on November 23, 2010.  Six [[Republic of Korea Marine Corps|ROKMC]] howitzers engaged against the surprise attack from the North Korean artillery.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2010/11/23/skorea-nkorea-fires-artillery-island/|title=North Korea Fires On Island in South, 2 Dead|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Fox News Channel]]|date=2010-11-23|accessdate=2010-11-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101123062722/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2010/11/23/skorea-nkorea-fires-artillery-island/|archive-date=2010-11-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2010/11/113_77022.html |title=Extent of NK damage remains uncertain |newspaper=The Korea Times |date=26 November 2010 |access-date=26 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430013729/http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2010/11/113_77022.html |archive-date=30 April 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Prior to the battle, the howitzers returned from a scheduled firing exercise, using most of the shells stored within the howitzer. In addition, one howitzer experienced a problem during the exercise when a shell became stuck in the barrel, disabling it. Two units received slight damage to their firing control systems during the initial North Korean attack, meaning only three out of the six units were able to counterattack. Eventually, the howitzer that had barrel problems joined the second counterattack after receiving field repairs. The K9s fired only one shell every 1.5 minutes, because the marines had to carry the shells from the armory and manually load the howitzer under heavy fire after exhausting B/L rounds.<ref>[http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=214&aid=0000161667 \"K-9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\uc5d0 \ud3ec\ud0c4 \ud55c \ubc1c\ub3c4 \uc5c6\uc5c8\ub2e4\"], MBC, 27. November 2010. Retrieved October 18, 2015</ref><ref>[http://m.mnd.go.kr/user/boardList.action?command=view&page=21&boardId=I_42745&boardSeq=o_52000000000069&titleId=&siteId=mnd&id=mnd_020500000000 MBC, 'K-9 \ud145 \ube44\uc5b4 \uc788\uc5c8\ub2e4' \ubcf4\ub3c4 \uad00\ub828 \uad6d\ubc29\ubd80 \uc785\uc7a5\uc785\ub2c8\ub2e4] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917164407/http://m.mnd.go.kr/user/boardList.action?command=view&page=21&boardId=I_42745&boardSeq=o_52000000000069&titleId=&siteId=mnd&id=mnd_020500000000 |date=2016-09-17 }}, Ministry of National Defense, 28. November 2010. Retrieved October 18, 2015</ref>\n\n==General characteristics==\nK9 is an indigenous system of an all-welded steel armour construction which is rated to withstand  14.5&nbsp;mm armour piercing rounds, 152&nbsp;mm shell fragments, and anti-personnel mines.<ref name=protection>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/06.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061101045200/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/06.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-11-01|title=K9 Features: Protection|publisher=Samsung Techwin}}</ref> The main armament consists of a 155&nbsp;mm/52 caliber ordnance with a maximum firing range of 40&nbsp;km;<ref name=firepower>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/03.html|title=K9 Features: Superior firepower|publisher=Samsung Techwin|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20061101045148/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/03.html|archivedate=2006-11-01}}</ref> the K307 BB-HE projectile propelled by the K676 top charge has a muzzle velocity of {{convert|928|m/s|ft/s|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"sputnik28june16\">[http://sputniknews.com/asia/20160628/1042052434/south-korean-government-developing-howlitzers.html South Korean Government Develops Remote Controlled Howitzers] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629155537/http://sputniknews.com/asia/20160628/1042052434/south-korean-government-developing-howlitzers.html |date=2016-06-29 }} \u2013 Sputniknews.com, 28 June 2016</ref> State-of-the-art mobility subsystems include a {{convert|1000|hp}} engine with potential for growth and [[hydropneumatic suspension]] unit, a requirement for Korea's rugged mountainous terrain.<ref name=mobility>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/05.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061101045133/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/05.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-11-01|title=K9 Features: Higher Mobility|publisher=Samsung Techwin}}</ref>\n\nIt was designed to give the artillery arm of the [[Republic of Korea Army]] a significant improvement in capability. With a claimed range of 75&nbsp;km, it offers greater mobility, longer range, higher rate of fire, and increased battlefield survivability, as it can quickly be brought into action, open fire, and come out of action. It is less likely to be engaged by counter-battery fire, by relying on [[shoot-and-scoot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/04.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061101045136/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k9_e_new/04.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-11-01|title=K9 Features: Shoot-and-scoot|publisher=Samsung Techwin}}</ref> The unit also supports full [[Chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear|CBRN]] protection.<ref name=protection />\n\nIn June 2016, the [[Defense Acquisition Program Administration]] (DAPA) revealed they were designing a new fully automatic projectile-and-charge loading system that will be retrofitted to the K9, essentially giving it a robotic turret.  The purpose is to reduce the crew needed to operate the vehicle to two in order to mitigate personnel losses expected to be suffered during North Korean attacks.<ref name=\"sputnik28june16\"/>\n\n=== MRSI ===\nThe K9 has the ability to fire its shells in [[Multiple Rounds Simultaneous Impact|MRSI]] mode (Multiple Rounds Simultaneous Impact). In the MRSI mode, the K9 is able to fire three shells in under 15 seconds\u20141 shell every 5 seconds\u2014each in different trajectories so that all of the shells will arrive on their target at the same time.<ref name=firepower/>\n\n===K10 Ammunition Resupply Vehicle (ARV)===\n[[Image:K10 ARV.jpg|thumb|left|K10 Ammunition Resupply Vehicle]]\n\nThe K10 is an automatic ammunition resupply vehicle built on the K9 platform, part of the K9 Thunder system. It shares the same chassis as K9, preserving K9's mobility, and can follow the main artillery battery without lagging behind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k10_e_new/02.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713213611/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k10_e_new/02.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2007-07-13|title=K10 Features: Higher Mobility&Common Chassis|publisher=Samsung Techwin}}</ref> Maximum transfer rate of shells is 12 rounds per minute, and maximum load of shells is 104 rounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/prd/pro_view.asp?pro_uid=1630&cat_uid=68&cat_biz=DEP&cat_lev=A|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218183858/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/prd/pro_view.asp?pro_uid=1630&cat_uid=68&cat_biz=DEP&cat_lev=A|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-02-18|title=K10 ARV|publisher=Samsung Techwin}}</ref>\n\nThe reloading process is fully automated. The reloading is done through a munition bridge on the K10 that extends out to lock itself into a reception hole located at the rear of the K9. This allows the unit to rearm itself under harsh combat conditions without the crew having to expose themselves to the combat environment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k10_e_new/05.html|title=K10 Features: Automatic Control System|publisher=Samsung Techwin|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20071111024607/http://www.samsungtechwin.com/product/features/dep/k10_e_new/05.html|archivedate=2007-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Export==\n\n===Turkey===\nWith technical support from ADD and Samsung Aerospace Industries, Turkey started designing the structure of its self-propelled howitzer based on the K9 in 1999.<ref name=\"DongA\">{{cite web |date=2001-07-20 |title=\uad6d\uc0b0 K9\uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec \uccab \uc218\ucd9c\u2026\ud130\ud0a4\uc5d0 1\uc8703000\uc5b5 \uaddc\ubaa8 |language=Korean |url=http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20010720/7717206/1 |publisher=The Dong-A Ilbo}}</ref> On 4 May 2000, the [[Ministry of National Defense (South Korea)|Ministry of National Defense of the Republic of Korea]] and Turkish Land Forces Command signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU) to supply K9 subsystems till 2011.<ref name=\"ROK Defense Media Agency\"></ref> A formal contract was signed by Samsung Techwin (formerly Samsung Aerospace Industries) and the Embassy of the Republic of Turkey in Seoul on 20 July 2001 worth an initial amount of $60 million\u2014a total deal of $1 billion, including technology transfer and license to produce, for 350 vehicles through 2011.<ref name=\"DongA\"></ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/rok/k9.htm|title=K9 155mm self-propelled howitzer|first=John|last=Pike|access-date=2007-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070320052724/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/rok/k9.htm|archive-date=2007-03-20|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=2014-12-16 |title=\uc0bc\uc131\ud14c\ud06c\uc708, \ud3f4\ub780\ub4dc\uc5d0 'K-9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec' \uc218\ucd9c...2017\ub144\ubd80\ud130 \uc9c1\uc811 \uacf5\uae09 |url=http://www.newsway.co.kr/news/view?tp=1&ud=2014121622273349811 |language=Korean |publisher=News Way}}</ref> The Turkish variant self-propelled howitzer was named [[T-155 Firtina]] and to be assembled in Turkey.\n\n===Australia===\nThe K9 was a contender for Phase 1C of Australia's Land 17 Artillery Replacement Program prior to that phase of the project being cancelled in May 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-05-03/defence-white-paper-now-due-in-2013/3987042|title=Rethink of Defence projects to save billions|publisher=[[ABC Online]]|date=May 3, 2012|accessdate=May 3, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503202448/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-05-03/defence-white-paper-now-due-in-2013/3987042|archive-date=May 3, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn May the 14th, 2019, despite the earlier refusal of Australia to purchase this system in 2012, the Prime Minister of Australia announced that 30 K-9 howitzers and associated support equipment would be acquired for the ADF. No time frame has been given for the purchase. <ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Australian Army to receive massive boost in firepower with 155mm SPH purchase|last=|first=|date=June 2019|work=Australian Pacific Defense Reporter|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===India===\nHanwha Techwin joined hand with Indian conglomerate [[Larsen and Toubro|Larsen and Toubro Limited]] to supply 100 K9-T guns (known in India as K-9 Vajra)for the Indian Army Howitzer competition.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/indl-goods-/-svs/engineering/lt-samsung-join-hands-for-indias-howitzer-artillery/articleshow/12457051.cms | work=The Times Of India | title=L&T, Samsung join hands for India's Howitzer artillery | date=29 March 2012 | access-date=30 March 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222153015/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/indl-goods-/-svs/engineering/lt-samsung-join-hands-for-indias-howitzer-artillery/articleshow/12457051.cms | archive-date=22 December 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, [[Larsen & Toubro|Larsen and Toubro]] emerged as the finalist for a US$800 million contract to supply 100 self-propelled howitzers to the [[Indian Army]].<ref>{{cite web|title = India's Newest Gun: Fast and Deadly|url = http://thediplomat.com/2015/10/indias-newest-gun-fast-and-deadly/|website = The Diplomat|accessdate = 2015-10-09|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151011181059/http://thediplomat.com/2015/10/indias-newest-gun-fast-and-deadly/|archive-date = 2015-10-11|url-status = live}}</ref> The vehicle is the K9 VAJRA-T, a variant of the K9 specially designed for operation in the desert areas bordering Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Global|first=IndraStra|title=Indian Army Inducts Two New Artillery Systems|url=https://www.indrastra.com/2018/11/Indian-Army-s-New-Artillery-Systems-004-11-2018-0021.html|journal=IndraStra|issn=2381-3652|access-date=2018-11-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118164856/https://www.indrastra.com/2018/11/Indian-Army-s-New-Artillery-Systems-004-11-2018-0021.html|archive-date=2018-11-18|url-status=live}}</ref>  India has not had any new artillery pieces since the 1980s and several rounds of modernization plans since 1999 had failed to select a gun.  India has been at a distinct disadvantage against Pakistan  regarding [[self propelled artillery]] since the United States supplied them with 115 [[M109 Paladin|M109A5]] cannon in 2009.  The final process to sign the contract could take up to six more months.<ref>[http://armyrecognition.com/september_2015_global_defense_security_news_uk/larsen_and_toubro_selected_to_supply_100_self-propelled_howitzers_to_the_indian_army_23009152.html Larsen and Toubro selected to supply 100 self-propelled howitzers to the Indian Army] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002133151/http://www.armyrecognition.com/september_2015_global_defense_security_news_uk/larsen_and_toubro_selected_to_supply_100_self-propelled_howitzers_to_the_indian_army_23009152.html |date=2015-10-02 }} \u2013 Armyrecognition.com, 30 September 2015</ref>\nIn 2017, Indian Defence Ministry signed the contract with private sector defence manufacturer Larsen & Toubro and by January 2020, the company was able to deliver more than half of K-9 Vajra guns in the Indian army ahead of schedule.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.defencestar.in/defence-industry/defence-news-india-rajnath-singh-flags-off-larsen-troubo-hanwha-defense-hanwha-techwins-51st-homemade-self-propelled-howitzer-gun-k9-vajra-ahead-of-schedule/?amp |title = Defence minister Rajnath Singh flags off 51st homemade K9 Vajra Gun ahead of schedule |newspaper = Defence Star|date = 16 January 2020|}}</ref>\n\n===Finland===\nIn July 2016, the Finnish Ministry of Defence announced that an undisclosed number of used K9s have been selected to be acquired from the Republic of Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defmin.fi/ajankohtaista/tiedotteet/maavoimien_tykistokaluston_uusiminen_etenee.7898.news|title=Maavoimien tykist\u00f6kaluston uusiminen etenee|access-date=2016-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705051603/http://www.defmin.fi/ajankohtaista/tiedotteet/maavoimien_tykistokaluston_uusiminen_etenee.7898.news|archive-date=2016-07-05|url-status=live}}</ref> The acquisition is claimed to be biggest of the decade for the Land Forces, whose both mobile and towed artillery face mass outdating in the 2020s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reservilainen.fi/uutiset/maavoimien_etsikkoaikaa_eletaan_parhaillaan|title=Maavoimien etsikkoaikaa elet\u00e4\u00e4n parhaillaan|date=26 February 2016|access-date=1 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608153559/http://www.reservilainen.fi/uutiset/maavoimien_etsikkoaikaa_eletaan_parhaillaan|archive-date=8 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2017, the Ministry of Defence announced that Finland will acquire 48 used K9s over a period of seven years starting in 2018, with conscript training on the equipment commencing in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/3-9466486|title=Suomi ostaa 48 k\u00e4ytetty\u00e4 panssarihaupitsia Etel\u00e4-Koreasta|website=Yle Uutiset|access-date=2017-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217152142/http://yle.fi/uutiset/3-9466486|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Estonia===\nEstonia has also confirmed its decision to purchase K9 Thunders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreadefence.net/detail.php?number=3887&thread=22r06|title=\uc5d0\uc2a4\ud1a0\ub2c8\uc544, K-9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec \ub3c4\uc785 \uacb0\uc815 - \uc790\uc8fc\uad6d\ubc29\ub124\ud2b8\uc6cc\ud06c-|website=koreadefence.net|access-date=2017-02-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204170833/http://koreadefence.net/detail.php?number=3887&thread=22r06|archive-date=2017-02-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> According to other sources Estonia is teaming up with Finland in the procurement of the K9 and will order 12 howitzers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/baltic_states/?doc=127392|title=Estonia to team up with Finland to procure K9 Thunder howitzers|first=The Baltic Course - \u0411\u0430\u043b\u0442\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439|last=\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441|access-date=2017-02-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203191818/http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/baltic_states/?doc=127392|archive-date=2017-02-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\nAt the end of June 2018 Rauno Sirk, the director of the Estonian military procurement agency, said in a statement, that Estonia will buy K9 Thunder howitzers, the first of the twelve will arrive in the country in 2020.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://estonianworld.com/security/estonia-to-buy-artillery-from-south-korea-for-e46-million/|title=Estonia to buy artillery from South Korea for \u20ac46 million|last=Hankewitz|first=Sten|date=June 26, 2018|work=Estonian World|access-date=June 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628055638/http://estonianworld.com/security/estonia-to-buy-artillery-from-south-korea-for-e46-million/|archive-date=June 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Norway===\nOn August 24, 2016 the Norwegian Defence Materiel Agency published their intention to continue negotiations with [[Hanwha Techwin]] and Swiss [[RUAG]], which has offered their [[M109 howitzer#M109 \"KAWEST\"|M109 \"KAWEST\"]] upgrade. At the same time, the NDMA said that negotiations concerning the [[Krauss-Maffei Wegmann|KMW]] made [[Panzerhaubitze 2000]] and the [[CAESAR self-propelled howitzer|Nexter Caesar]] had been put \"on hold\". Unnamed sources in the Norwegian Army had previously stated that the K9 was a leading candidate in the competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tu.no/artikler/haeren-ligger-an-til-a-fa-koreanske-kanoner/350619 |author=Per Erlien Dall\u00f8kken |title=H\u00e6ren ligger an til \u00e5 f\u00e5 koreanske kanoner |trans-title=The army is likely to get Korean cannons |language=Norwegian |publisher=tu.no |date=August 24, 2016 |access-date=August 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825165759/http://www.tu.no/artikler/haeren-ligger-an-til-a-fa-koreanske-kanoner/350619 |archive-date=August 25, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn December 20, 2017, a contract was signed between Hanwha Land Systems and Norwegian Defence Materiel Agency for \u20a9245.2 billion to supply 24 K9 Thunder and 6 K10 ARV by 2020. K9 outperformed competitors in various weather and terrain conditions according Norwegian military officials during trials.<ref>{{cite web |date=2017-12-21 |title=\ud55c\ud654, K-9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\u00b7K10 \uc7a5\uac11\ucc28 \ub178\ub974\uc6e8\uc774 \uc218\ucd9c\u20262452\uc5b5\uc6d0 \uaddc\ubaa8 |language=Korean |url=https://biz.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2017/12/21/2017122100835.html |publisher=Chosun Ilbo}}</ref>\n\nNorwegian variant was named as K9 VIDAR (Versatile InDirect ARtillery system), and is based on K9 PIP configuration. It uses Norwegian ODIN fire support system and radio communication systems.<ref name=\"Defense Times\">{{cite web |date=2019-10-05 |title=K9A1 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec\uc758 \uc2dc\uc791 |language=Korean |url=http://defensetimes.kr/article/view.php?&ss[fc]=4&bbs_id=DefenceTimes_news&doc_num=1754 |publisher=Defense Times}}</ref>\n\n===Egypt===\nIn April 2017, it was reported that [[Hanwha Techwin]] was in negotiations with Egypt to export its K9 Thunder self-propelled howitzer.<ref name=\"businesspost.co.kr\">{{cite news |url= http://www.businesspost.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=46398 |title= Hanwha Techwin to improve earnings due to K9 Thunder exports |date= 5 April 2017 |language= korean |access-date= 24 August 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170825020136/http://www.businesspost.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=46398 |archive-date= 25 August 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref> The K9 Thunder is one of the contenders for supplying Egypt with new artillery systems, other howitzers competing with the K9 include those from Russia, South Africa and France, specifically the [[CAESAR self-propelled howitzer]].<ref name=\"defenceweb.co.za\">{{cite news |url= http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48661 |title= Egypt evaluating new artillery |date= 24 July 2017 |language= english |access-date= 24 August 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170825020846/http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48661 |archive-date= 25 August 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref> South Korea's K9 self-propelled howitzer began performance evaluation tests in Egypt at the end of July 2017. A K9 howitzer arrived in Egypt earlier that month for test-firing at a range located west of Cairo. Egypt plans to complete performance evaluations of the howitzer by the end of the year and sign a contract in early 2018.<ref name=\"koreatimes.co.kr\">{{cite news |url= http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2017/07/205_233677.html |title= Egypt interested in buying K-9 howitzer |date= 26 July 2017 |language= english |access-date= 24 August 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170824221609/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2017/07/205_233677.html |archive-date= 24 August 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Variants and upgrades==\n* '''XK9:''' Experimental prototype.\n* '''K9 Thunder:''' First-production variant.\n** '''AS9 \"Aussie Thunder\":''' Offered Australian variant of the K9 in 2012.\n** '''AS9 \"Huntsman\":''' Offered Australian variant of the K9 in 2019 inline with Hanhwa's proposal of the AS21 \"Redback\" IFV offering for LAND 400 Phase 3.\n** '''K9 VAJRA-T (Lightning):''' Indian variant of the K9. Manufactured by [[Larsen & Toubro]] under license, consisting 50% component (by value) including 14 major sub-systems developed by Indian companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/defence/indian-army-gets-more-firepower-rajnath-singh-flags-off-51st-k9-vajra-t-gun/1825430/|title=Indian army gets more firepower! Rajnath Singh flags off 51st K9 VAJRA-T Gun|date=2020-01-16|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> It has been customised as per [[Desert|desert conditions]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/army-inducts-new-artillery-guns-after-three-decades/article25452662.ece|title=Army fire power gets booster shot|last=Peri|first=Dinakar|date=2018-11-09|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-20|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n** '''K9FIN Moukari (Sledge-hammer):''' Finnish variant of the K9 with APU.\n* '''K9A1:''' First enhanced variant. Added APU, GPS navigator, driver's thermal periscope, rear surveillance camera, and improved fire control system. A1 upgrade also allows to use new extended range ammunition, increasing its firing range.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hanwhatechwin.co.kr/product/product_05_01.asp|title=\ud654\ub825\uccb4\uacc4 : \ud55c\ud654\ud14c\ud06c\uc708 \uc81c\ud488\uc18c\uac1c|website=www.hanwhatechwin.co.kr|access-date=2017-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707104914/http://hanwhatechwin.co.kr/product/product_05_01.asp|archive-date=2017-07-07|url-status=live}}</ref> First K9A1 rolled out and is in service of the [[Republic of Korea Army]] since 2018. All K-9 operated by the [[Republic of Korea Armed Forces|ROK Armed Forces]] will be upgraded to A1 by 2030.\n** '''K9 VIDAR (Versatile InDirect ARtillery):''' Norwegian variant of the K9A1.\n* '''K9A2:''' Under development. A2 variant will apply auto-loader, increased firing rate, 3 operators, remote control directly from BTCS.\n* '''K10:''' Ammunition resupply vehicle using the K9 chassis.\n** '''AS10:''' Offered Australian variant of the K10.\n* '''[[T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na]]:''' Turkish version with modified turret, chassis, electronics and navigation system.\n* '''[[AHS Krab]]:''' Polish self-propelled howitzer, using the K9 chassis and [[AS-90]] turret.\n\n==Operators==\n[[File:K9 operators.png|thumb|400px|Map with K9 operators in blue and parts or subsystems operators in cyan]]\n[[File:Lippujuhlan p\u00e4iv\u00e4n 2017 paraati 104 K9 Thunder.JPG|thumb|K9 in Finnish Defence Forces' Flag Day parade]]\n[[File:AHS Krab in Kyiv 01.jpg|thumb|Polish AHS Krab using K9 chassis at Arms and Security 2017 exhibition]]\n\n===Current operators===\n; {{flag|Estonia}}\n\nOn 26 June 2018, Estonia signed an agreement with South Korea for the procurement of 12 K9 self-propelled howitzers, with a reported option for 12 additional artillery systems. The agreement also includes training, maintenance and spare parts. Deliveries to start in 2020. The purchase of additional 6 howitzers was announced in October 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kund |first1=Oliver |title=Uus tulej\u00f5ud lisab kaitsev\u00e4ele rammu |url=https://www.postimees.ee/4509552/uus-tulejoud-lisab-kaitsevaele-rammu |website=www.postimees.ee |accessdate=2018-06-26 |language=et |date=2018-06-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626015751/https://www.postimees.ee/4509552/uus-tulejoud-lisab-kaitsevaele-rammu |archive-date=2018-06-26 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Vahtla |first1=Aili |title=Gallery: Estonia, South Korea sign artillery purchase agreement |url=https://news.err.ee/842341/gallery-estonia-south-korea-sign-artillery-purchase-agreement |website=news.err.ee |publisher=ERR |accessdate=2018-06-26 |date=2018-06-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626164043/https://news.err.ee/842341/gallery-estonia-south-korea-sign-artillery-purchase-agreement |archive-date=2018-06-26 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.err.ee/987854/paper-more-military-equipment-to-be-bought-from-south-korea|title=Paper: More military equipment to be bought from South Korea|last=ERR|first=ERR News {{!}}|date=2019-10-03|website=ERR|language=en|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref>\n\n;{{flag|Finland}}\nThe [[Finnish Defence Forces]] announced on 17 February 2017 that they will buy 48 used K9s, with the deliveries starting in 2017.<ref>[http://www.iltasanomat.fi/kotimaa/art-2000005092507.html Suomi hankkii 48 k\u00e4ytetty\u00e4 panssarihaupitsia Etel\u00e4-Koreasta] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217144716/http://www.iltasanomat.fi/kotimaa/art-2000005092507.html |date=2017-02-17 }} iltasanomat.fi, February 17, 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Larrinaga, de |first1=Nicholas |title=Finland buys K9 howitzers from South Korea |url=http://www.janes.com/article/67827/ |website=IHS Jane's 360 |accessdate=18 February 2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170218122710/http://www.janes.com/article/67827/finland-buys-k9-howitzers-from-south-korea |archivedate=18 February 2017 |location=London |date=18 February 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n;{{flag|India}}\n10 units were brought from South Korea and assembled by L&T in India, were to be handed over to the Indian Army during Defexpo 2018. Rest of the 100 will be produced by [[Larsen & Toubro]] for the Indian Army.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/article/55127/k9-selected-for-indian-army-sph-requirement|title=K9 selected for Indian Army SPH requirement \u2013 IHS Jane's 360|access-date=2015-10-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009203112/http://www.janes.com/article/55127/k9-selected-for-indian-army-sph-requirement|archive-date=2015-10-09|url-status=live}}</ref> The first batch of 25 units was delivered to the Indian Army in May 2018. As on 17 January 2019 51 units have been delivered by the local manufacturer, L&T.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/rajnath-singh-flags-off-51st-k-9-vajra-at-l-t-gun-making-facility-11579175814226.html|title=First batch of K9 Vajra-T 155mm self-propelled howitzers delivered to Indian army|last=|first=|date=9 May 2018|website=Army Recognition|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512201516/http://www.armyrecognition.com/may_2018_global_defense_security_army_news_industry/first_batch_of_k9_vajra-t_self-propelled_155mm_howitzers_delivered_to_indian_army.html|archivedate=12 May 2018|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n;{{flag|Republic of Korea}}\nTotal production of 1,136 K9s and 179 K10s were fielded by 2019. All K9 will be upgraded to K9A1 by 2030, and K9A2 variant development is ongoing.\n;{{flag|Norway}}\nNorway has selected the K9 Thunder in its bid to replace the [[M109 howitzer|M109A3GNM]] SPHs that have been in service since the 1960s. 24 K9 and 6 K10 have been purchased, with an option for another 24 K9 and additional K10. Deliveries are scheduled to begin in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yeo|first1=Mike|title=Norway orders K9 howitzers in latest win for South Korean arms industry|url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2017/12/20/norway-orders-k9-howitzers-in-latest-win-for-south-korean-arms-industry/|website=Defense News|accessdate=26 December 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171220162835/https://www.defensenews.com/land/2017/12/20/norway-orders-k9-howitzers-in-latest-win-for-south-korean-arms-industry/|archivedate=20 December 2017|location=Melbourne|date=20 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Grevatt|first1=Jon|title=Hanwha confirms K9 export to Norway|url=http://www.janes.com/article/76637|website=IHS Jane's 360|accessdate=26 December 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171226214449/http://www.janes.com/article/76637/hanwha-confirms-k9-export-to-norway|archivedate=26 December 2017|date=22 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Erlien Dall\u00f8kken|first1=Per|title=N\u00e5 er det klart: Dette blir Norges nye artilleri|url=https://www.tu.no/artikler/na-er-det-klart-dette-blir-norges-nye-artilleri/414850|website=Teknisk Ukeblad|accessdate=26 December 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171226213704/https://www.tu.no/artikler/na-er-det-klart-dette-blir-norges-nye-artilleri/414850|archivedate=26 December 2017|language=Norwegian|date=20 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n;{{flag|Poland}}\n120 K9 chassis will be produced as part of the [[AHS Krab]] program.<ref>[http://www.armyrecognition.com/december_2014_global_defense_security_news_uk/samsung_techwin_signs_deal_for_delivering_120_k9_thunder_self-propelled_howitzers_to_poland.html Samsung Techwin signs deal for delivering 120 K9 Thunder self-propelled howitzers to Poland] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923180802/http://www.armyrecognition.com/december_2014_global_defense_security_news_uk/samsung_techwin_signs_deal_for_delivering_120_k9_thunder_self-propelled_howitzers_to_poland.html |date=2015-09-23 }} armyrecognition.com, December 17, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Grevatt|first1=Jon|title=South Korea's Hanwha secures Polish K9 export|url=http://www.janes.com/article/66310/|website=IHS Jane's 360|accessdate=16 December 2016|location=Bangkok|date=16 December 2016}}</ref>\n;{{flag|Turkey}}\nTurkey is guaranteed to build 350 [[T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na]] under license for 1.6 million USD per vehicle including right to export and modify.<ref>https://m.dcinside.com/board/war/275137</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.joins.com/article/23542876 |website=Korea Joongang Daily |title=\uc120\uc9c4\uad6d\uc774 \uc7a5\uc545\ud55c \ubb34\uae30\uc2dc\uc7a5, \uac00\uaca9 \uacbd\uc7c1\ub825\uc73c\ub85c \ub6ab\ub294\ub2e4 |date=2019-08-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news2day.co.kr/128214 |website=News2Day |title=[\uc218\ucd9c \ubc29\uc0b0 \uba85\ud488](2) \ud55c\ud654\ub514\ud39c\uc2a4\uc758 'K9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec' 2\uc870\uc6d0 \uaddc\ubaa8 \uc218\ucd9c |date=2019-05-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://quwa.org/2016/06/14/south-korea-markets-k9-thunder-sp-howitzer-eurosatory/ |website=Quwa Defence News & Analysis Group |title=SOUTH KOREA MARKETS K9 THUNDER SP HOWITZER AT EUROSATORY 2016 |date=2016-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.g-enews.com/view.php?ud=20190531102258736c63242687e_1&md=20190531130605_M |website=Global Economics |title=[\uae00\ub85c\ubc8c-Biz 24] \ud130\ud0a4, \ud55c\uad6d \uba85\ud488\ubb34\uae30 'K9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec' \ubcc0\ud615\ud55c 'T-155 \ud504\ub974\ud2b8\ub098' \uac1c\ubc1c...\ud615\uc81c\uc758 \ub09c? |date=2019-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.armyrecognition.com/turkey_army_artillery_vehicle_weapon_systems_uk/t-155_firtina_155mm_self-propelled_howitzer_technical_data_sheet_specifications_pictures_video.html |website=Army Recognition |title=T-155 Firtina 155mm 52 caliber self-propelled howitzer |date=2018-09-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/meet-k-9-thunder-south-koreas-giant-artillery-gun-aimed-north-korea-91431 |website=National Interest |title=Meet the K-9 Thunder: South Korea's Giant Artillery Gun (Aimed at North Korea) |date=2019-10-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/defense/2018/01/27/domestically-produced-defense-systems-deployed-in-afrin-offensive |website=Daily Sabah |title=Domestically produced defense systems deployed in Afrin offensive|date=2018-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-hit-syria-with-s-korean-designed-howitzers-31653 |website=Hurriyet Daily News |title=Turkey hit Syria with S. Korean-designed howitzers |date=2012-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hanwha-defense.co.kr/kor/products/firearms-system-k9.do |website=Hanwha Defense |title=K9 \uc790\uc8fc\ud3ec}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defensenews.com/global/europe/2014/12/16/south-korea-to-export-k-9-howitzers-to-poland/ |website=Defense News |title=South Korea To Export K-9 Howitzers to Poland |date=2014-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bulgarianmilitary.com/2019/12/07/the-norwegian-armed-forces-received-self-propelled-howitzers-k9/ |website=BulgarianMilitary.com |title=The Norwegian Armed Forces received self-propelled howitzers K9 |date=2019-12-07}}</ref> The first 8 units were built in South Korea.\n[[File:T-155F\u0131rt\u0131na (1).jpg|thumb|Turkish variant [[T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na]]]]\n\n===Potential operators===\n;{{flag|Egypt}}\nThe [[Egyptian Army]] is currently performing evaluation tests for the K9 howitzer in Egypt. Final contract is expected to be signed in early 2018.<ref name=\"koreatimes.co.kr\"/>\n\n== Related developments ==\n* [[AHS Krab]]\n* [[T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[M109 howitzer|M109]]\n* [[AS-90]]\n* [[PzH 2000]]\n* [[SSPH1]]\n* [[Type 99 155 mm Self-propelled howitzer|Type 99]]\n* [[PLZ-05]]\n* [[2S35 Koalitsiya-SV]]\n* [[Bhim self-propelled howitzer|Bhim]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|K9 Thunder}}\n* [https://www.hanwha-defense.co.kr/eng/products/firearms-system-k9.do K9 Thunder Self-propelled Howitzer - Artillery Systems - Hanwha Defense]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/rok/k9.htm Global Security on K-9 Howitzer]\n* [http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4425860 Defense News]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n[[Category:Self-propelled artillery of South Korea]]\n[[Category:155 mm artillery]]\n[[Category:Tracked self-propelled howitzers]]\n[[Category:Self-propelled howitzers]]\n", "name_user": "Lakun.patra", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1.6 million USD \u2192  US$1.6 million", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K9_Thunder"}
{"title_page": "K. K. Anand", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=June 2013}}\n{{COI|2=see [[Special:PermanentLink/543004966]]|date=May 2013}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Dr. (Prof) K. K. Anand.jpg\n| image_size =  200px \n| name        = Dr. (Prof) K. K. Anand\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  =\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation     =\n| main interests = \n| spouse      = \n| url         = \n}}\n\nDr. (Prof.) Kewal Krishan Anand (22 June 1930 - 22 January 2013) was a management consultant in India. After completing his post-doctoral training at Harvard University in the US, he returned to India as founding Professor at IIM Ahmedabad from 1965 to 1969. Thereafter, he set up the HR department at Larsen & Toubro,<ref>{{Cite journal | url = https://books.google.com/?id=qCZTEPI52pkC&pg=PR13 | title = Performance Management and Appraisal Systems: HR Tools for Global Competitiveness | isbn = 9780761998464 | author1 = Rao | first1 = T. V. | date = 2004-05-15}}</ref> a large industrial group in India,  as founding Chief Organization Manager from 1969 to 1973. Finally, he founded his consulting firm Anand & Associates in Bombay and was a management thinker in India from the 1970s till 2000 advising large corporations, family businesses and non-profit organizations.\n\nHe was very active in management associations and organized conferences on leadership, management and quality. He authored 4 management books.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nDr. KK Anand was born in Gujranwala in pre-partition India. He was the eldest of 8 children, 4 boys and 4 girls. He educated himself and most of his family as the eldest sibling of a refugee family in Delhi.\n\n== Education ==\n\nAfter completion of his Doctorate in Psychology from Punjab University, he pursued his Post-Doctoral studies at The University of Tennessee and the Harvard Business School. He was a Fulbright Scholar and recipient of the Ford Foundation Fellowship.\n\n== Career ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable \"\n|-\n!Position Held\n!Where\n!Years\n|-\n| Civilian Psychologist of the Officers Selection Board || Indian Army and Indian Navy || 1958\u20131962\n|-\n| Post Doctoral Training in the US || [[Harvard University]] and [[University of Tennessee]] || 1962-1965\n|-\n| Founding Professor of Human Behaviour in Organizations; and Chairman of Admissions Committee || [[Indian Institute of Management Ahmedabad]] || 1965-1969\n|-\n| Founding Chief Personnel & Organization Manager || [[Larsen & Toubro]] || 1969-1973\n|-\n| Management Consultant. Founder and Chairman || Anand & Associates and KK Anand Consultants Pvt. Ltd. || 1973-2000||\n|}\n\nIn a license-raj era in India, he focussed on three core areas:\n\n# professional management as a science that all organizations, especially family run businesses, must embrace for long-term success;\n# leadership and human resource management as key to building successful corporations;\n# quality management systems <ref>{{cite web|url=http://iso9001-2008awareness.blogspot.in/2012/10/understanding-total-quality-management.html |title=Quality Concepts and ISO 9001:2008 QMS Awareness: Understanding Total Quality Management |publisher=Iso9001-2008awareness.blogspot.in |date=2012-10-18 |accessdate=2013-05-15}}</ref> to make India compete globally and domestically against international corporations.\n\nAnand & Associates became an Indian management consulting firm doing work in the above areas. Dr Anand and his team of consultants advised some of India's large corporate groups such as Godrej & Boyce,<ref>http://archives.godrej.com/assets/pdf/The_Archives_Times_Aug2012.pdf</ref> MUSCO (Mahindra Group), Anand Group, L&T, MTDC, Maharashtra Textile Corporation, Aptech, Hindustan PhotoFilms, Century Rayon (BK Birla Group), Jaslok Hospital. He also advised Bank of Baroda, Blue Star, Cable Corporation of India, Engineers India, Emco, Fedders Lyoyd, Fiberglass Pilkington, Hindustan Aeronautics Ltd., Indian Oil Corporation, Metal Box, Punjab National Bank, Richardson Hindustan, Swadeshi Polytex, Tube Investments India and many more. He advised Air India, and came away a firm believer that Government should not run business.\n\n== Board Positions ==\n\nDuring his active life, Dr Anand was an Independent Director on the Board of Directors of the following companies: \n \n* Chairman for Asia, Abu Dhabi Commercial Bank \n* Indfoss (erstwhile Danfoss) \n* Aptech \n* Hexaware Technologies <ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/hexaware-technologies-ltd/infocompanyhistory/companyid-4784.cms |title=Hexaware TechnologiesHistory &#124; Hexaware Technologies Ltd Company History & Profile |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15}}</ref>\n* Gabriel Ltd \n* Kores India \n* Bank of Madura Ltd. \n* Matheson Bosanquet & Co \n* Maharashtra Tourism & Development Corporation\n* Renaissance Worldwide India\n* Cedar\n\n== Institutions ==\n\nDr Anand invested his time also in Associations focussed on management:\n\n* President, Management Consultants Association of India (now the Institute of Management Consultants of India) <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imcindia.co.in/IMCIPresentation2008.ppt |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-03-09 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729025253/http://www.imcindia.co.in/IMCIPresentation2008.ppt |archivedate=2010-07-29 |df= }}</ref>\n* Chairman, Special Council for Quality, All India Manufacturer's Organization \n* Founder & later President, National Centre for Quality Management <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncqm.com/oraganisation.html |title=National Centre for Quality Management |publisher=Ncqm.com |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15}}</ref>\n* President, Industrial Relations Institute of India \n* Convenor, Conceptual Forum: Bombay Management Association <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bma-india.com/concep_forum.aspx |title=Bombay Management Association |publisher=Bma-india.com |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15}}</ref>\n* President, Indian Hospital Association \n* Honorary Secretary, National Kidney Foundation of India <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nkfi.in/committees.htm |title=National Kidney Foundation (India) |publisher=Nkfi.in |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15}}</ref>\n\nOther Associations<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isabs.org/memo.php |title=:: Indian Society for Applied Behavioural Science :: |publisher=Isabs.org |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15}}</ref>\n\n* Chairman, Hospital Services Committee, Bombay Management Association\n* Member, Panel of Experts, Voluntary Health Association of India\n* Convener of 8 National Conferences on Hospital & Health Care Management\n* Chairman, Management Education Committee, All India Management Association\n* Executive Committee member, Indian Institute of Public Administration\n\n== Books ==\n\nDr Anand authored 4 books:\n\n* Management Consultancy - A User Guide:<ref>http://books.rediff.com/book/management-consultancy:-a-users-guide/9780706977660</ref> Management Consultancy was a new profession compared to the Accountants, Lawyers etc. The book was addressed to Indian companies on why and how a company can benefit from a management consultant. Foreword by SS Nadkarni, Chairman National Stock Exchange of India and Chairman of IDBI;\n* Hospital Management - A New Perspective:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiabookmart.com/Book_detail.asp?Bid=Hospital+Management&catId=8125900841 |title=India Book Mart |publisher=India Book Mart |date= |accessdate=2013-05-15 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130629122149/http://www.indiabookmart.com/Book_detail.asp?Bid=Hospital+Management&catId=8125900841 |archivedate=2013-06-29 |df= }}</ref> Pre-90s, many hospitals were run by Doctors. Dr Anand believed that Indian hospitals had to bring in management trained leaders to run hospitals, instead of Doctors. This book explained why this change was necessary and how this could be brought about. Foreword by Dr Prathap C Reddy, Chairman, Apollo Group of Hospitals; \n* Quality Management Handbook:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Quality-Management-Handbook-K-K-Anand/dp/070698918X/ref=sr_1_11?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1358102170&sr=1-11 |title=Quality Management Handbook: Amazon.co.uk: K.K. Anand: Books |publisher=Amazon.co.uk |date=1998-11-15 |accessdate=2013-05-15}}</ref> Pre-90s, India was considered as a country that produced poor quality goods that could not compete globally. Dr Anand invited the Japanese quality guru, Dr Genichi Taguchi, to India and advised and wrote about the importance of quality management systems;\n* Human Resource Management: Dr Anand believed that people make organizations successful. This book covered the areas of industrial relations, leadership development and HR systems.\n* Other Publications: - Managing Health Institutions - Hospital Management Case Studies - Studies in Hospital Management\n\nVisiting Faculty\n\nDr. Anand taught as visiting faculty and also gave guest lectures across many educational institutions:\n* Indian Institute of Management, Ahemdabad;\n* Indian Institute of Technology, Bombay;\n* J. Bajaj Institute of Management, Bombay.\n\n== Family ==\n\nDr Anand's professional success was built on a family support system. Dr and Mrs Anand's three children and seven grandchildren all live in India in Mumbai and New Delhi. The eldest, Sanjiv Anand, founded and runs a management consulting firm, Cedar Consulting, advising global and Indian clients. Their daughter, Seema Singh, is a designer and homemaker. The youngest, Sumeet Anand, after 15 years in industry and a CEO, has set up an advisory and ventures firm, IndSight Growth Partners.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anand, K. K.}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=June 2013}}\n{{COI|2=see [[Special:PermanentLink/543004966]]|date=May 2013}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Dr. (Prof) K. K. Anand.jpg\n| image_size =  200