SR}}||'''Status: In service.''' Manufactured at Ordnance Factory Tiruchirappalli, used in small numbers.\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" |Indigenous Weapons\n|-\n|[[Vidhwansak]]\n|\n\n|[[Anti-materiel rifle]]||12.7\u00d7108mm, 20x82mm||{{IND}}||'''Status: In service.'''\n|-\n|[[INSAS|1B1 INSAS]]\n|[[File:INSAS Black.JPG|INSAS 1B1 Assault Rifle|150px]]||[[Assault rifle]]||[[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]]||{{IND}}||'''Status: In service/ To be replaced'''. Standard assault rifle of the Indian Army. To be replaced by [[AK-203]]\n|-\n|[[INSAS rifle#Variant & Developments|INSAS LMG]]\n|[[File:INSAS-LMG.jpg|INSAS LMG|150px]]||[[Light machine gun]]||[[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]]||{{IND}}||'''Status: In service(To be phased Out)'''  . Standard Squad Automatic Weapon (SAW) of the Indian Army. Light machine gun derivative of the INSAS assault rifle. Contract signed in 2020 to replace a large amount INSAS LMG with [[IMI Negev]]\n|-\n|[[Bren light machine gun|GUN MACHINE 7.62MM IA]]\n|[[File:Keeping Watch.jpg|Machinegun 7.62 MM IA|150px]]\n|[[Light machine gun|Light machine Gun]]\n|[[7.62\u00d751mm NATO|7.62 x 51 mm NATO]]\n|{{flag|India|3}}\n|'''Status: In Service (Being Phased out)''' Principal LMG for the Army, variant of British Bren Gun and Czech ZB 26, re chambered to NATO round. To be replaced by [[IMI Negev]] as per contract signed in 2020\n|}\n\n===Explosives, Rockets, and Mortars===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Name \n!Image\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Type \n! style=\"width:5%;\"| Quantity \n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Origin \n! Notes\n|-\n| Grenade 36mm \n| ||[[Hand Grenade]] ||  || {{Flagu|India}} || Fragmentation grenade which can be hand-thrown or rifle-launched from 1A SLR.\n|-\n| Multi Mode Grenade Shivalik \n|||[[Hand grenade]] || 1.8 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20100722/main6.htm |title=Army orders 1 million pieces of grenade developed by DRDO's Chandigarh lab |publisher=Tribuneindia.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-11|last=Mohar|first=Vijay}}</ref> || {{Flagu|India}} ||'''Status: In service.'''Standard grenade of the Indian Army. This modular grenade is available in Hand mode offensive, hand mode defensive and rifle mode. Types can be interchanged by changing outer sleeve.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ofbindia.gov.in/products/data/ammunition/gr/25.htm|title=Ordnance Factory Board|publisher=|accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref><ref>http://164.100.119.31/sites/default/files/pdf/Vol.7%20No.5%20October%201999.pdf{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[GP-25]] \n|[[File:GP-25 at Tula State Museum of Weapons.jpg|none|thumb]]||[[Grenade launcher]] (40mm) || || {{USSR}} ||Attached to AKM and AK-103 assault rifles.\n|-\n| Multi Grenade Launcher 40mm \n|\n|[[Grenade launcher]] (40mm) \n||\n| {{Flagu|India}} || '''Status: In service.'''Semiautomatic six shot 40mm x 46mm low velocity grenade launcher. Manufactured at [[Ordnance Factory Tiruchirappalli]]. *[http://ofbindia.gov.in/products/data/weapons/wmc/7.htm]\n|-\n| [[AGS-17|AGS-17 Plamya]] \n|[[File:30-\u043c\u043c \u0430\u0432\u0442\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043c\u0435\u0442 \u0410\u0413\u0421-17 \u041f\u043b\u0430\u043c\u044f.jpg|none|thumb]]||[[Automatic grenade launcher]] (30mm) || || {{USSR}} ||'''Status: In service.''' Standard automatic grenade launcher, used as fire support weapon in infantry formations.\n|-\n| [[AGS-30]] \n|[[File:Interpolitex 2011 (405-40).jpg|none|thumb]]||[[Automatic grenade launcher]] (30mm) || || {{IND}}<br>{{Flagu|Russia}} ||Replacing the AGS-17 and being manufactured at [[Ordnance Factory Tiruchirappalli]].\n|-\n| [[Carl Gustav recoilless rifle|RCL Mk II]] \n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[File:Carl Gustav recoilless rifle.jpg|none|thumb]]||[[Recoilless rifle]] (84mm) || || {{IND}}<br>{{SWE}} ||Carl Gustav Recoilless Rifle produced by OFB.\n|-\n| [[Carl Gustav recoilless rifle|RCL Mk III]